<DOCNO> APW19990819.0001 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 07:37:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Turkish Quake Death Toll Hits 6,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- The official death toll from western  
Turkey's worst recorded earthquake surpassed 6,000 today and hope 
waned for saving many of the thousands still missing under the 
mountains of rubble. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, hundreds of thousands of Turks camped out in yards,  
parks, and even on highway medians for yet another night in fear of 
going home -- or because they had no home to go back to. 
</P>
<P>
	The Anatolia news agency said that in the hard-hit Izmit and  
Golcuk areas, 3,000 people were killed, an increase of 1,000 from 
the earlier official count. The agency later reported that the 
death toll in the town of Yalova rose from 350 to 1,311. The 
increases raise the official death toll to some 6,300. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey's private Channel 6 reported that the death toll reached  
7,000, but did not say the source of its count. The discrepancy 
could be due to the large number of people still missing. The death 
toll was still expected to rise. 
</P>
<P>
	By today, some 21,000 people were reported injured.  
</P>
<P>
	``We don't trust our own homes,'' said 21-year-old Dilek Turkmen  
as she watched rescue workers sifting through the rubble of a 
collapsed apartment building on the outskirts of Istanbul. 
</P>
<P>
	More hard evidence of the destruction: an inferno at the major  
Tupras oil refinery, still raging out of control today and 
threatening severe setbacks to the area that accounts for a third 
of Turkey's economic output. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey's business newspaper, Finansal Forum, estimated the quake  
would cost Turkey's struggling economy $25 billion. Other estimates 
put the cost even higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Fresh rescue teams arrived from abroad overnight to continue  
searching for the missing. Many wore scarves over their faces as a 
barrier against the growing stench of decaying flesh. 
</P>
<P>
	An Austrian team moved from building to building in Izmit,  
searching for survivors with sniffer dogs. They found no one and 
said they feared that most of those trapped in the wreckage may 
have perished due to a lack of water. 
</P>
<P>
	People pleaded for rescuers to try to find loved ones in towers  
of rubble of what was once apartment buildings, many of them poorly 
constructed structures that served the poor who flocked to cities 
when economic progress created jobs over the last three decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Golcuk mayor Ismail Baris estimated as many as 10,000 were still  
trapped under collapsed rubble in his navy base town alone. 
</P>
<P>
	A 60-member French military rescue team worked in Yalova, 90  
miles southwest of Istanbul, trying to pull 16-year-old Elmas 
Kizilkaya from the rubble of a seven-story building. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has her ankle trapped in the concrete,'' said Capt.  
Jean-Marc Castagnet, head of the French team. ``We may have to 
amputate her foot. We will do everything not to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A team from Israel arrived in a village near Yalova, 90 miles  
southwest of Istanbul, after reports of 14 Israelis trapped in the 
rubble of a building. Police said one was pulled out alive. 
</P>
<P>
	Two women who had been trapped under the rubble of their  
five-story apartment building for 44 hours were rescued alive in 
Bolu, 160 miles east of Istanbul. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurriyet newspaper reported that seven people were saved from  
collapsed buildings after they used their cell phones to call for 
help. 
</P>
<P>
	But such rescue stories were expected to dwindle as more time  
passed, swelling the death toll. 
</P>
<P>
	A boggling array of misery emerged from the rubble: grotesquely  
contorted bodies, dead children with faces frozen in terror, 
corpses stacked in refrigerated meat wagons and at an ice-skating 
rink to slow rotting in the heat -- and a woman holding a vigil for 
a newlywed daughter expected to be among the dead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not leaving until they find her,'' proclaimed Ayse Mutlu,  
who has sat in the same chair in front of the toppled apartment in 
Izmit since Tuesday's quake. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit found himself increasingly under  
fire for his handling of the catastrophe. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rescue is a pure fiasco,'' the Radikal newspaper shouted.  
</P>
<P>
	``Helplessness'' the national Sabah newspaper blared on its  
front page. ``The people are helpless, the state is helpless, we 
can't even find a place to put our dead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Residents in Izmit, one of the hardest hit cities and site of  
the refinery fire, shouted complaints directly at Ecevit as he 
toured the city. 
</P>
<P>
	``When are they going to come and help us? When we are all  
dead?'' cried Zeyfettin Kus in front of a collapsed apartment where 
three neighbors were buried. He could no longer hear cries for 
help. 
</P>
<P>
	Dwindling food supplies on top of crippled power and water lines  
in some areas added to the mood of desperation. Crowds mobbed a 
convoy of bread trucks that entered the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, in the capital, Ankara, Ecevit announced hotlines had  
been set up from the worst-hit areas directly to his office, while 
defending the efforts so far. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rescue work is very sensitive,'' he said. ``If not done  
carefully, while saving one life you can lose 10.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Izmit, authorities tried to evacuate a three-mile zone around  
the oil refinery, about 80 miles southeast of Istanbul. 
</P>
<P>
	Chemical foam dropped by firefighting planes failed to quell the  
flames, which churned out enormous plumes of dark smoke that gave 
even sunny skies a twilight pallor. Electricity cuts kept fire 
crews from using pumps to draw water from the nearby Sea of 
Marmara. 
</P>
<P>
	The worst fear was that the blaze could engulf the entire field  
of 30 giant storage tanks, touching off an environmental disaster. 
Nearby, other serious dangers loomed: a fertilizer facility with 
8,000 tons of dangerous ammonia risked catching fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Barriers were set up to stop any oil from spilling into the sea.  
</P>
<P>
	The state-run plant provided more than a third of the retail and  
industrial grade fuel for the domestic market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0002 </DOCNO>
