<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Armstrong Cashes In on Tour Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Lance Armstrong is cashing in on his Tour  
de France victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong has signed a contract extension with his team, U.S.  
Postal Service, that will pay him $2 million in 2000, four times 
his 1999 base salary. He also has signed a string of new 
endorsement deals worth as much as $6 million through the year 
2004, the Austin American-Statesman reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Postal Service team representatives didn't immediately  
return calls from The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lance is somewhat astounded by what's happening now,'' said  
Armstrong's agent, Bill Stapleton. ``The numbers are pretty 
staggering and he's really flattered.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, 27, has pledged to donate at least $250,000 from his  
2000 salary to his Lance Armstrong Foundation for cancer research. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the endorsement deals call for Armstrong to appear in  
television commercials for financial news provider Bridge 
Information Systems, American General Financial Services and the 
Postal Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong already has been the subject of a commercial for Nike  
Inc., one of his apparel and equipment sponsors. He has made 
appearances as a motivational speaker since he was diagnosed with 
advanced testicular cancer in October 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to the Tour de France, Armstrong made $30,000 per speech.  
Stapleton said companies now are offering up to $100,000 per 
speech. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
