<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 14:20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Seeks 'New Way' on Trade Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WATERLOO, Iowa (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, seeking to ease  
tensions with labor leaders, called Thursday for ``a new way'' on 
contentious trade issues which have divided the two. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot open markets, but close the door on protections for  
America's workers,'' Gore said. ``We're going to move those exports 
out and those job numbers up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, speaking with reporters later, said he wasn't offering new  
trade proposals but was seeking to emphasize the administration's 
commitment to protect against the loss of jobs to overseas 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is time for a new way on trade,'' Gore said.  
</P>
<P>
	He chose to make his case during a state convention of the Iowa  
Federation of Labor just a day after New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley 
spoke to the same group. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been tensions between labor and the Clinton  
administration for years over trade issues, and Gore has faced 
tough questioning from some as he seeks the Democratic presidential 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Clinton and Gore have pressed for free trade agreements  
that open more markets for American products. Labor leaders argue 
those deals clear the way for shipping jobs overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore acknowledged the differences.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have supported free and fair trade,'' Gore said. ``It has  
brought me disagreements with some people I most respect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the heart of the disagreement is a question of emphasis.  
Trade bargainers have included provisions aimed at protecting 
environmental standards and labor laws in the nation's trading 
partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say those protections are inadequate, while Gore said  
he'd see to it they were enforced. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Gore said he would heighten the role of those  
standards in upcoming trade bargaining. 
</P>
<P>
	``Labor and environmental concerns need to be integrated into  
the negotiating approach to our country,'' Gore said, insisting the 
administration's policy is beginning to have an effect. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're seeing a new receptiveness in other countries,'' Gore  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore is the overwhelming early leader for the Democratic  
presidential nomination, and he clearly sought to minimize 
differences with a key Democratic constituency where he's already 
gotten some backing. 
</P>
<P>
	The state labor federation doesn't endorse candidates but the  
two-day lab meeting gave leaders a chance to look over the two 
Democratic contenders. Bradley called for a series of changes in 
labor laws while Gore sounded more general themes and focused on 
attacking Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not talking about any other candidates,'' Gore said, when  
asked to spell out his differences with Bradley. ``I'm not going to 
say anything negative about him at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech, Gore argued his labor record is better than any  
of his rivals -- a particularly notable achievement since he's from 
Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want you to know that was compiled in a southern state,''  
Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his labor ties date back to his father being the first  
labor secretary in Tennessee. He warned labor leaders that 
Democrats can't risk divisions, because split party could lose the 
White House. 
</P>
<P>
	He argued that Clinton has served as ``a back stop to stop this  
bunch from dismantling the labor law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a one-day campaign visit by Gore, who mingled with labor  
leaders and sought to shore up ties. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, he traveled to a farm south of Waterloo to  
collect the endorsements of more than 120 prominent farmers and to 
repeat his call for more federal assistance for a sagging farm 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore picked up the endorsement of Rep. Leonard Boswell of Iowa  
and state Agricultural Secretary Patty Judge as well as Iowa 
Farmers Union President John Whitaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore used the picture-perfect farm setting to launch the group  
``Farmers for Gore,'' which he said will bolster the grass roots 
activism of his campaign. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
