<DOCNO> APW19990819.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 15:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Dips to 7-Month Low vs. Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell broadly Thursday, losing ground  
to the euro and touching a seven-month low against the surging yen 
on news of a widening United States trade deficit and a burst of 
confidence in the European and Japanese economies. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0630 up from  
$1.0523 late Wednesday. The dollar also was quoted at 111.40 
Japanese yen, down from 112.03. 
</P>
<P>
	News that the half-year trade deficit had risen more than 40  
percent over last year's figure triggered a move by foreign 
exchange traders out of dollars and into other foreign currencies -- 
most notably the yen. Through the first half of this year, the U.S. 
trade deficit is running at an annual rate of $236 billion -- 44 
percent above last year's $164.3 billion record imbalance. 
</P>
<P>
	``This particular report seemed to get everyone nervous,'' said  
Don Hilber, an economist at Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. in Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	The worse-than-expected numbers and the dollar's slide renewed  
fears that the Federal Reserve will be forced to take more strident 
measures to keep inflation in check. A falling dollar makes imports 
more expensive for U.S. consumers, raising inflationary pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street has expected a one-quarter of a percentage point  
rate hike following next week's Federal Reserve policy-making 
meeting, but the latest deficit figures could force a larger 
increase. 
</P>
<P>
	In which case, ``investors will start to consider alternatives  
in overseas markets,'' Hilber said. ``And in this case it's Japan 
because there are concurrent signs that the Japanese economy is 
rebounding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Figures released last week by the Japanese government indicated  
the Japan's economy had grown faster in the first quarter than 
analysts had anticipated, which means the pace of the country's 
economic recovery may be speeding up. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're seeing the yen appreciate for all the right reasons,''  
said Kevin Lawrie, manager of foreign exchange at Mellon Bank in 
Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar dynamics are at work in Europe, where the euro has  
recovered from lows recorded in the past month. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5037 Swiss francs, down from  
1.5203, and 1.4930 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4827. The British 
pound rose to $1.6186 from $1.6015. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8403 German 
marks, down from 1.8584; 6.1708 French francs, down from 6.2336; 
and 1,821.51 Italian lire, down from 1,840.04. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
