<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals Court To Rethink Irish Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Three former Irish fugitives who were freed  
last fall after a federal appeals court overturned their 
extradition face a new hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Wednesday set a new  
hearing for Sept. 28 after the federal government asked it to 
reconsider its earlier ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The court had previously set aside a judge's extradition order  
and called for an examination of possible bias in the courts in 
British-governed Northern Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	In requesting reconsideration of the ruling, the Justice  
Department said there was an issue of whether U.S. courts can 
inquire into possible bias in another country's court system. 
</P>
<P>
	The men, Kevin Artt, Pol Brennan and Terence Kirby, remain free  
on bail. They were among 38 opponents of British rule in Northern 
Ireland who escaped from the Maze prison near Belfast in September 
1983. The three were arrested separately in California a decade 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	Artt and Kirby were both serving sentences for murder,  
convictions based on confessions that they said were beaten out of 
them. Brennan was convicted of possessing explosives that police 
said were to be used to blow up a Belfast shop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
