<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Liverpool Rocker Johnny Byrne Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIVERPOOL, England (AP) -- Johnny Byrne, a guitarist who was  
briefly teamed with Ringo Starr in a band called Rory Storm and the 
Hurricanes, has died at age 59. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrne, who used the stage name of Johnny Guitar, died Wednesday  
after collapsing at his home, the Liverpool Echo newspaper 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Rory Storm and the Hurricanes was one of Liverpool's most  
popular bands in the years before Beatlemania, but unlike a host of 
other Merseyside bands, it never had a record on the British hit 
charts. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrne and Alan Caldwell, who took the stage name of Rory Storm,  
started playing together in 1957 in a skiffle band called The 
Raving Texans, which combined elements of jazz, blues, country and 
folk. The group became the Hurricanes in 1959. 
</P>
<P>
	With Starr on drums, Rory Storm and the Hurricanes played at the  
Kaiserkeller in Hamburg, Germany, in late 1960, getting star 
billing over The Beatles. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr joined The Beatles in 1962.  
</P>
<P>
	``Even without the financial rewards of a hit record we seemed  
to have it all at the time,'' Byrne said in 1990. ``While most of 
the other bands were struggling from hand to mouth we had plenty of 
work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Hurricanes continued performing until 1967. Caldwell died in  
1972, and Byrne went to work as an ambulance driver the same year. 
</P>
<P>
	Information on survivors was not immediately available, and  
funeral arrangements were not announced. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
