<HEADLINE> Progress Seen in Nazi Survivor Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart Eizenstat  
said Thursday that negotiations with Germany on compensation for 
Nazi-era labor camp survivors are advancing. 
</P>
<P>
	Eizenstat, the chief U.S. negotiator in the talks, met with Otto  
Graf Lambsdorff, Germany's chief negotiator and former economics 
minister, to prepare for meetings on the matter beginning next 
Tuesday in Bonn, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have made considerable progress in laying the groundwork  
for these talks,'' Eizenstat said in a statement after Thursday's 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan, compensation would be paid to an estimated 1  
million survivors of slave or forced labor camps. 
  	   	
</P>
