<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Probe Ford SUV Wiper Failures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal safety agency said Thursday it is  
investigating complaints of windshield wiper failures on some late 
model sport utility vehicles made by Ford Motor Co. 
</P>
<P>
	There are nearly 1.5 million of the 1997-99 Ford Explorers and  
Mercury Mountaineers on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Highway Traffic Safety Agency, in a monthly report,  
said it was investigating 35 complaints from consumers asserting 
the windshield wipers malfunctioned in inclement weather. Either 
the wipers stopped, worked intermittently, or operated even though 
they were shut off, the consumers complained. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ford is aware of the investigation and we're cooperating fully  
with NHTSA,'' said spokesman Mike Vaughn in Dearborn, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the consumers said they crashed because of wiper  
failures. However, the report said: ``Wipers are a critical 
automotive safety system without which a vehicle operator is unable 
to adequately see the road surface and other vehicles during 
precipitation. This inability to see could result in a crash.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agency also is investigating 31 complaints that the plastic  
fuel tanks are cracking and leaking on some older model Ford 
Windstar minivans. No fires were reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The minivans are from model years 1995 through 1997. More than  
700,000 Windstars were manufactured during those years. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency also is looking at whether the rate of air bag deaths  
in Hyundai Accent cars is too high, the report said. That 
investigation was announced last month, but the report included 
more details. 
</P>
<P>
	NHTSA has identified five child deaths that may have been caused  
by deployment of front passenger air bags in minor to moderate 
crashes. About 136,000 Accents are under investigation from the 
1995 through 1997 model years. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyundai spokesman Chris Hosford, in Fountain Valley, Calif.,  
said, ``We don't feel the design of the vehicle had any affect on 
the unfortunate deaths of the individuals that NHTSA is 
investigating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said none of the five were using seat belts or child  
restraints. ``Without a seat belt, individuals are often not 
positioned to benefit from an air bag,'' Hosford said. 
</P>
<P>
	NHTSA opens any safety investigation with a preliminary inquiry  
in which the government and manufacturer exchange paperwork 
including any complaints, as in the Hyundai air bag and Ford 
windshield wiper cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation then could be upgraded to an engineering  
analysis, during which engineers study parts to see if they are 
defective, as in the Ford fuel tank case. An investigation 
eventually can lead to a recall. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency also upgraded an investigation into General Motors  
Blazer, Jimmy and Bravada four-wheel drive SUVs from the 1996 model 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	There were 79 consumer complaints about the front suspension  
collapsing. No crashes were reported. There were nearly 2,700 
warranty claims for ball joint failures on the vehicles, which can 
result in the front suspension collapsing. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
