<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Bank Giants Might Team Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- In what analysts said could be the start of a new  
series of shakeups in Japan's financial industry, three of the 
country's top banks said Thursday they are considering an alliance 
that would create the world's largest banking group. 
</P>
<P>
	Industrial Bank of Japan Ltd., Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd. and  
Fuji Bank Ltd. each confirmed they are considering a three-way 
combination. News reports said the banks are expected to formally 
announce the deal this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's financial industry has seen big changes in recent years  
since the government embarked on its ``Big Bang'' package of 
deregulation measures aimed at making Tokyo a financial center on a 
par with London and New York by opening it up to greater 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Competition has intensified and what was once unthinkable -- that  
financial institutions could fail if they don't measure up -- is 
more acceptable. 
</P>
<P>
	The banks refused to say what form their alliance might take,  
but Japan's leading business daily, the Nihon Keizai Shimbun, 
reported they had sealed a deal to create a joint holding company 
as early as the fall of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	That structure would allow the banks to put their retail  
banking, investment banking and brokerage subsidiaries under common 
management and cut costs by combining overlapping businesses, the 
paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets at the three banks exceed $1.2 trillion, which would make  
the new entity the largest banking group in the world. Their assets 
would surpass the $735.3 billion of Germany's Deutsche Bank and the 
$652 billion of Japan's largest bank, the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts welcomed the alliance as a a step toward making Japan's  
bloated banking industry more efficient. 
</P>
<P>
	``It points the banking industry in the right direction,'' said  
Koyo Ozeki, a bank analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``This is a step 
forward toward a major structural shake-up among Japan's city 
banks, and it will spur others to make similar deals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Ozeki and others warned that the success of the deal would  
depend largely on how serious the three banks are about cutting 
costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``How the banks can raise their efficiency is the key,'' said  
Setsuko Akiba, an analyst at Deutsche Securities Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance would pool the companies' respective strengths --  
investment banking for IBJ and retail banking for Fuji and DKB. 
</P>
<P>
	Securities business at the three banks will be integrated, while  
affiliate second-tier and smaller brokerages may be reorganized, 
the Nihon Keizai article said. 
</P>
<P>
	DKB and Fuji Bank already have a joint-venture trust bank.  
</P>
<P>
	News of the alliance sent the banks' stock prices shooting  
higher before trading in them was suspended shortly before the end 
of the session. 
</P>
<P>
	Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank shares finished up 11 percent at the  
equivalent of $8.12 a share, while IBJ rose 11 percent to $8.79 and 
Fuji Bank rose 12 percent to 89 cents a share. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
