<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel To Study Trade Deficits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Blue-ribbon congressional committees don't  
normally have their own songs, but the new U.S. Trade Deficit 
Review Commission would be completely justified in adopting the 
theme music from ``Mission: Impossible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 12-member panel, split evenly between members appointed by  
Democrats and Republicans, opened its public hearings today with 
the unenviable task of finding common ground on U.S. trade policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, Congress wants the commission to come up with  
answers to three questions: 
</P>
<P>
	What causes America's trade deficits?  
</P>
<P>
	What harm, if any, do they do?  
</P>
<P>
	What policy changes can be made to narrow the deficits?  
</P>
<P>
	The commission began that task with a string of expert witnesses  
describing what has caused the trade deficit to soar over the past 
two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Catherine Mann, an economist at the Institute for International  
Economics in Washington, said the deficit surge primarily reflected 
the fact that the U.S. economy, led by strong consumer demand, has 
continued to do well while the rest of the world has struggled with 
the impact of the Asian economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cyclical spending is robust, the rest of the world is growing  
slowly and this is why the ... deficit has continued to widen,'' 
she told the commission members. ``For the time being, the United 
States is an oasis of prosperity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission's first public hearings came on a day when the  
government reported that the trade deficit had surged to a monthly 
record in June. The panel of experts assembled by Congress finds 
itself in the middle of a raging debate. 
</P>
<P>
	On one side, ardent free traders argue that America's prosperous  
times with unemployment at the lowest level in three decades show 
that the trade deficits are not harmful. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side are protectionist forces, led by labor unions,  
who contend that the overall prosperity masks serious pain 
inflicted on thousands of Americans who have seen their jobs go 
overseas while countries such as Japan and China keep their markets 
closed to American goods. 
</P>
<P>
	Reconciling those two positions would appear daunting, but  
commission Chairman Murray Weidenbaum insists it can be done. 
</P>
<P>
	``We go in with a united determination that we are not going to  
issue two separate reports. That would be the easiest way out, but 
not very helpful,'' said Weidenbaum, an economist at Washington 
University who served in the Reagan administration as chairman of 
the Council of Economic Advisers. 
</P>
<P>
	The new commission plans at least four hearings in cities around  
the country over the next year before issuing its final report. It 
brings an assortment of views to its task with members ranging from 
George Becker, president of the United Steelworkers union, to Carla 
Hills, chief trade negotiator in the Bush administration. 
</P>
<P>
	While President Clinton ran for office in 1992 as a centrist new  
Democrat, he has seen his own trade agenda held hostage for more 
than two years now by members of his own party in the House who 
have refused to give him the votes he needs to negotiate new global 
trade deals. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Republicans, who traditionally back free trade because of  
its business constituency, have seen a growing divide. 
</P>
<P>
	``America's working men and women are being sacrificed to the  
global economy,'' complains Republican presidential candidate Pat 
Buchanan. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States last enjoyed a trade surplus in goods and  
services in 1975, but the deficits recently have been skyrocketing 
as the Asian economic crisis has dried up overseas markets for 
American manufacturers and farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's deficit hit an all-time high of $164.3 billion. The  
government reported today that the June deficit surged by an 
unexpectedly large 16.3 percent, setting a monthly record of $24.6 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Through the first half of this year, the trade deficit is  
running at an annual rate of $236 billion, a whopping 44 percent 
higher than last year's record. This deterioration has made 
politicians take notice even in the midst of the economy's overall 
prosperity. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress has become deeply fragmented on trade policy,'' said  
Greg Mastel, an economist at the National Policy Center, a 
Washington think tank. ``The consensus that kept trade policy 
moving in the same direction since World War II has really begun to 
erode.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
