<HEADLINE> NFL Camps Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                             *Bengals    	
</P>
<P>
	Rookie quarterback Akili Smith has missed so much of  
Cincinnati's training camp in his contract holdout that he is 
unlikely to be of much use this season, Bengals quarterback Jeff 
Blake says. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, Cincinnati's top draft choice, would be Blake's backup if  
he signs. But he is missing practice time needed to learn the 
Bengals' offense, Blake said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took me two years to learn this offense,'' said Blake, a  
Pro Bowl starter after his 1995 season with Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	``He could come in and play, but I don't think he could be  
productive,'' Blake said of Smith. ``He could get by on athletic 
ability, but that will only take you so far ... That's why they 
have training camp.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals have failed in their latest effort to sign Smith,  
the former Oregon star. 
</P>
<P>
	Management and Smith's agent, Leigh Steinberg, are at odds over  
how Smith would earn his money. The Bengals say they have offered a 
six-year deal for nearly $45 million. Under that proposal, Smith 
would average $4.7 million per year for six years if he 
participates in 55 percent of the plays and, as the contract 
progresses, has thrown for 2,500 yards in two of the three prior 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Bengals president Mike Brown said Smith's side doesn't like the  
performance requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	``They find that absurd, and we find that more absurd that they  
look at it like that,'' Brown said. ``They want us to give 
everything to their guy. We want him to earn some of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steinberg said he had sent a series of proposals to the Bengals  
in an attempt to close the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides have reportedly agreed on a $10.8 million signing  
bonus and the total money. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Broncos    	
</P>
<P>
	The two-time defending Super Bowl champion Broncos closed out  
training camp with a golf competition, as coach Mike Shanahan said 
the camp was one of the most competitive he had experienced with 
the Broncos. 
</P>
<P>
	Backup quarterback Chris Miller didn't practice and is still  
bothered by tendinitis in his right elbow that forced him out of 
last Saturday's exhibition game. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Dolphins    	
</P>
<P>
	Jimmy Johnson says he's in no hurry for Dimitrius Underwood to  
join the Dolphins. The rookie defensive end, waived by Minnesota 
after saying he preferred a religious calling to football, is 
willing to meet with Johnson but also is not rushing to get back on 
the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, the 29th overall pick in April's draft, was claimed  
Monday off waivers by the Dolphins. Johnson talked with him for the 
first time Tuesday and predicted the rookie will eventually join 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Redskins    	
</P>
<P>
	Redskins coach Norv Turner said he plans to play his starters  
well into the third quarter of Washington's exhibition matchup with 
Buffalo on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner played most of his starters for an entire half in last  
week's 20-14 victory at New England. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner said his decision is due to the need to build continuity  
after many offseason lineup changes. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Panthers    	
</P>
<P>
	The window of opportunity is narrowing on Jeff Lewis' bid to  
unseat Steve Beuerlein as the Panthers' starting quarterback for 
1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest chance yet for Lewis comes Friday night when the  
Panthers meet Pittsburgh in a home exhibition. 
</P>
<P>
	Beuerlein, 34, was one of the NFL's most accurate passers last  
season and has looked sharp again in training camp, but Lewis, 26, 
has struggled. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Titans    	
</P>
<P>
	Steve McNair will not start Friday when the Titans play an  
exhibition game at Arizona, coach Jeff Fisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	McNair has not practiced since Sunday's exhibition loss to  
Kansas City because of back spasms. He is expected back in the 
lineup Aug. 27 when Tennessee plays Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Neil O'Donnell, a 10-year veteran, will start in McNair's  
place. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Colts    	
</P>
<P>
	The Colts closed their training camp with veteran Jay  
Leeuwenberg unhappy over a demotion to a backup role on the 
offensive line. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not taking it very well at all,'' Leeuwenberg said. ``I'm  
going to do everything in my power to change the decision between 
now and the start of the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leeuwenberg has started 37 consecutive games for the Colts, the  
team's second-longest streak. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Lions    	
</P>
<P>
	With the retirement of Barry Sanders, Lions coach Bobby Ross  
said fans can expect the team to think pass first and try to 
complement it with the run. 
</P>
<P>
	In Detroit's 35-31 loss at Atlanta, quarterback Charlie Batch  
was 11-of-16 for 146 yards and a touchdown while backup Gus 
Frerotte was 15-of-21 for 171 yards and a touchdown. The Lions 
rushed for 113 yards. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Giants    	
</P>
<P>
	With backup quarterback Kerry Collins nursing a sprained foot,  
Giants' third-stringer Mike Cherry may get an unexpected chance to 
put as many points as he can on the scoreboard Saturday night when 
the Giants host Jacksonville. 
</P>
<P>
	The game plan has Kent Graham starting and playing the first  
half. Cherry is scheduled to play in the second, if Collins can't 
go. Cherry has been the Giants' No. 3 quarterback for the past two 
seasons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
