<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Utah Man Admits Bombing Fur Farm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- An animal-rights activist has admitted to  
federal charges in the 1997 bombing of a fur farm office that 
caused nearly $1 million in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton Ellerman, 22, pleaded guilty Thursday to one count of  
making a firearm and two counts of maliciously damaging property 
with an explosive in the bombing of the Fur Breeders Cooperative in 
Sandy. 
</P>
<P>
	Five pipe bombs -- some laced with nails -- exploded and a fire  
was set in the business offices in the attack. There were no 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellerman told U.S. District Judge Thomas Greene he was recruited  
to build the pipe bombs by his younger brother, Douglas Ellerman, 
20. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Ellerman pleaded guilty last year to helping plant  
the bombs. He was sentenced to seven years and two months in prison 
and ordered to pay $750,000 in restitution. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors claim a total of six suspects planted pipe bombs in  
four company trucks and its offices. All of the suspects have links 
to the Animal Liberation Front. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fur Breeders Cooperative is one of the country's largest and  
provides mink to hundreds of farmers in the West. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Ellerman faces a 30-year prison sentence, but could  
receive leniency for his cooperation in the prosecution of others 
allegedly involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentencing was set for Nov. 16. Trial for the other defendants  
is scheduled to begin Aug. 30. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
