<DOCNO> APW19990819.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 16:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> One Definition of Desperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Everybody has their own definition of desperation.  
</P>
<P>
	A decade ago, when Bill Walsh was wrapping up his tenure as  
coach of the San Francisco 49ers, it might have been calling three 
running plays in a row. Now that he's back by the Bay as vice 
president-general manager, desperate might be interpreted as 
letting Lawrence Phillips carry the ball even once. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it doesn't work out,'' Walsh said on the eve of Phillips'  
return to the NFL in Thursday night's exhibition against Seattle, 
``we'll just move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why this go-round will be different from the others,  
Phillips had a ready answer: ``I've shed 30 pounds. I'm a lot 
faster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If only it were that easy to run away from his past.  
</P>
<P>
	Phillips has a rap sheet long enough to print out and use for a  
first-down marker. He has tripped up every coach he played for, and 
ruined a few reputations in the bargain. But he remains that rare 
blend of problem and potential that persuades even smart men like 
Walsh to make risky decisions over and over. 
</P>
<P>
	The first to do so was coach Tom Osborne at Nebraska, where in  
1995, Phillips wound up being charged with trespassing and assault 
following a brutal attack on an ex-girlfriend. Osborne suspended 
Phillips in the wake of the Cornhuskers' first national 
championship, but brought him back in plenty of time to play for 
the second. 
</P>
<P>
	It cost the coach in ways he never completely grasped. Suddenly  
his reputation went from a coach who couldn't win the big one to 
coach who had to win at all costs. Osborne was only doing what he 
always did -- trying to save every kid he thought he could. But to 
all the people who started paying attention to the little duchy 
Osborne had carved out in Lincoln, Neb., it looked like he was 
interested only in saving kids who could run 40 yards in the blink 
of an eye and bench-press 500 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	A season after that, looking much older for the wear, Osborne  
walked away from coaching. ``I think it's wise to back off before 
you leave feet first,'' he said, ``or somebody tells you it's time 
to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips, who grew up in a group home in West Covina, Calif.,  
had no trouble finding another father figure to take him on. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis Rams owner Georgia Frontiere made him the sixth pick  
in the April 1996 draft and the chore eventually fell to coach Dick 
Vermeil. The bulk of Vermeil's work with Phillips would consist of 
bailing him out of jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months after the draft, Phillips was charged with driving  
under the influence. After an uneventful rookie season -- on and off 
the field -- he was charged with property damage and leaving the 
scene of an accident in St. Louis. Then he was arrested for 
disorderly conduct in Omaha. Soon after that, he spent three more 
weeks in jail because the drunken driving charge violated the terms 
of his probation on the original assault charge. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rams brought in veteran running back Craig ``Ironhead''  
Heyward to serve as a kind of big brother. Heyward had fought his 
own battles with alcohol, and he found Phillips almost as daunting. 
But just about the time Heyward thought he was making progress, 
Vermeil was making plans to ship his reclamation project out of 
town. ``He needs a fresh start,'' the coach wearily admitted. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not long in coming. Miami Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson  
welcomed Phillips with open arms two weeks later. He started out 
fumbling the ball, then fumbled away his chances of hanging onto a 
job when a woman accused him of punching her. He pleaded no contest 
and soon after, so did the Dolphins. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think when you look at the entire picture and how he fit  
here with the Dolphins,'' Johnson said without saying much, 
``that's why we released him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What followed was the feel-good portion of the story. At 23,  
Phillips got himself hired by the Barcelona Dragons of NFL Europe. 
Unbroken, he proved an effective running back one more time -- the 
first runner in the league's outpost to rush for 1,000 yards. 
Unsupervised, Phillips became like a model citizen, or so coach 
Jack Bicknell told anyone who would listen. 
</P>
<P>
	The sympathetic ear this time belonged to Walsh, whose team,  
coincidentally, had lost running back Garrison Heart. Whatever 
concerns he had going in, Walsh found that by turning the pieces 
this way and that, the puzzle seemed to fit. 
</P>
<P>
	Some people in San Francisco howled when the signing was  
announced. Some people in New York did the same when the Knicks 
signed Latrell Sprewell. They are not howling now. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had to make a calculated judgment,'' Walsh said.  
</P>
<P>
	And what it comes down to is this: Very nice men very rarely  
make good football players. If anything, the opposite tends to be 
true. If Phillips can't play, he simply gets thrown back on the 
scrap heap. But if he can -- and Walsh is as shrewd a judge of 
talent as anyone -- then all those questions about whether Phillips 
should be playing in the first place will be forgotten soon 
enough, 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> COLLEGE FOOTBALL '99: Big 12 Preview </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Texas A&AMP;M may finally give the old Southwest  
Conference braggin' rights in the Big 12. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Aggies and Texas Longhorns have won two of their  
new league's three championships, they've done it by upsetting 
Nebraska and Kansas State in one December game. From August to 
November and again in January, the former Big Eight schools have 
led the pack. 
</P>
<P>
	That could be changed this year by an A&AMP;M squad with a solid  
offense, a powerful defense and the confidence to take on any 
program in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we come up with a solid passing game,'' quarterback Randy  
McCown said, ``the sky is the limit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The No. 7 Aggies return eight players on each side of the ball  
from a team that went 11-3 and lost to only Florida State, Texas 
(on the day Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams broke Tony 
Dorsett's NCAA rushing record) and Ohio State in the Sugar Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, folks around College Station believe they can return to the  
Sugar Bowl -- only this time it would be to play for the national 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``That should be everyone's ultimate goal,'' linebacker  
Cornelius Anthony said. ``But we must take care of the little 
things first.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach R.C. Slocum's biggest challenge is replacing Lombardi  
Award-winning linebacker Dat Nguyen, the school's all-time leading 
tackler. 
</P>
<P>
	While several guys will share his duties on the field, McCown  
already has taken over as the team's leader by organizing summer 
practices and running them as Slocum would. 
</P>
<P>
	``He seems to have an air of confidence knowing he's the guy,''  
Slocum said. ``His spring practice was a notch above. He's making 
plays and looking poised.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If A&AMP;M passes major tests on Nov. 6 in Nebraska and the day  
after Thanksgiving at home against Texas, the Aggies could finish 
the season as the highest-ranked Big 12 team. The last South 
division school to do that was A&AMP;M in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The challenge for No. 17 Texas is getting quarterback Major  
Applewhite to play as well as a sophomore as he did as a freshman, 
only this time without Williams softening defenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Should Applewhite slip, second-year coach Mack Brown could turn  
to freshman Chris Simms, the son of former New York Giants star 
Phil Simms. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ricky took so much pressure off everyone else,'' said  
Applewhite, who passed for 2,453 yards and 18 touchdowns with 11 
interceptions and was named Big 12 freshman of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking of Ricky Williams, don't be surprised if he is once  
again the conference's best offensive player. Only this time, the 
award will have to be mailed to Lubbock instead of Austin. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Raiders running back with the same name as the former  
Longhorn had 1,582 yards as a sophomore last season. Although he's 
smaller than the other Williams, he's just as durable and nearly as 
difficult to tackle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I admire him for a lot of the things he did,'' the Tech star  
said of the Texas-ex. ``He helped me make a name for myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the North, the winner will be the team that best bounces from  
turmoil -- No. 6 Nebraska, No. 20 Kansas State or No. 15 Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cornhuskers went 9-4 last year, horrible by their standards.  
Nebraska hadn't had four losses since 1968, giving coach Frank 
Solich one more defeat in his first season than predecessor Tom 
Osborne had in his final five. 
</P>
<P>
	Solich believes his rookie record was a fluke, not the beginning  
of a trend. The health and success of quarterback Bobby Newcombe 
could determine that, as will a Nov. 13 home game against Kansas 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to show everyone in the country that we're still  
the same Nebraska team,'' said senior defensive back Mike Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wildcats ended a 29-year losing streak to the Cornhuskers  
last season and broke Nebraska's two-year grip on the North title. 
</P>
<P>
	Kansas State was within minutes of playing for the national  
title, but lost to A&AMP;M in double overtime of the Big 12 
championship, got frozen out of the major bowls and lost to 
unranked Purdue in the Alamo Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wildcats will be strong again, but things won't be the same  
without Michael Bishop at quarterback. He's one of eight offensive 
starters coach Bill Snyder must replace. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have faith in the youngsters we have,'' Snyder said.  
</P>
<P>
	Injuries and a running game that was 88th in the country sunk  
Colorado to 4-4 in league play last year. Then, late in the 
recruiting season, coach Rick Neuheisel bolted for Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The Buffaloes answered by luring former assistant Gary Barnett  
back from Northwestern. Hopes are high that Barnett, a master 
motivator, will fulfill the high expectations Neuheisel set but 
seldom met. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must be as good and as physical as any team in the  
conference,'' Barnett said. ``I want us to have that confidence. I 
don't think we quite see ourselves that way yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barnett is among three new coaches in the league, but the only  
one with head coaching experience. However, like Barnett, 
Oklahoma's Bob Stoops and Baylor's Kevin Steele also have strong 
Big 12 ties. 
</P>
<P>
	Stoops worked for Snyder for six years before spending the last  
three as Florida's defensive coordinator. His associate head coach 
is his younger brother Mike, Kansas State's defensive coordinator 
the last three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Steele spent six years at Nebraska under Osborne and was at  
Oklahoma State for three years in the mid-1980s. He was the 
linebackers coach with the NFL's Carolina Panthers the last four 
years; you might remember him as the coach attacked by Kevin Greene 
on the sidelines last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Although new coaches always get boosters fired up, outsiders  
also see Stoops and Steele as the right guys to end the coaching 
carousels at both schools. 
</P>
<P>
	At the other extreme are Terry Allen at Kansas and Dan McCarney  
at Iowa State, two guys whose honeymoons are over and must start 
producing. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa State has matched Baylor at 1-7 in league play three years  
running. Kansas also was 1-7 last year, although the Jayhawks were 
close to winning four more. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma State is counting on seven senior starters on offense  
and seven on defense to help rebound from a six-loss season that 
included four defeats to ranked teams. 
</P>
<P>
	At Missouri, coach Larry Smith is trying to keep alive the  
momentum of the Tigers' first consecutive winning seasons since 
1982-83. But it won't be easy without quarterback Corby Jones and 
running back Devin West. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
