<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Parole Official Admits Lie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A former parole official has admitted lying to  
investigators who are trying to determine whether the office of 
Gov. George Pataki sought the early release of a convicted armed 
robber in exchange for a campaign contribution from the inmate's 
family. 
</P>
<P>
	The admission came this week as part of a probe by the U.S.  
attorney's office into the fund-raising for Pataki. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald Hotaling told a federal magistrate on Monday that he was  
``instructed to communicate the interest of the governor's office'' 
in the release of inmate John Kim. He said he relayed the message 
to the lead parole commissioner on the case, Sean McSherry, and 
another commissioner, and Kim was paroled. Prosecutors say Kim's 
family and friends gave thousands of dollars to Pataki's campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Hotaling pleaded guilty to obstruction of justice.  
</P>
<P>
	He said the instructions came from the ``head of the agency,''  
but he did not name that person. The Division of Parole is chaired 
by Pataki appointee Brion Travis. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, it is not an everyday occurrence that the  
governor's office takes an interest in a case,'' said Hotaling, a 
27-year veteran of the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had withheld information from investigators because,  
``I was scared to death about what they were saying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Grant, a Board of Parole spokesman, denied any wrongdoing.  
</P>
<P>
	Hotaling, 52, is the second person to be convicted in an ongoing  
grand jury investigation of possible influence peddling in parole 
cases. Earlier this month, a jury found McSherry guilty of lying to 
the grand jury to protect himself and the Pataki administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ultimately, the truth will come out that the individuals  
involved in this case and this administration handled themselves 
with complete propriety,'' Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said 
after Hotaling's plea. 
</P>
<P>
	Hotaling faces a maximum of four months in jail under federal  
sentencing guidelines; no sentencing date was set. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mixed Reviews on NFL Instant Replay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	After attending a three-day NFL seminar, Fox's Bill Maas was  
convinced the league's new instant replay system would be 
successful. After watching his first game, however, he's not so 
sure. 
</P>
<P>
	Maas worked the Tennessee-Kansas City preseason game Sunday as a  
TV analyst for a local Kansas City station. The first replay 
opportunity came in the second quarter when Titans coach Jeff 
Fisher appealed an incomplete pass. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem? The computerized system didn't work, and the replay  
crew had to go to a backup videotape system. The process took about 
four minutes to resolve. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm in favor of instant replay of some sort, but I'm also a  
believer, after viewing it, there are going to be some hang-ups,'' 
Maas said. ``It's all going to depend on the feeds coming from the 
network trucks. When it comes down to a critical moment, the 
networks are going to be accountable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instant replay's other problem came during ABC's Hall of Fame  
Game, when officials didn't realize they were able to review a play 
during a commercial. Once they figured it out, the process took 
less than a minute. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a system without flaws, but it's about as close to  
perfect as you're going to get in this situation,'' said ABC's 
Boomer Esiason. 
</P>
<P>
	That's two mistakes in 18 exhibition games so far. Not a bad  
start. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 19 times play has been halted for replay this preseason,  
just one has been reversed. Thirteen have been coaches' challenges 
and the remaining six came during the final two minutes of the half 
and the game, when replay officials upstairs decide whether to 
review a play. 
</P>
<P>
	The sole reversal came when Pittsburgh coach Bill Cowher argued  
that one of his players, Hines Ward, was in possession of the ball 
before it went out of bounds after a blocked punt. The original 
call of a safety was correctly reversed to a touchdown by the 
replay crew. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been people quick to jump on us for the incident in  
Kansas City, but the preseason is about working out the kinks, and 
we'd rather have problems now than in the regular season,'' said 
Dennis Lewin, head of broadcasting for the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STARTING YOUNG:* When Josh Lewin was 13, he'd cram a card  
table, tape recorder and all of his statistics into a briefcase and 
head for the ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewin would search for the best available seats at the Rochester  
Red Wings Triple-A baseball game, spread everything out and begin 
broadcasting the game. With no audience. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewin, who recently turned 30, now sits next to the likes of Tim  
McCarver and Frank Robinson as a national play-by-play broadcaster 
for Fox's baseball coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew from the time I was five that this is what I wanted to  
do,'' Lewin said. ``I'd turn down the voice on the television and 
grab a spoon, a ladle or whatever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lewin's road was well-traveled, however.  
</P>
<P>
	He persuaded a CBA team that had just begun in Rochester to let  
him broadcast a game a week over local cable access television. 
Lewin was still 13. 
</P>
<P>
	That turned into an internship with the Red Wings, which led to  
a series of three-inning-a-game radio stints during college. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Lewin headed to Baltimore's WBAL radio station for a sports  
director position and backup to Jon Miller. He called about 10 
games when Miller was working for ESPN before he got a call from 
Fox, which was looking for young play-by-play guys. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewin left his full-time job in Baltimore for WGN in Chicago,  
where he was to be Harry Caray's fill-in. Lewin was told he'd do 
road games and the middle three innings at Wrigley Field. 
</P>
<P>
	But he never even got to do one inning at Wrigley for WGN.  
</P>
<P>
	``Harry absolutely didn't want any young go-getter filling in  
unless it was (his grandson) Chip,'' Lewin said. ``I understood 
what his problem was. He didn't want me there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So Lewin left prior to the 1998 season to broadcast Detroit  
Tigers games for Fox Sports Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I overshot the mark,'' Lewin said. ``I never  
aspired to be a network TV guy. They've got a lot more talented 
guys in the stable here than me -- Joe Buck, Kenny Albert and Thom 
Brennaman. I'm just happy to be in the mix.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TUBE BITS:* The ``Monday Night Football'' halftime show airs  
live from the ESPN Zone in New York. It begins Sept. 20, the second 
week of ``MNF,'' because halftime the first week is dedicated to 
the retiring of John Elway's jersey. ... ESPN ``SportsCenter'' 
anchor Dan Patrick's radio show debuts Sept. 13 from 1-4 p.m. EDT. 
... ABC Radio and The Fabulous Sports Babe have agreed to end their 
relationship. ... NBC golf analyst Johnny Miller caddied for his 
son, Todd, during the first two rounds of the U.S. Amateur this 
week. ... ESPN's 21st season of college football features 92 games 
and begins Aug. 28 with Louisiana Tech at No. 1 Florida State. ... 
ABC airs the Arena Football League championship game Saturday at 3 
p.m. EDT. ... ESPN's Kenny Mayne and his wife, Laura, had a baby 
girl, Riley Hope Mayne, on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
