<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 23:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elliott Says He's Fine After Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Sean Elliott is unsure whether he'll return  
to the NBA now that he's had a kidney transplant. At the moment, 
he's simply concentrating on walking around a little. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott, appearing for the first time in public since receiving  
a kidney from his brother on Monday, met with reporters in the 
lobby of Methodist Specialty and Transplant Hospital on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I'm doing great. I'm a little tired. But other  
than that, I'm just excited,'' he said, sitting in a wheelchair. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott, a 10-year NBA veteran at age 31, helped lead the San  
Antonio Spurs to their first NBA championship in June. His standout 
moment came when he hit a game-winning 3-pointer against Portland 
in the Western Conference finals. Elliott made the shot in the 
final seconds while balancing on his tiptoes as he nearly fell out 
of bounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The excitement of making that shot now has been overshadowed by  
the seriousness of undergoing a kidney transplant, Elliott said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was something else,'' he said. ``I was a little nervous  
when I got out (of surgery). But they started telling me how good I 
was doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott needed the transplant because of a condition he has had  
for several years called focal segmental glomerular sclerosis. The 
illness prevents the kidneys from properly filtering waste from the 
blood. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott's 32-year-old brother, Noel Elliott, underwent surgery  
to donate one of his healthy kidneys. Doctors immediately implanted 
the kidney in Sean Elliott's body. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been hard to move. My brother gave me a giant kidney, so  
I've got this extra lump in here and it's a little different,'' 
Elliott said. ``But it's working really good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Without the transplant, Elliott likely would have had to begin  
kidney dialysis in a matter of weeks. He said there is no way he 
can repay his brother for donating the kidney, which Elliott called 
``the greatest gift.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've just got to be the best brother I can and take care of  
what he's given to me,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott urged others to follow his brother's example and become  
organ donors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just so proud of him,'' Elliott said. ``To be able to give  
a part of your body like that is just an amazing sacrifice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Francis Wright, Elliott's transplant surgeon, said both  
brothers are recuperating nicely. 
</P>
<P>
	``We couldn't wish them any better,'' Wright said.  
</P>
<P>
	Elliott has indicated he would like to return to the Spurs. On  
Thursday, he said he hadn't thought much yet about an NBA comeback, 
although he didn't rule it out. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I feel as good and keep progressing as I have been, I'm  
sure I'm going to want to have a go at it. But we'll have to wait 
and see,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If he doesn't return to basketball, Elliott said, he doesn't  
know what he'll do. But he doesn't intend to remain idle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want to enjoy life, that's for sure,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Elliott said he might spend some of his recovery time in Tucson,  
Ariz., his hometown where several relatives live. But because his 
doctors are in San Antonio, much of his recuperation period will be 
spent in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	He thanked well-wishers from around the world.  
</P>
<P>
	Several NBA players have called, visited or sent flowers. Karl  
Malone, Scottie Pippen, Detlef Schrempf and former Spurs player 
Vinny Del Negro have been among those offering support, Elliott 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	David Robinson, Avery Johnson and Steve Kerr of the Spurs have  
visited the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dave came by, Avery came by. Avery was scared to death. I  
think I scared him,'' Elliott said with a chuckle. ``I had all 
these tubes and stuff coming out of me, so I don't think he was 
used to that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
