<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Settlement for Tobacco Growers OKed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH (AP) -- A judge approved a court settlement with  
cigarette companies Thursday that could give the nation's tobacco 
farmers and quota owners more than $5 billion over the next 12 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The so-called Phase II settlement is intended to help farmers  
and allotment holders -- people granted the right by the federal 
government to grow a certain amount of tobacco -- in 14 
tobacco-producing states deal with the fallout from a $206 billion 
national settlement between the cigarette companies and the states. 
</P>
<P>
	``The price of the product is going to rise. The consumption of  
this product is going to go down,'' said Phil Carlton, who 
represented the cigarette companies in negotiating the settlement. 
``That's simple economics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina farmers and quota owners could receive about $2  
billion, the largest portion of the settlement among the states. 
The national settlement, which should begin sending payments to 
growers by the end of the year, will be overseen by North Carolina 
state courts under an agreement by all 14 tobacco states. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no way to help every single person who is going to be  
affected by this,'' Carlton said. ``But one group the companies 
wanted to be sure to help were the tobacco farmers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carlton said the settlement between the companies and  
tobacco-producing states would help farmers offset future losses, 
but would not help with the 35 percent reduction over the past two 
years in the amount of tobacco they can grow. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Judge Donald Stephens signed the legal documents  
Thursday morning finalizing the delivery of the payments to the 
states. 
</P>
<P>
	The checks will be good news for farmers, many of whom never  
believed they would get any money from the settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of them still don't believe it's going to happen,'' said  
tobacco farmer Ed Bissette of Spring Hope, who is on a state board 
that will oversee the distribution of the money. ``I can't get out 
of the warehouse. They just smother me when I go in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement for farmers and allotment holders in the states  
could total $5.1 billion over 12 years, Attorney General Mike 
Easley said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a joint statement, Philip Morris, R.J. Reynolds, Brown &AMP;  
Williamson and Lorillard tobacco companies said they hoped the 
settlement would help farmers adjust. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is our strong desire that affected tobacco farmers be well  
prepared for the changes in the marketplace that lie ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other states expected to receive Phase II settlement money are  
Kentucky, Tennessee, South Carolina, Virginia, Georgia, Ohio, 
Indiana, Florida, Missouri, West Virginia, Alabama, Maryland and 
Pennsylvania. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
