<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida Ag Did Well Last Year / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Florida growers and ranchers saw their cash  
receipts rise in 1998 to their largest ever due to solid gains in 
citrus and vegetables, the U.S. Department of Agriculture said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cash receipts for Florida agriculture rose 3.8 percent to a  
record $6.69 billion as citrus and vegetables offset weakness in 
Florida's livestock and foliage industries. The previous record was 
$6.24 billion in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida farm receipts had declined during the mid-1990s because  
of storms, droughts and the result of the North American Free Trade 
Agreement, state agriculture officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm delighted that our farmers are continuing to increase  
their sales despite our many trade issues and adverse weather 
conditions threatening their survival,'' Florida Agriculture 
Commissioner Bob Crawford said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Citrus led the way with $1.61 billion in revenue, up 7.8 percent  
for the year. Citrus accounted for 23.8 percent of all farm cash 
receipts in the state last year. Oranges alone accounted for $1.2 
billion, or about 20 percent of all farm cash receipts, and offset 
the 27 percent decline in grapefruit to $145 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Vegetables and melons, boosted by tomatoes, potatoes and squash,  
generated $1.54 billion, or 22.9 percent of Florida's farm revenue 
-- up 5.3 percent for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Cash receipts are the key measure of farm income for Florida,  
the nation's ninth-largest agricultural state. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOTTINEAU, N.D. (AP) -- As area farmers head into harvest, a  
coalition is preparing to help them find financial and mental 
health services. 
</P>
<P>
	The Team for Interfaith Rural Support was formed to serve  
Bottineau, McHenry, Renville and Rolette counties. 
</P>
<P>
	``People really want to be working together because they know  
they have to,'' said Desiree Uhrich of Bottineau, who works with 
the Lutheran Rural Response unit of Lutheran Social Services. 
</P>
<P>
	The coalition includes representatives of agriculture mediation,  
churches and social service, health care and emergency relief 
agencies as well as community leaders. By forming the coalition, 
Uhrich said, the different groups have learned what others have to 
offer and are able to make referrals. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharon Parsley, a social worker with Catholic Family Services in  
Minot, said the team expects the brunt of the disaster will be felt 
this fall, when farmers normally collect an income from their 
crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbor-to-neighbor support is needed as well as agency help,  
said Kenneth Rogers of Maxbass, a mediator with the state 
agriculture mediation program. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have television and newspapers and computers and cell  
phones -- all these modern communication devices -- but we 
communicate less people-to-people, farmer-to-farmer, than we ever 
have,'' he said. ``Somehow, we need to break that isolation down a 
little bit.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
