<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Under Fire For WWF Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- A watchdog group and an environmentalist  
both took on Gov. Jesse Ventura, saying he will violate conflict of 
interest laws by refereeing a wrestling event this weekend. Ventura 
took the first round today when a judge threw one complaint out. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Wrestling Federation match is scheduled for Sunday at  
the Target Center. 
</P>
<P>
	In a complaint filed Wednesday with a state agency, Common Cause  
Minnesota President David Schultz said the governor -- a former 
professional wrestler -- has used his ``official position to secure 
benefits for himself which are distinct from benefits available to 
the general public.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state Department of Employee Relations didn't immediately  
issue any response, but a second, similar complaint from Leslie 
Davis, president of the environmental group Earth Protector, was 
heard in court today. 
</P>
<P>
	``Seventeen years of work that we've done is being dismantled  
because of a governor who is not doing his work,'' Davis told 
Ramsey County District Judge Kathleen Gearin. 
</P>
<P>
	But Ventura's attorney, Alan Eidsness, said Davis wouldn't be  
harmed by Ventura's participation in the event. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge sided with Ventura, saying ultimately it is the role  
of the voters to judge their elected officials. She also said an 
elected official does not automatically ``become someone who does 
not have personal, social, economic and private interests.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Ventura's spokesman John Wodele called the criticism  
``irritating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The governor obviously is not one out of the conventional  
mold,'' Wodele said. ``Common Cause, other politicians and elected 
officials obviously have some trouble with that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The colorful Ventura, who won election last year under the  
Reform Party banner, has said he will donate to charity the 
$100,000 fee he is getting from the WWF. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
