<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Bush Slips Slightly in N.H. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful George W.  
Bush retained a big lead among New Hampshire voters, according to a 
new poll, but that lead has slipped slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona Sen. John McCain has an edge for the second spot in New  
Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Hampshire survey of 450 registered Republicans by the  
independent American Research Group indicates 40 percent would vote 
for the Texas governor -- a drop from the 47 percent he had a month 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll showed McCain at 16 percent, compared with 13 percent  
in the same poll in July. Pat Buchanan, Elizabeth Dole, Dan Quayle, 
Alan Keyes, Steve Forbes, Gary Bauer and Orrin Hatch were all in 
single digits. Fifteen percent said they were undecided. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush was at 61 percent in a national CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll  
of 434 respondents who are Republican or who lean toward 
Republicans. Dole was in second place at 13 percent and the other 
candidates were grouped in single digits. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush had close to the same lead he had in a June CNN/USA  
Today/Gallup poll. This poll was taken from Monday through 
Wednesday, before the latest controversy over Bush's refusal to 
talk about whether he ever used illegal drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Both surveys had a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage  
points. 
</P>
<P>
	The polls are the first measure of voter sentiment in New  
Hampshire since the Iowa straw poll. In the straw poll -- an 
unscientific popularity contest held by the Iowa Republican Party -- 
Bush won, followed by Forbes, Dole and Bauer. McCain did not 
participate. 
</P>
<P>
	Dick Bennett, president of the American Research Group, noted  
that none of the top finishers in the straw poll got a bounce in 
their New Hampshire poll numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa leads off the selection process with its caucuses in early  
February, followed by New Hampshire, which holds the nation's first 
presidential primary. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Democratic side, Vice President Al Gore has maintained  
his lead among New Hampshire voters over former New Jersey Sen. 
Bill Bradley, the survey said. In July, Gore held a 48-32 lead in 
New Hampshire; this month, he had 46 percent to 29 percent for 
Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-five percent of the 415 Democrats polled said they were  
undecided. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore led Bradley 58 percent to 31 percent in the national poll  
of 493 respondents who were Democratic or lean Democratic, while 10 
percent were undecided. Gore's national lead is largely unchanged 
from June. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Hampshire telephone poll was conducted Sunday through  
Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
