<HEADLINE> Alaska Has Online Shopping Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KENAI, Alaska (AP) -- Kenai Mayor John Williams said he is  
opposed to a state sales tax because it could boost online 
shopping. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican State Sen. John Torgerson has said he would bring up  
the idea of a state sales tax with lawmakers this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	But Williams told the Kenai Chamber of Commerce Wednesday he is  
worried that the Internet already is taking a bite out of Kenai's 
economy, and any state sales tax would make cyber commerce more 
inviting. 
</P>
<P>
	It is difficult to impose a tax on goods sold over the Internet  
and that makes many goods less expensive online, even after paying 
for shipping, Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor said some businesses in the area already were feeling  
the brunt of online retailing. 
</P>
<P>
	In the auto industry, for example, huge dealerships in the Lower  
48 list their prices online. Williams said it can be cheaper to fly 
down to these dealers and buy a car there than to buy a car on the 
Kenai Peninsula. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
