<HEADLINE> Clinton Vacates for 53rd Birthday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, among the nation's oldest  
baby-boomers, is celebrating his 53rd birthday today by going on 
vacation. The White House was tightlipped about Clinton's birthday 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes it's a surprise, so maybe we should leave it at  
that,'' White House spokesman Jake Siewert said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's a safe bet that Clinton will celebrate his birthday  
during his stay on Martha's Vineyard in Massachusetts. His friend 
Vernon Jordan threw parties for him each of the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and his family are dividing their vacation this year  
between two places: Martha's Vineyard, a family favorite, and New 
York state, a nod to Hillary Rodham Clinton's senatorial 
aspirations. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the fifth Martha's Vineyard vacation for the Clintons.  
They will spend nine days on the 20-acre Oyster Pond estate of 
developer Richard Friedman, their host for the past three years. 
</P>
<P>
	They are expected to be far more visible this year than last,  
when they remained indoors because Clinton's admission that he had 
an affair with Monica Lewinsky was still fresh. 
</P>
<P>
	Now though, with the Lewinsky matter ended and Mrs. Clinton's  
bid for a Senate seat from New York all but official, the president 
and first lady are making lots of plans. Already, they have 
penciled in a jaunt to Nantucket on Friday for an event with the 
American-Ireland Fund, a non-profit group that finances educational 
ventures in Northern Ireland and Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund has agreed to finance projects for Vital Voices, an  
effort to foster understanding between Protestants and Catholics 
that Mrs. Clinton has been involved with in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 28, the Clintons leave the Vineyard to go to East  
Hampton, N.Y., where they will take part in a Democratic National 
Committee weekend retreat and other events to help raise money for 
Democratic candidates. On the 30th, they go to Skaneateles in 
upstate New York, returning to Washington at the start of the Labor 
Day weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Siewert acknowledged there were plans for the Clintons to make  
appearances during their stay in New York state, but ``on balance, 
the vacation will be a vacation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Skaneateles, a quiet resort town of 7,500 people on Skaneateles  
Lake just southwest of Syracuse, once was a stop on the Civil 
War-era Underground Railroad that ferried slaves north to freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons will stay at the lakeside home of real estate  
developer Thomas McDonald. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
