<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Says Soil Conservation Works </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An intense study of a Wisconsin watershed is  
providing good news for farmers: Soil conservation efforts work. 
</P>
<P>
	UCLA geography professor Stanley W. Trimble found that erosion  
has declined sharply in the Coon Creek Basin in western Wisconsin. 
His findings appear in Friday's edition of the journal Science. 
</P>
<P>
	While his work focused on one area, Trimble said in a telephone  
interview that the same ``processes are representative of many 
agriculturally disturbed basins in the Eastern U.S., but magnitudes 
and timing would differ. Erosion is certainly a less serious 
problem than it was in the 1930s.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Moffitt of the Agriculture Department's Natural Resources  
Conservation Service said that while Trimble's study ``certainly 
points to the benefits of conservation,'' the Coon Creek watershed 
is unique in that it became a demonstration area for conservation 
efforts starting in the 1940s. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency's National Resources Inventory has indicated a  
general decline in soil erosion in recent years, Moffitt said. 
</P>
<P>
	Trimble studied sediment washed off the land in the basin and  
found an average of 405,000 metric tons per year between 1853 and 
1938, peaking in the 1930s. That declined to 209,000 metric tons 
per year from 1938 to 1975, and since 1975 has averaged about 
80,000 metric tons per year. A metric ton is 2,205 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sediment is the other end of erosion,'' he explained. ``the  
amount of sediment should equal the amount of erosion that has 
occurred.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
