<HEADLINE> Castro Describes Signing Baseballs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Joking with an audience of students Thursday,  
Cuban President Fidel Castro described the minor annoyances of his 
life: cell phones, flash bulbs and signing baseballs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know why in the United States they really think that I  
am involved in baseball,'' he said to a burst of laughter from 
about 2,000 people at a congress of leftist youth groups at 
Havana's National Theater. 
</P>
<P>
	Castro, a noted baseball fan who was a promising pitcher as a  
university student, said U.S. visitors continually bring him books 
on baseball ``and a mountain of baseballs to sign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that is hardest for me is signing baseballs,'' he  
said, comparing the task to trying to write on a drinking glass. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cuban leader, dressed in his usual olive-green fatigues,  
also grumbled that the sound of cellular telephones ``is 
unbearable'' and added: ``Some believe they are very important 
because they carry one of those little telephones.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had been photographed with flashes so often that ``it  
is a miracle I am not blind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Castro also referred to his nocturnal lifestyle, saying he often  
worked and read until near dawn. The students learned this first 
hand. Castro began to speak Wednesday shortly before 9 p.m. -- but 
didn't finish until after 1 a.m. Thursday 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday I finished working at about 6 or 7 (in the  
morning).... I got up at 8:20,'' he said, apologizing for not 
having read all of the conference's resolutions condemning 
free-market political systems and ``U.S. imperialism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 73-year-old president, who had been in power since 1959,  
also referred to his place in history. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am of this century which is ending,'' he said, saying that  
the students in the audience would face the problems of the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
