<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Univision Reports Record Ad Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Univision, the nation's dominant  
Spanish-language television network, said that advance advertising 
sales for the new TV season have reached a record $425 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The 42 percent increase for the 1999-2000 season includes  
advertisers new to Univision and reflects the growing interest by 
companies in reaching the Hispanic market. 
</P>
<P>
	Henry Cisneros, president of parent company Univision  
Communications Inc., issued a statement crediting the advertising 
community for recognizing that targeting Hispanics through TV makes 
``both cultural and financial sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Univision showed its strongest revenue growth in key airline,  
movie and entertainment, automotive, retail and telecommunications 
industries. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong economy helped boost ad sales for English-language  
networks by 13 percent during the ``upfront'' market, the period 
beginning in late May when TV networks sell about 80 percent of 
their commercial spots for the coming fall season. 
</P>
<P>
	Univision is the country's fifth-largest TV network with about 4  
million primetime viewers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 07:30:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Control Board Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The control board created to put the District  
of Columbia's chaotic financial house in order has it's own 
problems managing money, congressional auditors say. 
</P>
<P>
	A report by the General Accounting Office criticized the  
presidentially appointed D.C. Financial Responsibility and 
Management Assistance Authority for the way it awarded and 
administered contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was terrible,'' Bernard Ungar, who conducted the GAO  
investigation, said Wednesday of the control board's 
record-keeping. ``We saw no evidence of how the control board 
monitored or certified satisfactory contract performance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In assessing nine contracts awarded by the financial control  
board, the GAO found the panel did not always comply with its own 
procurement regulations and procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	It sought competition for seven of the nine contracts but failed  
to document how three of the contractors were selected, as is 
required. The panel also did not provide written justification for 
two sole source contract awards, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the control board, including Chairwoman Alice Rivlin  
and Executive Director Francis Smith, declined to comment 
Wednesday. But in an appendix to the report, they stated that the 
contracts mentioned in the report were ``highly selective rather 
than a random sample.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The control board, established by Congress in 1995, is to go out  
of existence once the city has balanced four consecutive budgets. 
So far, it has balanced three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 09:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cable Nielsen Ratings / Cable Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
