<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AHP Stock Surges on Merger Rumors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- American Home Products Corp.'s stock jumped more  
than 6 percent Wednesday amid rumors the drug maker may merge with 
British pharmaceutical firm Glaxo Wellcome PLC. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies refused to comment on the rumors and analysts  
largely discounted the prospects for Glaxo to buy American Home, 
which makes the world's most prescribed drug, the estrogen therapy 
Premarin. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of American Home rose $2.62 1/2 to $44.50 on the New York  
Stock Exchange. Glaxo's American depositary receipts rose 37 1/2 cents 
to $52, also on the Big Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Glaxo, which sells leading asthma and AIDS medications, is the  
world's second largest pharmaceutical firm behind Merck &AMP; Co. But 
Glaxo has seen profit growth slow this year amid weak sales of its 
top migraine drug, Imitrex. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything is possible,'' said Anthony Butler, an analyst with  
Lehman Brothers. '' But this one doesn't make sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glaxo is unlikely to want American Home because of agricultural  
and consumer products businesses, Butler said. American Home makes 
most of its money from Premarin, but consumers know the company for 
making Robitussin cough syrup, Advil pain reliever and Chap Stick 
lip balm. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home has had weak earnings in recent quarters compared  
to top rivals including Merck and Pfizer Inc. The Madison 
N.J.-based company's problems stem from weak sales in its 
agricultural business, and thousands of lawsuits related to its 
Norplant contraception and diet pills. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home had plans last year to merge with life sciences  
company Monsanto Co., but it was called off in October when the 
companies' top managers could not get along. American Home has also 
had talks with British drug maker SmithKline Beecham PLC. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
