<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mom Acquitted of Shooting Daughter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- An elderly woman has been acquitted of  
attempted murder in a shooting that paralyzed her daughter and 
eventually led the younger woman to request to be taken off life 
support. 
</P>
<P>
	Shirley Egan, 68, squeezed her attorney's hand and smiled  
Wednesday night after a jury decided she didn't try to kill her 
daughter or her daughter's live-in boyfriend in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan said she knew her daughter, Georgette Smith, 42, didn't  
want her to go to prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's up there with God, I pray to her in God's hands,'' Ms.  
Egan said. ``She was my best friend. We were together our whole 
lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Smith was paralyzed from the neck down, left barely able to  
speak and incapable of swallowing or controlling her bladder. In 
May, she won the right to be taken off life support, saying she did 
not blame her mother. 
</P>
<P>
	The day before she died, Ms. Smith gave a 20-minute videotaped  
deposition in which she said her mother didn't mean to shoot her 
when she opened fire. Jurors were riveted as they watched the tape 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure it was an accident. I know it was. She can't see that  
good,'' Ms. Smith said, struggling to pronounce each word from her 
hospital bed. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Ms. Egan, who is blind in one eye, weighs 85  
pounds and suffers from emphysema, opened fire March 8 after 
overhearing Ms. Smith and her boyfriend, Larry Videlock, talk about 
putting her in a nursing home. 
</P>
<P>
	After the verdict, Ms. Egan said she was tired of the influence  
Videlock was having over her daughter. ``I think I was losing it,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Her lawyer, Bob Wesley, told the jury that Ms. Egan was  
involuntarily intoxicated from prescription drugs and didn't intend 
to shoot the couple, only scare them. 
</P>
<P>
	``She is not to be blamed,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors disagreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's no accident when you pull this firearm and you aim it at  
two victims and you use your finger to pull this back,'' prosecutor 
Pam Smith told jurors in closing arguments, holding up the gun. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan was charged with two counts of attempted murder, which  
carries a maximum sentence of life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	After Ms. Smith died, prosecutors considered charging Ms. Egan  
with murder, but decided against it, citing her poor health and 
closeness with her daughter. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
