<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 22:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lutherans OK Pact With Episcopals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- After years of debate, the nation's largest  
Lutheran organization has agreed to form an alliance with the 
Episcopal Church under which they will exchange clergy, recognize 
each other's sacraments and cooperate in missionary projects. 
</P>
<P>
	The Evangelical Lutheran Church in America approved the pact  
Thursday at its national convention. The Episcopalians are expected 
to approve the pact during a convention next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The two churches have a combined 7.5 million members in 18,000  
congregations, and supporters said the ``full communion'' agreement 
will help in urban and rural areas where church resources are 
scarce. 
</P>
<P>
	The pact, which needed the approval of two-thirds of the  
delegates at a Lutheran convention here, passed 716-317, or with 69 
percent of the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents objected to the agreement's requirement that Lutherans  
follow an ordination practice known as the historic episcopate, in 
which a bishop is installed by a laying-on of hands by three 
predecessor bishops from a line believed to extend back to Christ's 
apostles. 
</P>
<P>
	Lutheran teachings don't require such historic succession, and  
many of the world's Lutheran bodies do not practice it. This is the 
first time that any U.S. Protestant body has approved such a 
relationship with an American denomination that follows the 
historic episcopate. Catholic and Orthodox churches also follow the 
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the pact said the Episcopal Church should be  
willing to take Lutherans as they are. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, the Episcopal Church overwhelmingly approved a  
similar alliance, but it fell just short of passage by the 
Lutherans. The pact has been slightly reworked since then. 
</P>
<P>
	``I pray that our response can be positive,'' said Episcopal  
Presiding Bishop Frank T. Griswold. ``The promise of our deepening 
life together offers real hope for the broken world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lutherans have previously approved similar pacts with the  
Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.), Reformed Church in America and United 
Church of Christ. But those didn't require changes in Lutheran 
tradition regarding bishops. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
