<DOCNO> APW19990819.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 07:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Track Coach Sues Under Title IX </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Vanderbilt women's track and cross  
country coach Paul Arceneaux has filed a lawsuit claiming the 
school does not properly fund the program and does not pay him as 
much as coaches of male athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court, claims Vanderbilt  
discriminated against Arceneaux ``on the basis of the 
student-athletes he coaches, in violation of Title IX,'' which 
guarantees equality in men's and women's athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanderbilt officials declined to comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Arceneaux has been at Vanderbilt since 1993 and coaches the  
men's and women's cross country teams, and the women's indoor and 
outdoor track teams. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the lawsuit, filed Friday, Arceneaux requested  
additional financial support for the women's track team and was 
denied. As a result, those athletes have suffered and continue to 
suffer, the lawsuit claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanderbilt has ``consistently and systematically failed to  
provide the program with adequate resources to be competitive and 
has instead diverted financial support from the women's programs to 
comparable men's programs,'' according to the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Arceneaux said his salary, which was not disclosed, is ``well  
below the fair market value of that of other women's coaches of 
comparable programs at other schools'' and below that of Vanderbilt 
coaches responsible for male athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit seeks an increase in salary and compensatory and  
punitive damages to be determined at trial. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 20:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Officials Acquitted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A Seoul court on Friday absolved two  
former top economic officials of charges they neglected their 
duties during a regional financial crisis that forced South Korea 
to seek help from the International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	A three-judge panel cleared former Finance Minister Kang  
Kyong-shik and former chief presidential secretary Kim In-ho of 
charges that they failed to keep then-President Kim Young-sam 
properly informed about the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Seoul District Criminal Court found them guilty of  
separate charges that they pressured state-controlled banks to 
extend millions of dollars in preferential loans to three 
financially shaky companies. They were given suspended sentences. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said they would appeal to a higher court. They had  
earlier sought four years in prison for Kang and three years for 
Kim. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials were fired two days before South Korea was forced  
to accept a $58 billion bailout from the IMF in late 1997. 
Thousands of companies collapsed, stripping millions of people of 
their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The government of reformist President Kim Dae-jung, who was  
inaugurated in February 1998, accused the two former officials of 
mishandling the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	But the officials called themselves scapegoats for political  
persecution, saying the crisis was caused by the economy's 
structural problem and a policy failure cannot be subject to 
criminal punishment. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korea's family-controlled conglomerates, known as chaebol,  
have thrived on cozy relations with past military-backed 
governments, over-expanding and over-diversifying during the 
country's boom years, sowing the seeds for the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, debt-ridden Daewoo group, the second largest  
conglomerate, bowed to pressure from its creditors and agreed to 
sell most of its 40 subsidiaries and keep only its core businesses 
in return for billions of dollars of fresh loans to save it from a 
possible bankruptcy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
