<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coast Guard Searches for Sailors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After searching up and down the East Coast and  
phoning marinas from New York to the Canadian border, the Coast 
Guard on Thursday appealed for the public's help in locating a 
sailing family. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have basically vanished,'' said Cmdr. Jim McPherson,  
spokesman for Coast Guard headquarters in Washington. ``We have no 
reports of finding life jackets or life rings or (signals from) 
emergency beacons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richard and Debbie Stewart and their children Chad, 16, and  
Mischa, 12, of Ludlow Falls, Ohio, had been sailing from Florida to 
the Midwest. They last spoke to relatives around July 25 from 
Newport, R.I., McPherson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The family's credit cards were last used July 26 in Newport. The  
last time a call was attempted on their cellular phone was Aug. 3 
near Piscataway, N.J., about 20 miles inland from the entrance to 
the Hudson River. 
</P>
<P>
	In the more than two weeks since, there has been no contact with  
the Stewarts. The Coast Guard has been unable to locate them 
despite an aerial search along the East Coast and calls to marinas 
along the New England coast, the Hudson River Valley and the St. 
Lawrence Seaway, which parallels the U.S.-Canadian border. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had situations where we've had single-hand sailors  
change their itinerary and not tell anybody, but it's seldom that 
you have an entire family disappear,'' McPherson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The family was traveling on the ``Jolly Joyce,'' a 65-foot,  
cream-colored ketch with two white sails and a gray, 10-foot 
dinghy. The Dayton (Ohio) Daily News reported that the family had 
been living on the boat in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., since buying it 
in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Chad and Mischa are home-schooled, according to their older  
sister, Beth Stewart. She told the Daily News she stayed behind in 
Ludlow Falls, near Dayton, to run the family's two video rental 
stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Beth Stewart and Coast Guard officials described Richard  
Stewart as an inexperienced sailor. They said he intended to head 
north along the East Coast to the St. Lawrence Seaway, before 
turning inland to the Great Lakes. The ultimate destination was the 
Michigan home of Debbie Stewart's parents, Beth Stewart told the 
Daily News. 
</P>
<P>
	En route, one of the boat's two engines died near Newport and  
the other started faltering, so the family docked there and sought 
repairs, said Coast Guard Petty Officer Al Bennett, based at 
Atlantic Area Headquarters in Portsmouth, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	They had problems finding parts, however, because the boat was  
nearly 30 years old. Bennett said a family friend located some 
parts in Louisiana and intended to install them in Ft. Lauderdale, 
but the Stewarts never returned, Bennett said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know which way they went and our search area is  
literally the Atlantic Ocean and the Hudson River,'' said 
McPherson. ``What we're hoping is somebody gives us a better search 
area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He asked anyone with information about the Jolly Joyce or the  
Stewart family to call the local Coast Guard station. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
