<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mortage Rates Edge Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The average interest rate on 30-year  
fixed-rate mortgages edged down to 7.93 percent this week from its 
highest level in more than two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The average was down from 8.15 percent last week -- the highest  
rate since early April 1997 -- according to a weekly survey released 
Thursday by Freddie Mac, the mortgage company. 
</P>
<P>
	Mortgages rates have been on an upward climb. So far this year,  
average rates on a 30-year mortgage have hit a low for the year of 
6.74 percent set at the end of January before reaching 8.15 percent 
last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing,  
averaged 7.53 percent this week, down from the average of 7.70 
percent last week. 
</P>
<P>
	On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an  
average initial rate of 6.18 percent this week, also down from 6.24 
percent the previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which  
averaged at or just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three 
types of mortgages. 
</P>
<P>
	Freddie Mac's chief economist Robert Van Order said that  
interest rates began to fall back following government reports that 
inflation at both the wholesale and retail levels was tame. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, Van Order along with many other economists believe  
that the Federal Reserve will nudge up interest rates next week for 
the second time this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the Mortgage Bankers Association reported Wednesday  
that mortgage loan applications for the week ending Aug. 13 were 
down 3.3 percent from the previous week and down 26 percent 
compared to the same week last year. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
