<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Center 911 Call Shows Panic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The head of the Los Angeles Police Department  
called for ``total gun control'' as he released 911 tapes that 
captured the terror unleashed by a gunman's rampage at a Jewish 
community center. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do we want to see another incident or do we want to bite the  
bullet and get these guns off the street,'' Bernard Parks said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The chief wants a ban on assault weapons and ``Saturday Night  
Special'' handguns. He also has called for a ban on gun shows and 
strict regulation of gun sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The 911 tapes revealed the fear and panic as well as fast action  
by employees of North Valley Jewish Community Center, where three 
boys, a teen-age counselor and a receptionist were wounded Aug. 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Callers provided dispatchers with vital information about the  
location and what was happening, but there also was some confusion 
over the gunman's description and weapon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Please hurry. He's got a huge machine gun,'' cried the first  
woman to call 911. ``I don't know how many people are dead, but 
there's hundreds of children. There's a summer camp here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a dispatcher sought information about the shooter, the woman  
said she had seen a white, heavyset man wearing black. 
</P>
<P>
	In another call a woman shouted, ``There's been a shooting here.  
He shot the whole damn place! ... Oh my God!'' 
</P>
<P>
	As an officer tried to question her, she shouted, ``Somebody  
just came in and shot up our whole school. ... He came in with a 
shotgun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dispatcher tried to calm her, telling her: ``You're my only  
link.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She then gave him details including the address of the center  
and who was there. ``There's 200 people in camp and there's 60 or 
70 in nursery school and staff,'' she said, telling the emergency 
operator she was under her desk. 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrived within four minutes of the first call.  
</P>
<P>
	One caller reported that children said an Asian man had opened  
fire. Another call described the gunman as Hispanic. Still another 
said it was a teen-ager. 
</P>
<P>
	The very first description phoned in matched that of Buford  
Furrow Jr., 37, the white supremacist who eventually surrendered 
and faces charges of attempted murder at the center and the murder 
of a postal worker shot to death a short distance away. 
</P>
<P>
	The weapon turned out to be a 9 mm semiautomatic assault weapon,  
not a machine gun or shotgun. 
</P>
<P>
	Parks said he believes the public is ready for a wide-ranging  
ban on guns, but lawmakers and the National Rifle Association have 
deterred such efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The resolve of the citizens has been high for a long time,''  
Parks said. ``The resolve of public officials is not as high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NRA's lobbying arm has said that Furrow was in violation of  
gun control laws already in place in California and has questioned 
whether new gun control proposals would have prevented the 
shootings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
