<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Guards Win $300 Each From Denny's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Six black and three white prison guards were  
awarded $300 each in damages Thursday from a Denny's restaurant 
whose manager told them they didn't ``look right together'' and 
ordered them to leave. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge awarded compensatory damages in the non-jury  
trial but said punitive damages were unwarranted for the ``less 
than 10-minute encounter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The guards sued the restaurant chain for discrimination,  
claiming an employee told them the restaurant was out of food when 
they arrived on Jan. 2, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	When they protested, manager Carlos Ibarra told them to call a  
company complaint line and said the 24-hour restaurant was closed. 
Seven guards testified that Ibarra commented they didn't ``look 
right together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Denny's Inc. claimed the guards were aggressive and  
rude. Ibarra was fired for violating company policy by closing the 
restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	``We respect the judge's decision in this case,'' Denny's said  
in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has been operating under a consent decree not to  
discriminate since reaching a $46 million agreement with the 
federal government five years ago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
