<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Putin Agree on New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin and his new prime  
minister, Vladimir Putin, have agreed on the makeup of the new 
Cabinet, which will be little changed from the old one, Putin said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair met in the Kremlin this morning, and Putin said  
afterward that the president had approved a list of ministers he 
had submitted. 
</P>
<P>
	Putin made his remarks at a session of the acting Cabinet  
members, and did not divulge names of the new ministers, but few 
changes were expected. Putin has proposed a new justice minister, 
but has not announced any other planned changes. 
</P>
<P>
	The prime minister, who was appointed just last week in the  
latest government shake-up, said his priorities included 
preparations for parliamentary elections in December and a draft 
budget that will be submitted to lawmakers next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of work will be needed to finalize the budget,'' Putin  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's economy remains in recession and the government is  
chronically short of cash. However, the economy has shown some 
signs of stabilizing this year following a financial meltdown in 
August of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Putin, who has spent most of his career in the country's  
security services, has not said what his economic policies will be 
beyond offering a general endorsement of market reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	He did say that the government was spending almost all its money  
on current needs, and should set aside more for investment in 
science, education and social development. 
</P>
<P>
	``Current spending is too large and estimates of our development  
needs are too low,'' he was quoted as saying by the Interfax news 
agency. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we lose our positions here, we will be relegated to the  
position of a third-rate country and we would never climb back 
again,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Putin is not expected to launch any major initiatives  
due to the government's lack of money and the looming parliamentary 
elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kremlin is hoping its allies can make a strong showing and  
reduce the clout of the Communist Party and other hardline factions 
that currently dominate parliament's lower house. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Yeltsin's inability to solve the country's economic,  
political and social problems gives his allies little on which to 
base their campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	Ex-Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, considered the country's  
most popular politician at the moment, joined an alliance this week 
that includes Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov and several regional 
governors. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance is seen as a direct challenge to Yeltsin and his  
allies, but Primakov claimed the coalition was not an 
``anti-presidential force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Primakov, who was fired by Yeltsin in May despite his  
popularity, said he was not seeking ``revenge'' against the 
president. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
