<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Dollar Falls, Tokyo Stocks Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar dropped sharply against the yen today as  
investors rushed to buy Japan's currency on growing optimism about 
the economy. Tokyo stocks edged lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 111.63 in afternoon trading, down 1.45  
yen from its level late Wednesday in Tokyo and below its late level 
of 112.03 yen overnight in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar hasn't traded that low late in Tokyo since Jan. 13  
when it was quoted at 111.55 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average dropped 12.52 points, or 0.07  
percent, to close at 17,879.74. On Wednesday, the average rose 
32.17 points, or 0.18 percent, to finish at 17,892.26. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar sank against the yen as investors sold the greenback  
following its plunge overnight, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was alos sharply lower, falling to  
116.98 yen from 119.30 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were buying yen as they moved funds into Japanese  
assets, betting that Japan's long-suffering economy may finally be 
on the mend. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are real money flows moving into Japan from Europe. It  
appears that until that subsides, the yen is going to keep getting 
stronger,'' Suzuki said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar fell to as low as 111.20 yen in Asian trading and  
moved as high as 112.30 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the dollar's fall was fueled by rumors that Eisuke  
Sakakibara, a former influential finance ministery official, had 
suggeted Japanese companies could withstand a stronger yen. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen can hurt Japan's exporters by forcing them to raise  
prices abroad or accept less in terms of yen from their overseas 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Tokyo stock exchange, share prices fell slightly amid  
worries that the stronger currency would do just that. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue chip shares sank, though the decline was offset somewhat by  
investor interest in domestic shares, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many companies can't make money with the yen above 113 yen''  
against the dollar, said Robert Sasaki, head of the quantitative 
strategy group at Jardine Fleming. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section dropped 3.08 points, or 0.21 percent, to 1,475.35. 
The TOPIX added 4.29 points, or 0.29 percent, to 1,478.43 the 
previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading on the exchange's main section was estimated at 493  
million shares, down from 502 million shares Wednesday. Declines 
outnumbered advances 709 to 458, while 135 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.8700 percent from Wednesday's close of 1.9350 
percent, boosting its price to 99.40 yen from 98.86 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
