<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saturn Says Station Wagons Are Hot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saturn Corp. President Cynthia Trudell said  
Wednesday that station wagons appear to be staging a comeback, and 
the automaker hopes to exploit it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe firmly there will be a resurgence in the wagon,''  
Trudell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturn, the small-car unit of General Motors Corp., last month  
launched its first midsize sedan and wagon. The L-series is the 
first new model line for Saturn since it began selling its S-series 
subcompact cars in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	The L-series offers a lower-cost alternative to the new luxury  
wagons that have recently arrived here from Europe, where wagons 
are far more popular. Saab, Volvo, Mercedes-Benz, Audi, BMW and 
Volkswagen have wagon versions of popular sedans in the U.S. 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Offerings in the midsize segment are fewer. Japan's Subaru has  
done well with the Legacy and Outback wagons and Ford Motor Co. 
offers a wagon version of its popular Taurus and the Mercury Sable. 
But in recent years, Toyota Motor Corp. eliminated its Camry wagon 
and Honda Motor Co. did the same with the Accord wagon. 
</P>
<P>
	With fewer automakers competing in the lower end of the market,  
Saturn is betting its reputation for friendly, no-haggle service 
will help drive up L-series sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a strong influence now coming in from Europe on the  
Audi, the Volvo wagon and the like. And people are seeing this as 
an alternative,'' Trudell told reporters during a briefing. ``We 
feel that's a really nice niche we can carve out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said Saturn dealers are expecting the wagon to represent 20  
percent to 30 percent of their sales with the L-series' arrival. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturn's L-series wagons include the LW1 with a four-cylinder  
engine for $19,275 and the LW2, with a V6, for $21,800. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than 2 percent of light vehicle sales nationally are  
wagons, said Christopher Cedergren, an industry consultant with 
Nextrend. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market for wagons overall is small,'' he said. ``That  
doesn't mean there isn't demand there. Subaru is creating new 
fortunes based on a reincarnation of the wagon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A key to the growth of wagon sales is whether they can project a  
``cool image'' rather than conjuring up the big, family-hauling 
station wagons of decades ago, Cedergren said. 
</P>
<P>
	During a luncheon speech at the National Press Club, Trudell  
endorsed the company's unique labor-management contract, which 
gives workers a say in how the company is run and rewards increased 
productivity. 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, before Trudell became president and chief  
executive, workers at the Saturn plant in Spring Hill, Tenn., upset 
with dwindling bonuses and their role in management decisions, gave 
their union leaders authority to call a strike. None was ever 
called. 
</P>
<P>
	``Like democracy, the partnership process is not always smooth.  
It can be downright messy,'' Trudell said. ``We can't reach 
creative solutions without conflict. Any successful relationship 
must have room for tension and disagreement.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
