<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 19, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Time Running Out for Quake Victims  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Hope is fading today for thousands of  
people buried alive by an earthquake that has killed almost 7,000 
people in Turkey. Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit admitted today what 
many Turks feared -- even the hundreds of professional rescue 
workers sent in from around the world will not be able to save all 
those under the rubble. Many earthquake victims will die of thirst 
and exposure. ``Thousands of buildings are in ruins,'' Ecevit said. 
``It is not possible to reach all of them.'' Some 35,000 people 
could be still buried under debris. 

</P>
<P>
	KLA Says It Has Disarmed  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Kosovo Albanian rebels rejected  
accusations they have orchestrated ongoing violence in Kosovo and 
insisted today that they have complied with a deadline to turn over 
weapons to NATO peacekeepers. The Kosovo Liberation Army's 
statements came a day after attackers hurled grenades and firebombs 
at the main Serbian Orthodox Church. Ethnic violence persists in 
Kosovo despite the presence of more than 40,000 NATO-led 
peacekeepers. Most of the unrest has been revenge attacks on a 
dwindling Serb minority, prompting NATO and U.N. officials 
overseeing Kosovo to hint of a KLA role. 

</P>
<P>
	Navy Predicts Widespread Y2K Failure  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Navy report predicts ``probable'' or  
``likely'' failures in electrical and water systems for many cities 
because of the Year 2000 technology problem -- an assessment more 
dire than any other made by the government. President Clinton's top 
Y2K adviser called the Navy's conclusions overly cautious, saying 
they assumed that major utilities would fail unless proved 
otherwise. The most recent version of the study, updated less than 
two weeks ago, predicted ``probable'' or ``likely'' partial 
failures in electric utilities that serve nearly 60 of roughly 400 
Navy and Marine Corps facilities. 

</P>
<P>
	China Cautions U.S. on Taiwan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At a news conference today, China's ambassador  
voiced opposition to any increase in the flow of U.S. arms to 
Taiwan -- particularly deployment of a U.S.-developed missile 
defense shield to protect the island. Li Zhaoxing said Beijing 
would not rule out force to stop Taiwanese independence or 
``possible foreign intervention.'' He also suggested China is 
concerned that Taiwan could become an issue in the U.S. 
presidential campaign and other political races. ``The issue of 
Taiwan is entirely China's internal matter,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Army Won't Test Missile Again  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After two successful tests of an Army missile  
designed to shoot down enemy missiles at the edge of space, the 
Pentagon announced today it will skip a planned third test. The 
Pentagon last year said it would require the missile contractor, 
Lockheed Martin Corp., to validate its design by scoring three 
successful intercepts. The missile had failed in its first six 
attempts to shoot down a mock warhead. Army Maj. Gen. Peter 
Franklin said the two successful tests this summer have ``proven'' 
that the missile works. 

</P>
<P>
	Ken Starr May Quit Early  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Kenneth Starr's imprint would be on a final  
report focusing on President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, even 
though a successor may finish the independent counsel's work, legal 
experts say. Starr informed a three-judge panel earlier this month 
that he plans to leave before his office's work is finished, a 
legal source said today. ``He indicated there were allegations to 
be prosecuted or declined,'' said the source. 

</P>
<P>
	School Enrollment Swells to Record  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's school enrollment swelled to a  
record for the fourth consecutive year, riding the crest of a 
second baby boom and increased immigration, the Education 
Department said today. Public and private school pupils in 
kindergarten through 12th grade will step into their classrooms 
this fall 53.2 million strong, surpassing last fall's enrollment by 
a half-million, according to an annual report that surveys schools 
on their fall enrollments. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 27.54  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- At the close on Wall Street, the Dow Jones  
industrial average was down 27.54 at 10,963.84. Declining issues on 
the New York Stock Exchange led advancers 1,616-1,375. The Nasdaq 
was down 36.30 at 2,621.43. 

</P>
<P>
	WNBA's Kim Perrot Dies at 32  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Kim Perrot, the Houston Comets point guard often  
described as the heart and soul of the two-time WNBA champions, 
died today of lung cancer. She was 32. Perrot was signed three 
years ago as a developmental player for the fledgling Women's 
National Basketball Association franchise here. Despite her 
5-foot-5 frame, Perrot quickly became a starter and crowd favorite 
noted for ferocious play that helped the Comets win consecutive 
championships in 1997 and 1998, the league's inaugural seasons. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  











  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
