<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 12:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Americans Killed in Quake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Georgia man and four of his young  
grandchildren were among the thousands killed in the earthquake 
that shook western Turkey. Two other family members were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	They are the only American casualties known so far from the  
Turkish tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	The dead were identified by family members as Nizam Kilic of  
Marietta and his four grandchildren: Jeffrey Michael, 6; Jennifer 
Kayla, 5; David Tansan, 2; and Katherine ``Katie'' Michelle, 9 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The father, Babur Kilic, a Marietta anesthesiologist, had  
planned to join his wife, their five children and his parents this 
weekend in Turkey for a vacation. Instead, he left for Istanbul 
Wednesday to make funeral arrangements, other family members told 
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	Kilic's wife, Jan, and 6-year-old daughter, Natalie, survived  
the quake. Kilic's mother is in critical condition and Jan Kilic is 
in an Istanbul hospital, although the family has not yet learned 
her condition. Natalie was not injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, a White House spokesman said U.S. rescue teams were  
working today to free three people pinned amid rubble from the 
earthquake. The three -- a 5-year-old girl, a 24-year-old woman and 
a man of undetermined age -- were found alive amid rubble in the 
hard-hit city of Izmit, National Security Council spokesman David 
Leavy said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 70 search and rescue experts from Fairfax, Va., and  
Miami are stationed in the southeast quadrant of Izmit, Leavy said. 
The search teams began round-the-clock shifts early today, Leavy 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three Air National Guard C-130 transport planes were to leave  
U.S. bases today and Friday, carrying medical supplies and 
emergency equipment, White House and Pentagon officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The planes will fly to Istanbul from Channel Islands, Calif.,  
Charlotte, N.C. and Cheyenne, Wyo., a Pentagon spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	A fourth U.S. plane, a C-17, will carry 2,200 pounds of  
firefighting equipment, chiefly for use against an oil refinery 
fire ignited by the earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States also plans to bring in a water purification  
unit that can handle emergency water needs for about 10,000 people, 
along with a 20-member U.S. medical team based in Europe, Leavy 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, three Navy ships with 2,100 Marines were ordered Wednesday  
to head for the Aegean Sea to provide humanitarian assistance to 
earthquake victims. 
</P>
<P>
	The ships from the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit are due to  
arrive near Istanbul on Sunday, Leavy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The three ships, the USS Kearsarge, the USS Ponce and the USS  
Gunston Hall, have about 630 beds, six operating rooms and five 
X-ray rooms, eight doctors, three dental officers and 88 medical 
corpsmen. Their 22 helicopters can provide medical evacuations from 
the damaged areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit recently completed  
peacekeeping duties in Kosovo, where they were the first American 
forces to enter the Serb province after the war ended in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Leavy said there is no estimate yet of the cost of U.S. relief  
efforts in Turkey. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 17:36:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Won't Work Too Hard on Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton celebrated his 53rd  
birthday Thursday by sharing a few inside jokes with White House 
staff, and then leaving Washington for more than two weeks of 
vacation and politicking. 
</P>
<P>
	He promised reporters traveling with him to Martha's Vineyard:  
``I'll try not to work you too hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, presidential friend Vernon Jordan met Clinton's plane at  
the island off the Massachusetts coast. As in past years, Jordan 
planned a small birthday celebration for Clinton at Jordan's 
vacation home. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the estimated 40 guests were Maurice Tempelsman, former  
companion to Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis; former Clinton budget 
director Franklin Raines; NBC sports chief Dick Ebersol and his 
wife, actress Susan Saint James; CNN correspondent Charlayne 
Hunter-Gault and her husband, Ronald Gault; investment banker 
Steven Ratner and author William Styron. 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 members of the White House staff and volunteers threw  
Clinton a much larger birthday party earlier Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton sat under an  
umbrella on the White House South Lawn while listening to a country 
western band from Arkansas called The Greasy Greens. 
</P>
<P>
	National Economic Council head Gene Sperling led a mock game of  
``Jeopardy'' based on little-known administration trivia: 
</P>
<P>
	Q: What are James Carville and Dick Morris?  
</P>
<P>
	A: No, not political handlers who helped Clinton win in 1992 and  
1996. They're the reason Kansas educators rejected the theory of 
evolution. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House has been officially mum on the subject of the  
Kansas state school board's recent decision to de-emphasize the 
teaching of the biological concept of evolution. Critics in Kansas 
and educators elsewhere have called the move a capitulation to 
religious conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	After the music and jokes, Clinton, the first lady, daughter  
Chelsea and first dog Buddy walked to the presidential helicopter 
for the first leg of their trip to Martha's Vineyard. 
</P>
<P>
	Arriving a short time later at Andrews Air Force Base, where the  
Air Force One jet is housed, Clinton let Buddy off the leash. The 
chocolate lab bounded up the steps of the plane ahead of Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the plane took off, Clinton popped his head into the  
press compartment in the back of the plane and offered assurances 
the vacation would be, well, mostly a vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and his family are dividing their vacation this year  
between the island and New York state, a nod to Mrs. Clinton's 
senatorial aspirations. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the fifth Martha's Vineyard vacation for the Clintons.  
They will spend nine days on the 20-acre Oyster Pond estate of 
developer Richard Friedman, their host for the past three years. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Mrs. Clinton planned to visit a church on the  
neighboring island of Nantucket as part of a program that 
highlights historic sites to encourage preservation of the nation's 
culture and heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 28, the Clintons leave the island for equally tony East  
Hampton, N.Y., and a Democratic National Committee fund-raising 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Then they head to Skaneateles, a quiet resort town of 7,500  
people on Skaneateles Lake just southwest of Syracuse, for five 
days. The Clintons will stay at the lakeside home of real estate 
developer Thomas McDonald. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Jake Siewert has acknowledged plans for  
the Clintons to make appearances during their stay in New York. 
Mrs. Clinton is considering a 2000 run for the seat of retiring 
Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
