<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Natural Gas Futures Race Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Natural gas futures raced higher Wednesday on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange, reaching their highest levels nearly two 
years, amid concern about storms developing in key producing 
regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude and its products also rose sharply. On other markets,  
soybeans also rose sharply. Wheat gained, while corn retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas prices jumped more than 4 percent as tropical storms  
developed in the Gulf of Mexico and in the Atlantic, situations 
that could threaten production platforms at a time when inventories 
are lower than normal. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas supplies in storage have fallen to 5.6 percent below  
levels of a year ago after blistering heat forced utilities to 
power up plants to meet consumer demand from air conditioners and 
fans running at overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas in storage now must be replaced ahead of the busy  
winter heating season, and the threat of production outages for 
offshore platforms is causing concern that a colder-than-normal 
fall would bring shortages. 
</P>
<P>
	Heating oil futures helped boost crude and unleaded gasoline  
amid positioning from investors who are betting that supplies this 
winter will be tight because of production cutbacks from major oil 
producers. Heating oil is a byproduct of crude production, and 
analysts are predicting supplies could become critically tight in 
some areas later this year if the Organization of the Petroleum 
Exporting Countries and other producers succeed in keeping supplies 
of the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas for September delivery rose 10.6 cent to $2.898 for  
each 1,000 cubic feet; September crude rose 25 cents to $21.77 
cents a barrel; September heating oil rose 1.05 cents to 57.50 
cents a gallon; September unleaded gasoline rose 1.2 cents to 66.20 
cents a gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures rocketed higher Thursday on the Chicago Board of  
Trade after overnight rains missed bone-dry Midwest growing 
regions. Wheat also gained, while corn retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans led the gains after rainfall of up to an inch fell in  
Minnesota, Iowa and parts of Illinois, but missed fields that have 
languished for weeks under hot, dry conditions. Forecasters says 
those same fields likely will remain dry over the next week, which 
will increase the potential for lower yields. 
</P>
<P>
	Farm tours are finding that average yields for corn and soybeans  
are slipping as the dry weather prevents maturing crops from 
filling properly. Corn futures, after initially gaining on the 
strength of soybeans, later retreated amid perceptions the rainfall 
helped most major growing areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures also were supported by strong weekly export sales.  
The U.S. Agriculture Department reported that net export sales 
totaled 566,800 metric tons, which was slightly higher than market 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	November soybeans rose 8 1/4 cents to $4.77 3/4 a bushel; December  
wheat for rose 1 3/4 cents to $2.89 1/2 a bushel; December corn fell 1 3/4 
cents to $2.26 1/4 a bushel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
