<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 17:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Greek Orthodox Church Head Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The embattled leader of the nation's 1.9 million Greek Orthodox  
Christians resigned Thursday, ending two years of efforts to oust 
him by critics who said he stifled dissent and was behind the 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	Archbishop Spyridon, the first American-born leader of the U.S.  
church, had appeared to have the support of the world leader of 
Eastern Orthodox Christians, Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew of 
Istanbul, Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a statement from his New York office, Spyridon indicated  
he had been forced out, saying he resigned ``for reasons totally 
independent of and unrelated to my personal intentions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bartholomew, the spiritual leader of the world's 300 million  
Orthodox Christians, had come under strong pressure from Orthodox 
leaders in the United States to replace Spyridon. Some had 
threatened to break away from the patriarchate and declare an 
independent church. 
</P>
<P>
	Bartholomew announced that Spyridon will be replaced by  
Metropolitan Demetrios of Greece, who has studied and taught in the 
United States and is considered to have a base of popularity to 
build on. 
</P>
<P>
	Spyridon, 54, was born in Warren, Ohio, but has spent most of  
his life in Europe. Critics claimed he could not relate to 
parishioners who are third- and fourth-generation Americans and 
feel less and less tied to Byzantine and Greek traditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Spyridon claimed he was only trying to protect the church's  
values and traditions. 
</P>
<P>
	A lay group, Greek Orthodox American Leaders of Cambridge,  
Mass., began working for Spyridon's ouster in 1997, a year after 
Bartholomew appointed him to lead the U.S. church. Last January all 
five U.S. regional bishops, called metropolitans, told Bartholomew 
that Spyridon must go. 
</P>
<P>
	The spokesman for GOAL, businessman Dean Popps of McLean, Va.,  
said ``the long ordeal and period of disorderliness in the affairs 
of our archdiocese appears to be over.'' However, Popps said 
Demetrios, 71, ``will have a monumental task ahead of him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spyridon said he will serve until Aug. 30, then take a post with  
the tiny Greek Orthodox church in Turkey and await reassignment. 
</P>
<P>
	In his statement, Spyridon referred obliquely to the church  
tensions. ``My heart is clean of any malice, ill will, or judgment 
of others,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that he enjoyed the loyalty of ``the vast majority of  
the faithful.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 08:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hilton Settles Union Bias Complaint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Three waitresses who alleged they were barred from  
working at a new pub because they didn't speak with an Irish brogue 
will work there now as part of a settlement of their discrimination 
claim against Hilton. 
</P>
<P>
	Gloria DiMartino, Dorothy ``Dottie'' Webb and Jo Murray had each  
worked at the Logan airport Ramada's bar for more than three 
decades until it closed last weekend. In June they filed a 
complaint with the Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination, 
alleging that Hilton -- which has taken over the old hotel and is 
renovating it -- intended to open Kitty O'Shea's, an Irish theme 
bar, and give first preference for jobs in the new bar to those 
with Irish accents. 
</P>
<P>
	Beverly Hills, Calif.-based Hilton Hotels Corp. officials had  
denied wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	With the settlement, the women will be allowed to work in the  
new Irish pub at the $100 million hotel, slated to open Sept. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eveyone is going to have a job,'' said Coleman Nee, a  
spokesman for the Logan Airport Hilton Hotel and Towers. 
</P>
<P>
	Local 26 union President Janice Loux said the hotel workers  
accepted a new contract with hotel management and agreed to drop 
the bias complaint. The new hotel will employ 500 workers, compared 
with the 250 to 300 at the old Ramada. 
</P>
<P>
	Hilton General Manager Bert James said he was pleased the issue  
was resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	When they filed their complaint, the three waitresses said their  
heavy ``Bahstahn'' accent was good enough while to calm anxious 
travelers -- and they were happy to entertain a common request from 
tourists. Said Murray: 
</P>
<P>
	``They all want to hear us say 'Pahk the cah in Hahvahd Yahd'  
and `chowdah.''' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Drug Co. Exec To Plead Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A former Swiss pharmaceutical company  
executive agreed Thursday to plead guilty and serve six months in 
jail for his role in a worldwide case of vitamin price-fixing, the 
Justice Department announced. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the 10th prosecution in the case in which the company,  
F. Hoffmann-La Roche, already has been sentenced to pay a record 
$500 million criminal fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoffmann-La Roche and some of its competitors have admitted that  
from January 1990 until this May, they raised and fixed prices and 
allocated market shares for vitamins used in virtually every 
American home and added to bread, milk and breakfast cereal. 
</P>
<P>
	In a one-count criminal charge filed in U.S. District Court in  
Dallas, the government alleged that Dr. Roland Bronnimann, a Swiss 
citizen and resident and former president of Hoffmann-La Roche's 
vitamins and fine chemicals division, conspired in violation of the 
Sherman Act to fix prices in the United States and elsewhere for 
vitamins A, B2, B5, C, E, and beta carotene. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the jail time, Bronnimann agreed to pay a  
$150,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	The government also charged that the conspirators rigged bids  
and allocated customer contracts between themselves for vitamin 
premixes throughout this country. Vitamin premixes are used to 
enrich breakfast cereals and numerous other processed foods. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bronnimann knew of, approved and participated in key aspects  
of Hoffmann-La Roche's operation in the vitamins cartel,'' said 
Gary R. Spratling, deputy assistant attorney general in charge of 
antitrust criminal enforcement. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a member of Hoffmann-La Roche's executive committee at the  
time of his involvement, Bronnimann put the full weight of 
legitimacy behind the company's involvement in the most pervasive 
international cartel ever uncovered.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The government said Bronnimann conspired with counterparts at  
BASF, Rhone-Poulenc and other unnamed competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Bronnimann is the second former senior Hoffmann-La Roche  
executive to be charged in the continuing investigation. On May 20, 
Dr. Kuno Sommer, former director of worldwide marketing for 
Hoffmann-La Roche's vitamins and fine chemicals division, was 
charged with participating in the vitamin cartel and with lying to 
Justice Department investigators in 1997 to cover up the 
conspiracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Sommer, also a Swiss citizen and resident, pleaded guilty and  
was sentenced July 23 to four months in prison and fined $100,000. 
</P>
<P>
	On March 2, a third foreign national, Antonio Felix, a Mexican  
citizen and vice president for basic and international products at 
DuCoa L.P., agreed to plead guilty to plotting to fix the prices of 
vitamin B4. He has not been sentenced. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 18:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pan Am 103 Families To Get Briefings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Families of victims of the 1988 bombing of Pan  
Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, will be briefed here next 
week by Scottish prosecutors about the upcoming trial in the 
Netherlands of two Libyans accused of the crime. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department's Office for Victims of Crime arranged  
the two-day, closed meeting with Scottish prosecutors, constables 
and Justice officials ``to try to address all the questions that 
arise before a trial is to begin to indeed make sure that survivors 
are informed,'' Attorney General Janet Reno told her weekly news 
conference Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is very important for survivors, for victims, to  
understand what the processes are,'' said Reno, who will address 
the families Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Libyan intelligence officers, Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi  
and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, are being tried under Scottish law in The 
Hague on charges of planting a suitcase bomb that blew up the jumbo 
jet, killing 270 people, including 189 Americans. The trial is to 
begin in early February. 
</P>
<P>
	Some victims' families are critical of the deal brokered by the  
State Department and the United Nations with Libya to hold the 
trial in the Netherlands rather than in Scotland or the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should have held fast for a trial here or in Scotland even  
if it meant Libya would not turn over these two guys, because then 
there would be less risk that this trial would be used as an excuse 
to drop economic sanctions against Libya,'' Dan Cohen said Thursday 
in a telephone interview from his home in Cape May Court House, 
N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen, whose daughter Theodora died in the bombing, fears the  
trial of the two operatives could become ``a judicial fig leaf for 
the rehabilitation of (Libyan leader) Moammar Gadhafi,'' who he 
believes ordered the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Noting that Great Britain cited the upcoming trial in dropping  
its sanctions against Libya, Cohen said he fears that even if the 
pair are convicted, British officials later may grant them early 
release from prison, rather than keep them locked up for years 
trying to pressure them to identify the masterminds of the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has not dropped its economic sanctions,  
including a ban on American travel to Libya or doing business 
there. The United Nations suspended its sanctions, but has not 
decided whether to lift them permanently. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. Security Council resolutions require Libya to cooperate  
with the prosecution and to pay compensation to the families of the 
victims of the bombing if the two men are convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will be watching very carefully whether Libya complies with  
the requirement in the Security Council that they cooperate fully 
as the trial unfolds and that they pay compensation to the victims 
of the Pan Am 103 terrorist bombing,'' State Department spokesman 
James Rubin said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if U.S. officials believe Gadhafi or other senior Libyan  
officials ordered the bombing, Rubin replied, ``Under legal advice, 
it is our considered judgment that it would be best to allow the 
trial to unfold without expressing our opinions publicly prior to 
that trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Using funds derived from fines paid by U.S. criminals, the  
Justice Office for Victims of Crime is helping pay to fly some 
relatives to the Netherlands to watch the trial, arranging a 
satellite telecast of the trial or its highlights for families 
here, and providing a daily report of trial activity on a toll-free 
telephone line for families. 
</P>
<P>
	It also is establishing a secure Internet Web site with trial  
reports and an electronic bulletin board through which families can 
communicate with each other. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 16:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ayala Returns To Ring After Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Tony Ayala Jr. was signed to fight for  
$750,000 and a world championship when, fueled by a mixture of 
heroin, cocaine and alcohol, he broke into a home New Year's Day 
1983 and raped a woman. 
</P>
<P>
	He returns to the ring Friday night in a comeback improbable  
even by boxing standards, one not even Ayala could have imagined 
while serving 16 years in a New Jersey state prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``Throughout my prison sentence I wondered what might have  
happened against the fighters of the time,'' Ayala said. ``But did 
I see myself making a comeback at the age of 36? No.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of hometown fans who remember the ferocious teen-ager  
dubbed ``El Torito'' who once spit on an opponent after knocking 
him out are expected to turn out as Ayala fights Manuel Esparza in 
what he hopes is the first step toward the title fight he never 
got. 
</P>
<P>
	What Ayala will show in the ring is anyone's guess, including  
his own. He's 36 and balding with suspect reflexes, and no longer 
has the anger which seemed to carry him in fights. 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala will get $200,000 to find out, in a scheduled 10-round  
fight at the 162-pound weight limit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't say I'm where I was at when I was 19. But I never want  
to be the kind of person again that I was at 19,'' Ayala said. 
``I've made a lot of progress in four months since I got out of 
prison. And I certainly have enough to win this fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the ring, Ayala has more confidence in himself. There,  
he hopes to prove himself as a man who finally takes responsibility 
for his actions, and is truly remorseful for a crime that sent him 
to prison for half of his life. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems society is willing to put the past aside and let me  
prove myself. That's all I asked for,'' Ayala said. ``I expected a 
lot worse from people for what I did than what has actually 
happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala's return to boxing has generated grumblings from those who  
think he should have served his entire 35-year sentence. But it has 
also sparked excitement and memories of a teen-ager who once seemed 
destined to rule the junior middleweight ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	In just a few short years after turning pro, Ayala was 22-0 with  
19 knockouts and had signed for a fight with WBA 154-pound champion 
Davey Moore. He was the top-ranked contender and was coming off 
consecutive knockouts of Robbie Epps and Carlos Herrera in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala was already being mentioned against the likes of Sugar Ray  
Leonard, Roberto Duran and Marvelous Marvin Hagler. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the most exciting fighter in boxing,'' said Lester  
Bedford, who helped promote some Ayala fights at the time and is 
promoting Friday's bout. ``He was Mike Tyson before Mike Tyson.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Much like Tyson, though, Ayala couldn't control himself outside  
the ring. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early morning hours of Jan. 1, 1983, he broke into a  
neighbor's apartment, tied her up and raped her. Police reports at 
the time indicated Ayala not only assaulted the woman, but also 
cruelly taunted her. 
</P>
<P>
	In a few short hours, Ayala was on his way from ring riches to  
prisoner No. 69765 at the state prison in Rahway, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pain I put the victim through will never be forgotten.  
It's something I want to keep speaking out on,'' said Ayala, who 
had already been on probation before for assaulting a woman at a 
San Antonio drive-in theater. ``It was a terrible thing for me to 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala, who credits prison counseling for helping him come to  
terms with his behavior, blames some of his conduct on being 
molested as a child and an adolescence spent getting drunk and 
high. 
</P>
<P>
	He started drinking as a child and was using heroin by the time  
he was 12. His habits made his success in the ring even more 
remarkable. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would clean up from two weeks to 10 days before a fight,''  
he said. ``It was a constant level of misery. I equated getting 
high with something good and positive, never realizing the torment 
was within myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala said he never seriously considered a boxing comeback until  
a fellow prisoner brought it up during a workout about a year 
before he became eligible for parole. 
</P>
<P>
	He weighed about 190 pounds when he walked out of prison in  
April, but weighed in Thursday at 160 pounds, only six pounds 
heavier than he was when he was terrorizing opponents in the junior 
middleweight division. Esparaza weighed 161 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	``The desire is there, but I don't know if the ferocity is  
there,'' Ayala said. ``I don't recognize any difference. It's just 
that I don't get as excited or as wound up as I used to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Ayala is successful against Esparza, he figures it will take  
a handful of fights before he is able to fight a top contender. 
After that, he can see himself fighting the likes of Oscar De La 
Hoya or Felix Trinidad. 
</P>
<P>
	If not, though, life will go on. He remarried his former wife,  
Lisa, just after getting out of prison and wants mainly to lead a 
normal and sober life. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's always hope I will fight for a world title and make  
tens of millions of dollars,'' Ayala said. ``But every single day 
is a new beginning for me. I much prefer who I am today, even if 
that means not being successful in the ring.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 16:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
