<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> K-State Looks To Keep Winning Touch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- Jonathan Beasley says he's not bothered  
at the prospect of replacing the only Kansas State quarterback to 
beat Nebraska in 29 years. 
</P>
<P>
	David Allen shrugs his shoulders when asked about replacing  
K-State's career rushing leader. 
</P>
<P>
	And Aaron Lockett, when reminded that he's one of only two  
returning Wildcats who caught a pass last season, just grins. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite two heartbreaking losses to end last season, the  
Wildcats seems genuinely upbeat heading into a season without 
Michael Bishop, Eric Hickson and Darnell McDonald. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have faith in the youngsters we have,'' said Bill Snyder,  
who will also be without kicker Martin Gramatica. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wildcats are coming off an 11-2 season in which they had the  
national championship game squarely in their sights but squandered 
it in a double-overtime loss to Texas A&AMP;M in the Big 12 title game. 
Still depressed three weeks later, they lost to unranked Purdue in 
the Alamo Bowl and saw what had been the finest season in 103 years 
of Kansas State football turn into one of the most bitterly 
disappointing. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, as they take their first steps toward regaining all  
that momentum, their biggest void is at quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	In two years as a starter, Bishop walked off the field a loser  
only three times. His powerful arm and legs led K-State to its 
finest two years, getting the Wildcats close to a national title 
game in the Fiesta Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Beasley, a backup in 1996 and '97 and redshirted last season,  
can throw about as well as Bishop but is not as quick on his feet. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll be competing with junior Adam Helm.  
</P>
<P>
	``They both have some experience in our system. They've had the  
opportunity to play and compete for several years,'' said Snyder. 
``This will be Adam's fifth year and Jon's fourth year. Jonathan's 
being a backup quarterback for two of those three years, and 
redshirting the other has given him an opportunity to get a lot of 
reps on the practice field. What they don't have is an ample amount 
of playing time under stressful conditions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newcomer Eli Roberson could also have an impact.  
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever a great quarterback leaves this program, it seems  
like we've had somebody step in and do the job,'' said Beasley. 
``No matter who gets to be No. 1, they're always going to have 
comparisons with Mike. We'll just have to deal with it and go from 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Wildcats took a big blow when running back Frank Murphy  
broke a bone in his foot during conditioning exercises on July 28. 
He could be out as long as eight weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	But the No. 1 running back spot was probably going to go to  
Allen, among the nation's most dazzling punt returners of 1998. 
Allen returned punts for touchdowns in three consecutive games and 
tied an NCAA record with four TD returns. He broke his own Big 12 
record with 730 yards in punt returns. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really excited about this year, because now at tailback I  
get more of an opportunity to play and see what I can do there,'' 
said Allen, who had only 31 carries last year. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonald is a big loss. But Lockett was No. 2 on the team with  
44 catches for 928 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just working hard and staying focused,'' said Lockett, a  
sophomore. ``We have enough people here from last year to know what 
it takes to get there.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
