<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Polls: Bush Keeping Big Lead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful George W. Bush  
has kept a big lead in a new national poll, but has slipped 
slightly in a survey of New Hampshire voters. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor was at 61 percent in a national CNN/USA  
Today/Gallup poll of 434 respondents who are Republican or who lean 
toward Republicans. Elizabeth Dole was in second place at 13 
percent and the other candidates were in single digits. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush had close to the same lead he had in a June CNN/USA  
Today/Gallup poll. The new survey was taken from Monday through 
Wednesday before the latest controversy over questions about Bush's 
past use of illegal drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	In the New Hampshire poll, Bush was at 40 percent, down from the  
47 percent he had a month ago. The New Hampshire survey of 450 
registered Republicans by the independent American Research Group 
showed that Arizona Sen. John McCain had an edge for the second 
spot in New Hampshire. Dole, Pat Buchanan, Dan Quayle, Alan Keyes, 
Steve Forbes, Gary Bauer and Orrin Hatch were all in single digits. 
Fifteen percent said they were undecided. 
</P>
<P>
	The state poll was taken Sunday through Tuesday and both surveys  
had a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	The polls are the first measure of voter sentiment in New  
Hampshire since the Iowa straw poll. In the straw poll -- an 
unscientific popularity contest held by the Iowa Republican Party -- 
Bush won, followed by Forbes, Dole and Bauer. McCain did not 
participate. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa leads off the selection process with its caucuses in early  
February, followed by New Hampshire, which holds the nation's first 
presidential primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore led former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley  
58 percent to 31 percent in the national poll of 493 respondents 
who were Democrats or lean Democratic, while 10 percent were 
undecided. That national lead is largely unchanged from June. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Hampshire, Gore has maintained his lead among New  
Hampshire voters over Bradley, the survey said. In July, Gore held 
a 48-32 lead in New Hampshire; this month, he had 46 percent to 29 
percent for Bradley. Twenty-five percent of the 415 Democrats 
polled said they were undecided. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
