<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Tips for the Drought-Stressed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Northeasterners, is the drought taking a toll  
on your lawn? Your flower beds? 
</P>
<P>
	How about your psyche?  
</P>
<P>
	Not to worry, the government is ready to help.  
</P>
<P>
	``Are there activities or things people can do to reduce  
drought-related stress?'' asks a news release from the Center for 
Mental Health Services. The answer, an unqualified ``Yes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, when brushing your teeth, cut off the faucet and  
focus on the ``actual brushing,'' instead of the sound of 
``continually flowing water in the background.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Or, when you realize the running faucet is wasting water: ``Put  
a glass ... under it, and put it in the refrigerator for later. By 
day's end, you will likely be surprised how much water you might 
have wasted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, another solution is to simply shut off the faucet.  
But the center suggests you might use the glass to ``make a game of 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still another suggestion for late-night trips to the bathroom:  
</P>
<P>
	``Resist the reflexive action of automatically flushing the  
toilet if you awaken at night and there is only liquid waste. 
Simply wait and flush in the morning. Believe it or not, flushing 
itself can add to the stress of awakening in the middle of the 
night because of the noise element.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All of this raises a central question: Are these serious  
stress-reduction suggestions? Yes, they are, assures Curtis R. 
Austin, spokesman for the center, a branch of the Department of 
Health and Human Services. It is all part of his effort to get 
people to think about mental health issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not talking major breakthroughs. We're not finding a  
cure for AIDS,'' he said. ``We're trying to turn a negative 
situation into a positive, and what's so bad about that?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
