<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> California GOP Mired in Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The California GOP is in debt,  
spending money faster than it comes in as the organization prepares 
for next year's crucial elections in the face of lackluster 
donations. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans hope to rebound from 1998, when they were swept from  
every statewide office but two and lost control of the governor's 
mansion for the first time in 16 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The stakes are even higher in next year's federal races:  
Republicans want to hold on to their slim majority in the U.S. 
House of Representatives, and California has 52 seats up for grabs, 
more than any other state. 
</P>
<P>
	Cash will be vital in the rebuilding of GOP voter rolls.  
Republican registration has dropped more than 10 percent this 
decade, to about one in three voters. 
</P>
<P>
	The party listed $414,818 in debts as of June 30, according to  
an Associated Press review of reports the parties must file with 
the secretary of state and the Federal Election Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	That was far more than the $262,137 they had in the bank. The  
party also borrowed $300,000 to pay bills left over from the 1998 
elections. 
</P>
<P>
	While it has raised about the same amount of money this year as  
California Democrats, the GOP has spent nearly twice as much. 
</P>
<P>
	So while Republicans sink further into debt in the first half of  
the year, Democrats are sitting on nearly $2.7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	John McGraw, the chairman of the state Republican Party, said  
fund raising this year has been disappointing. 
</P>
<P>
	The party's state and federal committees raised $1.84 million in  
the first half of the year, slightly less than the $1.91 million 
California Democrats took in. 
</P>
<P>
	The California GOP's bottom line was pumped up by transfusions  
from the national party, which accounted for one-sixth of the state 
party's total take. 
</P>
<P>
	McGraw said several factors help explain the lackluster  
fund-raising, including his relatively young tenure as party chief. 
McGraw took over the GOP in early March. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a new chairman, I have to establish credibility with the  
donor community, which means saying what you're going to do and 
doing what you say. I'm in that phase,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, many would-be donors are not paying attention to  
politics in this non-election year, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
