<HEADLINE> Lobbying Follows Clinton on Vacation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton may be taking a vacation,  
but lobbyists never rest. 
</P>
<P>
	The Biotechnology Industry Organization, an association of  
specialty drug companies, is chasing Clinton to his retreat on 
Martha's Vineyard with radio ads critical of the president's plan 
to add prescription drug coverage to Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	The ads will air only on the resort island's WMVY radio this  
week and next, but will be repeated at least seven times a day 
while Clinton and his family are there. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a portable mobile White House just like people carry  
mobile phones these days and this week and part of next it's 
operating out of Martha's Vineyard,'' said BIO president Carl B. 
Feldbaum, who interrupted his own family vacation in Idaho to talk 
about the ad campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Another good reason to target Clinton while he's away from  
Washington: 60 second radio spots on Martha's Vineyard cost just 
$65 apiece. When BIO ran similar ads in the nation's capital 
earlier this summer, aimed at members of Congress, they cost more 
than ten times that much. 
</P>
<P>
	In BIO's ads, senior citizens supportive of the idea of Medicare  
drug coverage nevertheless raise concerns about the specifics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want a big government agency to set drug policy,''  
says a retired school teacher in one. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug companies developing scores of new medicines for the  
elderly are walking a fine political line by opposing Clinton's 
plan. But also, Feldbaum said of the ads, ``We toned them down a 
little bit because while we wanted to get our message across, 
everybody is entitled to a vacation.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
