<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Bans Loral Satellite Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The State Department has refused Loral Space  
&AMP; Communication's request to lift a suspension that has delayed the 
launch of a satellite the company sold to China. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's technical-assistance agreement to deliver  
satellites to China was suspended in December amid an investigation 
that Loral's dealings may have passed on technology to China that 
could compromise U.S. security. Hughes Electronics also is under 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Loral was notified this month that the State Department has  
extended the ban, which has left the $124 million satellite sitting 
idle. If the suspension remains in place, China could cancel the 
contract and the company could face up to $12 million in penalties 
plus $38 million in expenses to refurbish the satellite for another 
buyer, Loral said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We remain hopeful the suspension will be lifted,'' Tom Ross,  
Loral vice president for government relations, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it has not transferred sensitive information to  
China, but State Department spokesman James Rubin said the 
government's ``concerns have not been alleviated, so the suspension 
continues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Loral's agreement would allow export of missile-control  
technical data for which certification from the president is now 
required, Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department has approved other launches of satellites  
in China built by U.S. contractors, including Motorola's Iridium 
launch in June, Rubin said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
