<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CDC Warns of Rare Fungal Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        ATLANTA (AP) -- Three people in Arizona have contracted a fungal  
infection this year that is rare in humans and can cause noncancerous 
growths, the government said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
        The fungus -- gastrointestinal basidiobolomycosis -- is commonly  
found in decaying vegetation and soil and in the gastrointestinal tract 
of reptiles and amphibians. It is rarely found in people, the federal 
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said. 
</P>
<P>
        Only 12 cases have ever been reported -- three in Brazil, one  
in Kuwait, one in Florida and the rest in Arizona, where the three 
most recent cases occurred between January and March, the CDC said. 
The other three Arizona cases occurred from 1994 to 1998. 
</P>
<P>
        The disease is often misdiagnosed as cancer or inflammatory  
bowel disease, the CDC said. Such was the case with those infected 
in Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
        The fungus is passed through ingestion or an open wound.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
