<HEADLINE> KB Toys Gets Web Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- After a net loss of over $8 million so far  
this year, Columbus-based Consolidated Stores Corp. is counting on 
online sales with its new KB Toys Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	Consolidated joined with Denver-based BrainPlay.com on July 21  
to create KBkids.com. Consolidated holds 80 percent and BrainPlay 
20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The site offers over 10,000 toys, games, videos and books --  
about five times more choices than in a traditional KB Toys store. 
</P>
<P>
	Consolidated Stores Corp. operates 2,504 stores in all 50 states  
and Puerto Rico. Of those stores, 1,327 are toy and close-out toy 
stores operating as KB Toy Works, KB Toy Outlet and with the online 
shopping. 
</P>
<P>
	The KB Toys chain is the No. 2 toy retailer in the United  
States, behind Toys ``R'' Us Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Consolidated chief financial officer Michael Potter said  
Thursday that with its $1.9 billion in yearly retail toy sales, KB 
has better toy-buying power that can translate into better 
selection and lower prices for customers than cyberspace-only 
competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	KB will compete with the Internet's most successful vendor,  
Amazon.com, which has more than 10 million established customers 
and added a toys and games site last month. Two-year-old eToys.com, 
another competitor, is selling 100,000 items each year online. 
</P>
<P>
	Toys ``R'' Us is the No. 3 online toy retailer in terms of  
number of visitors, according to market research firm PC Data, of 
Reston, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal reported Thursday that the company plans  
to spend $50 million to revamp its Web site Toysrus.com, which 
trails SmarterKids.com, a closely held concern in Needham, Mass., 
and eToys, of Santa Monica, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Srikant Srinivasan, founder and CEO of KBkids.com, said  
Consolidated put $80 million into the Internet business and will 
spend $50 million promoting the Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	``By Christmas we expect to be the leader in toy sales,''  
Srinivasan said. 
</P>
<P>
	BrainPlay.com has been around for two years and was the No. 2  
online toy retailer last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Srinivasan said a child who doesn't like a gift bought over the  
Internet can take it back to a store and get something else. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's something the others can't do,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Margaret Whitfield, an analyst for the brokerage firm Tucker  
Cleary, said KB is unique because up to 30 percent of its products 
are close-outs. 
</P>
<P>
	``They buy it cheap and mark it up and sell it at a nice  
profit,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitfield said Internet sales will help make up for  
Consolidated's early losses this year from revenue problems with 
Odd Lots, the close-out business, and the seasonality of the toy 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Consolidated this week reported a net loss of $8.1 million, or  
seven cents per share, for the six months ending July 31, compared 
with earnings of $7.3 million, or six cents per share, in the same 
period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitfield believes that by the end of the Christmas season 15  
percent of the toy industry sales will have been done on the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``You got the child's wish list, now you don't have to fight the  
malls,'' she said. ``Plus, it's easier to keep presents a 
surprise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forrester Research of Cambridge, Mass., did a study last  
November that predicted Internet sales ballooning to $108 billion 
in 2003 from $8 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	But not everybody wants to join that trend.  
</P>
<P>
	Joe Prosek, 64, of Warsaw in eastern Ohio, said he has a  
computer but prefers the experience of shopping in a store. 
</P>
<P>
	``I enjoy bringing the grandchildren to get a better idea of  
what they like,'' Prosek said as he shopped at a KB Toy Store in 
Columbus on Wednesday with his grandson, Austin, 7. ``Sometimes 
they have one thing in mind and then see something else they like 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said his grandson, who was busy inspecting the latest Star  
Wars action figures, wouldn't have as much fun browsing an Internet 
site for toys. 
</P>
<P>
	``Austin is more of a hands-on type of guy,'' Prosek said.  

</P>
</TEXT>
