<HEADLINE> Fumes Kill Steel Worker in Michigan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- A steel plant maintenance worker died  
after being overcome by noxious fumes during a routine maintenance 
job this morning and three other workers were hospitalized. 
</P>
<P>
	They had been doing normal maintenance work in a blast furnace  
building at Rouge Steel and were found about 5 a.m. EDT, the 
company said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	A 45-year-old man suffered cardiac arrest after being overcome  
by the fumes, a spokeswoman for Oakwood Hospital and Medical Center 
said. She said two other workers, ages 53 and 44, were in stable 
condition, alert and able to walk around. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit television station WXYZ-TV reported the workers had high  
levels of carbon monoxide in their blood. The hospital would not 
confirm the report. 
</P>
<P>
	Another worker was expected to be released from Henry Ford  
Hospital later today, and a fifth was treated at the plant. 
</P>
<P>
	All are employees of Metro Industrial Contracting Inc., Rouge  
Steel said. Their names were not released. 
</P>
<P>
	The source of the fumes had not been determined, Dearborn Fire  
Chief Jack McArthur said this morning. He said the Occupational 
Safety and Health Administration would investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	The steel plant is in the same industrial complex as the Ford  
Motor Co. Rouge plant, where an explosion killed six workers last 
winter. A small explosion at the steel plant in July injured one 
worker. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
