<HEADLINE> Flammable Children's Robes Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bentley Lingerie is recalling more than 30,000  
children's robes because they fail to meet federal flammability 
standards. 
</P>
<P>
	The robes present a risk of serious burn injuries to children,  
the Consumer Product Safety Commission said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	No injuries have been reported.  
</P>
<P>
	Federal standards require that children's sleepwear be flame  
resistant or self-extinguish if they ignite. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Esleep Junior'' robes in sizes four to 14 were sold for  
about $25 in JC Penney stores nationwide from July 1998 through 
April 1999. They are made of green or blue polyester, with long 
sleeves and patch pockets showing either a pair of bear cubs or a 
sleeping puppy. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers are advised to stop using the robes immediately and  
return them to the store where they were purchased for a refund. 
</P>
<P>
	For additional information consumers can call Bentley Lingerie  
at (888) 330-3803. 

  	   	
</P>
