<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 07:31:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Gene Swap Makes Better Mouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Scientists may have built a better mouse.  
</P>
<P>
	Researchers reported today that they transformed aloof  
laboratory mice into much more social creatures -- even loving ones 
-- by transplanting a single gene, raising the possibility that such 
switches from one species to another can alter behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	The research could lead to new treatments for psychological  
disorders such as autism and schizophrenia that are marked by 
isolation, the Emory University researchers suggested today in the 
journal Nature. 
</P>
<P>
	The work involved mice and prairie voles, a small rodent known  
for its monogamous, social lifestyle and strong bond with mates. 
</P>
<P>
	The scientists bred mice with a prairie vole gene that caused  
the development of receptors that respond to vasopressin, a hormone 
in the brain that affects social behavior, among other things. 
</P>
<P>
	Unaltered male mice put in a cage with a female would sniff her  
briefly and then scamper off to explore. Altered mice would spend 
significantly more time with the female -- and researchers said it 
was quality time. 
</P>
<P>
	``They spent more time with her, smelling her, grooming her and  
generally being nice to her,'' said Larry Young, a psychology 
professor at Emory and leader of the research team. 
</P>
<P>
	The location of the receptors within the brain -- which differs  
greatly in every species examined so far -- is believed to affect 
how most animals interact. The team used mice because their genes 
are easy to manipulate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think there's something about the distribution of receptors  
that gives a species its typical social behavior,'' Young said. 
</P>
<P>
	The scientists began their study observing behavioral  
differences between prairie voles and montane voles, which have 99 
percent identical DNA. 
</P>
<P>
	But while prairie voles are monogamous and spend most of their  
time with their mates and children, montane voles are promiscuous 
and typically abandon their offspring. 
</P>
<P>
	Oberlin College psychology professor Norman Henderson, editor of  
the journal Behavior Genetics, said the study was interesting. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are certain behaviors that are going on in psychotic  
diseases that could possibly be related to this receptor,'' he told 
the Los Angeles Times. 
</P>
<P>
	But he also said it was unlikely that vasopressin works alone to  
mold complex behavior such as human social interaction. 
</P>
<P>
	``We humans inhibit our behaviors a lot,'' Henderson said. ``Our  
brain tells us not to behave in certain ways, even if there is some 
instinct to.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 10:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bengals Can't Sign Top Draft Pick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GEORGETOWN, Ky. (AP) -- The Cincinnati Bengals have failed in  
their latest effort to sign quarterback Akili Smith, their 
first-round draft choice. 
</P>
<P>
	The club and Smith's agent, Leigh Steinberg, are at odds over  
how Smith would earn his money. The Bengals say they have offered a 
six-year deal for nearly $45 million. Under that proposal, Smith 
would average $4.7 million per year for six years if he 
participates in 55 percent of the plays and, as the contract 
progresses, has thrown for 2,500 yards in two of the three prior 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Bengals president Mike Brown said Smith's people don't like the  
performance requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	``They find that absurd, and we find that more absurd that they  
look at it like that,'' Brown said. ``They want us to give 
everything to their guy. We want him to earn some of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides reportedly agree on a $10.8 million signing bonus and  
the total money. 
</P>
<P>
	Steinberg said he had sent a series of proposals to the Bengals  
in an attempt to close the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Bengals negotiator Katie Blackburn said Steinberg is looking for  
a deal that would give Smith $6 million a year if he plays in 55 
percent of the plays and throws for 2,500 yards in just one season. 
</P>
<P>
	The holdout by Smith, the former Oregon star, reaches 21 days on  
Friday. That would be the halfway point of quarterback David 
Klingler's holdout in 1992. Klingler, also a Bengals' first-round 
selection, was also a Steinberg client. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I've learned from that experience. I don't know if  
he has,'' Steinberg said, referring to Brown. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
