<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Talk Show Slaying Trial Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- The man who killed a gay acquaintance  
after the victim revealed a crush on him during a TV taping should 
be convicted of manslaughter and nothing more, his own attorney 
told jurors today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't ask you to set him free. I want you to convict him of  
what he did,'' attorney Jerome Sabbota told jurors. 
</P>
<P>
	He made the comment in his opening statement in the retrial of  
Jonathan Schmitz, accused of second-degree murder for the 1995 
shotgun slaying of Scott Amedure. 
</P>
<P>
	In her statement, Oakland County assistant prosecutor Donna  
Pendergast called the crime ``the epitome of senseless violence and 
destruction, the cold-blooded and unwarranted obliteration of human 
life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She called Schmitz ``a man with a gun, a man with a grudge.''  
She played the 911 call from Amedure's roommate and said Schmitz 
clearly had set out to kill Amedure. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz, then 24, and Amedure, 32, flew to Chicago for the  
taping of an episode of ``The Jenny Jones Show'' on March 6, 1995. 
Amedure, who was gay, revealed his crush on Schmitz to the studio 
audience during the taped segment, which never aired. 
</P>
<P>
	In Schmitz's confession after the shooting three days later, the  
self-described heterosexual told police he had been humiliated on 
national television. 
</P>
<P>
	In the defense's opening argument, Sabbota contended that  
Amedure provoked Schmitz. He argued that a manslaughter conviction 
would be the just outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	After the taping, the defense contends, Amedure's affection  
turned into an obsession that frightened Schmitz. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happens is that Scott Amedure lights a fuse and every  
time that fuse starts to flicker out, Scott Amedure relights it,'' 
he told jurors. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz was convicted of second-degree murder at his first trial  
in 1996, but the verdict was thrown out because of errors made by 
the judge. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first trial, Schmitz's lawyers argued that mental illness  
and ambush tactics of the Jones show pushed him into a rage that 
led to the killing. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge in the new trial has ruled that the defense won't be  
allowed to present evidence of Schmitz's extensive history of 
mental illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Michigan law, diminished mental capacity cannot be used as  
a defense against a charge of second-degree murder. Such a defense 
was allowed in the first trial because the original charge then was 
first-degree murder. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate civil case, a jury in May found the show and its  
corporate owner, Warner Bros., negligent and ordered them to pay 
$25 million in damages to Amedure's relatives.	   Ms. Jones, who testified during Schmitz's first criminal trial 
and the civil trial, is not being called as a witness for the 
retrial. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
