<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer: Amedure Provoked Killer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- A man went on trial Thursday for the  
second time on charges he killed a gay acquaintance after the 
victim revealed a crush on him during a TV taping of a talk show. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense lawyer for Jonathan Schmitz said the gay man, Scott  
Amedure, was to blame because he pursued his client to the point 
that Schmitz ``lost it'' three days after the taping of ``The Jenny 
Jones Show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What happens is that Scott Amedure lights a fuse and every  
time that fuse starts to flicker out, Scott Amedure re-lights it,'' 
Jerome Sabbota said in his opening statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz was convicted of second-degree murder in 1996 and  
sentenced to 25 to 50 years in prison. But an appeals court 
overturned the verdict, saying the judge was wrong to bar defense 
lawyers from removing a juror before the trial began. 
</P>
<P>
	During the first trial, Schmitz was charged with first-degree  
murder, allowing him to claim he was mentally ill at the time of 
the shooting. But in this trial he is charged with second-degree 
murder and under Michigan law not permitted to use a mental illness 
defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors contend Schmitz calmly bought ammunition and a  
shotgun before shooting the defenseless Amedure twice in his home 
in March 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The crime was ``the epitome of senseless violence and  
destruction, the cold-blooded and unwarranted obliteration of human 
life,'' Oakland County Assistant Prosecutor Donna Pendergast told 
jurors Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz and Amedure flew to Chicago for the taping of a Jenny  
Jones segment about secret same-sex crushes on March 6, 1995. 
Amedure revealed his crush on Schmitz to the studio audience during 
the show, which was taped but never aired. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabbota claims Schmitz was humiliated, and that Amedure later  
pushed him over the edge by leaving a suggestive note in Schmitz's 
front door. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate civil case, an Oakland County jury in May found  
the show and Warner Bros. negligent and ordered them to pay $25 
million in damages to Amedure's relatives. Warner Bros. is 
appealing that decision. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
