<HEADLINE> Kim Perrot Was a Feisty Competitor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Kim Perrot and Teresa Weatherspoon battled each  
other from college all the way to the WNBA. 
</P>
<P>
	Weatherspoon recalls playing feisty games against Perrot and Sun  
Belt Conference rival Southwestern Louisiana in the late 1980s. The 
two point guards were adversaries during the game, but always 
shared a hug and a smile afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	Perrot, the popular Houston Comets point guard, died Thursday of  
lung cancer. She was 32. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been hard,'' said Weatherspoon, who learned of Perrot's  
death before taking the floor Thursday night with the New York 
Liberty. ``She had been keeping in touch with me, and I had been 
keeping in touch with her. But I just learned of her passing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perrot went on to lead the nation in scoring (30.1 ppg) during  
her senior year and set 26 school records for the Ragin' Cajuns. 
Her most memorable basketball moment came when she scored 58 points 
against Southeastern Louisiana in a double-overtime game. 
</P>
<P>
	Weatherspoon, who played at Louisiana Tech, and Perrot renewed  
their friendly rivalry in the professional ranks. Perrot was second 
in voting behind Weatherspoon for the 1998 WNBA defensive player of 
the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Not bad for a 5-foot-5, 130-pound dynamo from Lafayette, La.,  
called ``Kim-Bim'' by her family. 
</P>
<P>
	The Liberty had a moment of silence after a recent practice to  
pray for Perrot and most players were informed of Perrot's death 
before their game against the Cleveland Rockers. 
</P>
<P>
	New York's Kym Hampton sang the national anthem Thursday night  
as the rest of the Liberty embraced at center court, wiping away 
tears. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
