<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Museum Glance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Computer Museum of America's display collection includes:  
</P>
<P>
	-- 1920 Comptometer, ``The Machine Gun of the Office,'' one of  
the first machines that could calculate faster than accountants, 
many of whom could add four columns of figures at a time. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1950s Hollerith Manual Card Punch, built by American inventor  
Herman Hollerith, who in an effort to win the U.S. Census Bureau 
competition, began experimenting with mechanical tabulation 
methods. In 1884, he patented the first ``Census Machine,'' which 
was used to tabulate the 1890 U.S. Census. He improved the 
machines, incorporating the tabulator and punched cards, and built 
an international clientele which included railway offices, the 
Czarist government of Russia, department stores and insurance 
offices. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1963 Royal Precision Vacuum Tube Computer, representing the  
end of the vacuum tube era. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1966 Digital Development Corporation Drum Memory Disk, a  
primitive forerunner to today's hard disk drives. The 3 1/2-foot-tall 
drum rotated 3,600 times per minute and once it reached its 
operational temperature, it had to cool down for three hours before 
the cover could be opened. The device has 1,024 individual read and 
write heads, compared to current single-head drives, and a 
data-transfer of 60 characters per second. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1968 Hewlett Packard Computing Calculator, one of HP's highly  
successful engineering tools, programs were entered by magnetic 
program card. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Early 1970's DEC PDP 8/E Minicomputer, this minicomputer was a  
mainstay in the smaller computer environment which was emerging to 
challenge the stranglehold which mainframes had on computing. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Mid-1970s, MITS Altair 8800 computer, considered the first  
commercially available microcomputer. Ed Roberts, who got out of 
the computer business in 1977 and returned to medicine, sold the 
machines usually as mail-order kits from the MITS factory in 
Albuquerque, N.M. Instead of a keyboard, it was operated with a 
series of 25 toggle switches. The name Altair apparently was the 
suggestion of Roberts' daughter, who said it was the name of a 
planet on a Star Trek episode. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1975, Paul Allen and Bill Gates, then a student at Harvard,  
wrote a programming language to run on the Altair, a scaled down 
version of BASIC, and thus began Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Mid-1970's Apple, Atari, IBM, Commodore, and Amiga PCs  

</P>
<P>
	 *Source: The Computer Museum of America    	



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 17:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
