<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alcoa Wins Bid for Reynolds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Alcoa Inc., the world's largest maker of  
aluminum, reached agreement to acquire No. 3 Reynolds Metals Inc. 
for more than $4 billion Thursday. But the deal disappointed Wall 
Street because it was only slightly better than Alcoa's initial 
hostile bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of both companies tumbled, reducing the value of the  
all-stock transaction to $4.34 billion from $4.45 billion. Alcoa's 
initial bid, made Aug. 11, was $4.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Reynolds accepted Alcoa's unsolicited advances over those of  
Michigan Avenue Partners, a little-known Chicago investment group, 
after Alcoa threatened to take its bid directly to Reynolds 
shareholders. But Reynolds also won a concession from Alcoa that 
gives it 30 days to solicit a better offer and Michigan Avenue 
Partners refused to step aside from the bidding. 
</P>
<P>
	Reynolds agreed to be acquired for 1.06 shares of Alcoa stock  
for each of its shares, which was valued at $70.88 3/4 when the deal 
was announced. 
</P>
<P>
	That was at the bottom end of analysts' estimates that Reynolds  
was worth $70 to $80 a share. By end of trading Thursday, Alcoa 
stock had dropped 2.5 percent, reducing the value of the offer to 
$69.09 7/8 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the confusion, Reynolds has a month to seek a better  
deal, but would have to pay Alcoa $100 million if it walks away 
from Alcoa, said Alain J. P. Belda, Alcoa's president and chief 
executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan Avenue Partners said it would continue to pursue  
Reynolds, according to Dow Jones Newswires. Michael Lynch, the 
chairman of the real estate investment group, did not immediately 
return repeated telephone calls from The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The real estate investment group entered the metals industry  
last year with the purchase of a Reynolds plant in McCook, Ill., 
and has purchased about $1 billion in aluminum assets in the past 
18 months. It has yet to disclose the terms of its offer but has 
questioned whether an Alcoa-Reynolds merger will survive an 
antitrust review. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal that would create a company with annual sales of $20.5  
billion, about 120,000 employees and operations in 36 countries. It 
would control more than one-sixth of the world's aluminum 
production. 
</P>
<P>
	It also would unite two storied companies.  
</P>
<P>
	Alcoa, the world's oldest aluminum manufacturer, made engine  
parts for the Wright Brothers' plane. Reynolds was instrumental in 
marketing the first aluminum soda cans and later created flip tops 
that stay with cans after opening. 
</P>
<P>
	Belda said Alcoa would preserve Reynolds' brand name. ``Reynolds  
Wrap is the Coca-Cola of the foil business,'' said David Moison, an 
analyst with Metals Research Inc. of suburban Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators likely will be concerned whether the merger will mean  
higher prices for consumers or for Alcoa's and Reynolds' customers, 
said Steve Newborn, a former mergers attorney for the Federal Trade 
Commission who now heads of the antitrust division at the Rogers &AMP; 
Wells law firm in Washington. And the manufacturers' customers -- 
makers of everything from cola cans to automobiles and jet planes -- 
may balk if prices go up. 
</P>
<P>
	``Alcoa is likely to encounter headwinds with the  
trustbusters,'' said Moison, the Metals Research analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the merged company will own three-fifths of the  
equipment that turns bauxite into alumina in the United States and 
Canada. Alumina, when charged with electricity during smelting, 
becomes aluminum. 
</P>
<P>
	Pittsburgh-based Alcoa and Richmond, Va.-based Reynolds said  
they hope the takeover will be completed by year's end. Reynolds' 
shareholders also must approve the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The aluminum industry is consolidating following a decade of  
troubles. Companies in the former Soviet Union flooded the market 
with aluminum as they sought foreign currency, pushing prices down. 
The financial crisis in Asia, Russia and Latin America depressed 
the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Worldwide, the capacity to make aluminum far exceeds the demand,  
said Robert Dammon, a finance professor at Carnegie Mellon 
University in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokeswomen for both companies had no comment on the prospect of  
job cuts or plant closings, but there were expectations that 
payrolls would be trimmed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason that they're merging is to consolidate operations,  
and you are going to have plant closings and layoffs. It is going 
to happen,'' said Dammon. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcoa went public with its unsolicited bid for Reynolds on Aug.  
11, shortly after No. 2 aluminum maker Alcan Aluminium Ltd. of 
Canada reached an agreement to merge with two European rivals to 
create a company with about $21 billion in annual sales, about the 
same size as a combined Alcoa and Reynolds. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcoa fell $1.68 3/4 to $65.18 3/4 a share Thursday on the New York  
Stock Exchange, where Reynolds fell 3.9 percent, or $2.68 3/4, at 
$65.56 1/4. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
