<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Moesha' Actor Is Fined $450 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Lamont Bentley, who appears on UPN's  
``Moesha,'' has been fined $450 for his role in a disturbance 
outside a nightclub. 
</P>
<P>
	Bentley, a 25-year-old Milwaukee native who lives in North  
Hollywood, Calif., pleaded guilty to disorderly conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	The confrontation took place after a celebrity basketball game  
Aug. 1. A man who attended the event with Bentley argued with 
officers and was arrested after he became loud and profane, police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bentley approached and allegedly told police, ``You can't arrest  
him. If you're going to arrest him, you're going to have to arrest 
me, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``At this, the crowd became inflamed,'' police said.  
</P>
<P>
	Officers handcuffed Bentley, who struggled, according to police.  
</P>
<P>
	Bentley plays Hakeem on the TV show.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 23:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Insiders Can Beat the System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It was an official document called a  
suspicious activity report, which banks and other financial 
institutions are required to file with federal authorities when 
employees detect unusually large deposits or transfers or other 
aberrations. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of New York Co. is believed to have filed the report  
sometime after federal authorities began investigating accusations 
that Russian mobsters holding accounts at the bank may have used it 
to launder billions of dollars. British authorities reportedly 
alerted the FBI to suspected money laundering at the bank more than 
a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank's report was one of more than 150,000 suspicious  
activity reports filed by U.S. banks, thrifts and credit unions 
since the federal requirement went into effect about two years ago. 
The reports are submitted to the Treasury Department's Financial 
Crimes Enforcement Network, known as FinCen, and shared with law 
enforcement authorities and the federal bank regulatory agencies, 
such as the Federal Reserve and the Office of the Comptroller of 
the Currency, which oversees nationally chartered banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet despite the new national system, and vigilance by financial  
institutions, bank insiders bent on money laundering or other 
criminal pursuits still can beat the system, experts say. 
</P>
<P>
	``What really gets tough is when people on the inside compromise  
the system,'' Bert Ely, a banking industry consultant based in 
Alexandria, Va., said Thursday. ``Any time people get inside help, 
it's tougher for the bank to detect activities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said questions likely will be raised about Bank of New York's  
procedures for screening customers following a New York Times story 
that as much as $10 billion was laundered through the nation's 
15th-largest bank in what investigators say is an operation run by 
Russian organized crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Some $4.2 billion passed through a single account in more than  
10,000 transactions between October and March, the Times reported 
Thursday, citing unidentified investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank has suspended two senior officers in its Eastern  
European division pending the outcome of the investigation, but 
said the case appeared to be an isolated incident. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bank of New York has been cooperating with the office of the  
U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York in the 
confidential investigation of the use of bank facilities to 
transfer funds from Russia to other countries,'' the bank said in a 
statement, adding that no funds were lost and there were no 
allegations of wrongdoing by the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	It declined to provide further details.  
</P>
<P>
	Big U.S. banks and foreign nationals have been involved in other  
recent cases: 
</P>
<P>
	--Officials at Citigroup, the nation's largest bank, violated  
their own money-laundering controls in helping the brother of 
former Mexican president Carlos Salinas de Gortari move as much as 
$100 million in alleged drug money out of the country, 
congressional investigators concluded in December. 
</P>
<P>
	--BankBoston Corp. disciplined 20 employees last summer for  
negligence in connection with the case of fugitive former bank 
executive Ricardo Carrasco, a Uruguayan citizen accused of 
embezzling $73 million by making fraudulent loans. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you have insider complicity ... you can go a long way if  
you want to abuse a financial institution,'' said Charles Intriago, 
publisher of Money Laundering Alert, a monthly publication. 
</P>
<P>
	The system of requiring banks to file suspicious activity  
reports with the government isn't ``infallible,'' Intriago 
maintained, though it has improved efforts to suppress money 
laundering. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials view money laundering as the Achilles' heel  
of organized crime -- the need to convert illegal and unusable 
proceeds into usable funds. An estimated $57 billion in illicit 
proceeds is laundered through banks each year by drug traffickers 
and other criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury officials say the system of suspicious activity reports  
has made a strong start, and has banking industry support. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials of the American Bankers Association weren't available  
for comment on the matter Thursday. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
