<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Derby-Preakness Winner Cracks Leg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- Winning the Breeders' Cup Classic  
is a tough assignment. This year, just getting to the race seems to 
be even tougher. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest star to fall is Real Quiet.  
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner who also captured  
the Pimlico Special and Hollywood Gold Cup is out for the year with 
a cracked bone in his right front leg. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, injury ended the careers of Charismatic, this year's  
Derby-Preakness winner; Victory Gallop, winner of 1998 Belmont 
Stakes and of the Whitney Handicap on Aug. 1 at Saratoga, and Free 
House, winner of the 1998 Pacific Classic and this year's Santa 
Anita Handicap. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver Charm, Real Quiet's Bob Baffert-trained stablemate,  
winner of the Derby and Preakness in 1997 and the Dubai World Cup 
in 1998, was retired in June after a fourth straight loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether the 4-year-old Real Quiet will join them in retirement  
is not known. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a little crack in the splint bone in the right front  
leg,'' Baffert said Thursday from Del Mar in California. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he's been told the injury should heal fine, but ``we'll  
wait 90 days and see how it looks. He's finished for this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert said the injury was discovered after Real Quiet worked  
seven furlongs Sunday at Santa Anita. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a little filling, and X-rays showed a little crack  
at the top of the splint bone,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Real Quiet, who won the Hollywood Gold Cup in his last start  
June 27, was scheduled to start next in the Pacific Classic on Aug. 
29 at Del Mar, then run in the $4 million Breeders Cup Classic 
</P>
<P>
	When Real Quiet, owned by Mike Pegram, is retired, he will stand  
at stud at The Vinery in Kentucky. Purchased for $17,000, Real 
Quiet has won six of 20 starts and has earned $3,271,803. 
</P>
<P>
	Pegram also owns the Baffert-trained Silverbulletday. The two  
men are to arrive in Saratoga Springs tonight to watch the prized 
3-year-old filly run in the Alabama on Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
