</P>
<P>
	Settlement for Tobacco Growers OKd  
</P>
<P>
	RALEIGH (AP) -- A judge approved a court settlement with  
cigarette companies today that could give the nation's tobacco 
farmers and quota owners more than $5 billion over the next 12 
years. The so-called Phase II settlement is intended to help 
farmers and allotment holders -- people granted the right by the 
federal government to grow a certain amount of tobacco -- in 14 
tobacco-producing states deal with the fallout from a $206 billion 
national settlement between the cigarette companies and the states. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Bank Giants Might Team Up  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- In what analysts said could be the start of a new  
series of shakeups in Japan's financial industry, three of the 
country's top banks said they are considering an alliance that 
would create the world's largest banking group. Industrial Bank of 
Japan Ltd., Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd. and Fuji Bank Ltd. each 
confirmed they are considering a three-way combination. Japan's 
financial industry has seen big changes in recent years since the 
government began deregulation, aiming to make Tokyo a financial 
center by opening it up to greater competition. 

</P>
<P>
	Chase Cuts 32 Jobs in New York  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Bank has closed its U.S. equity  
management department in New York, eliminating 32 jobs, as the 
nation's third-largest bank tries to streamline its operations. 
Chase, which has divided its $39 billion U.S. equity management 
business between offices in New York and Houston, will shift all of 
the operations to Houston. The development fueled more rumors about 
an eventual merger between Chase and Merrill Lynch. Merrill Lynch, 
the nation's largest stock brokerage firm, has a $309 billion U.S. 
asset management business. Stock in Chase Manhattan Corp. closed 
down 2 9/16 at 82 7/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Barnes &AMP; Noble Earnings Rise  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc.'s second-quarter earnings  
rose from a year ago, boosted by strong results at its giant 
bookstores. The company reported today that its operating earnings 
were $9 million, or 8 cents a share, in the quarter ended July 31, 
compared with a loss of $9.68 million, or 8 cents a share, a year 
earlier. The 1999 results exclude a $36 million gain in the quarter 
that came from the May initial public stock offering of 
barnesandnoble.com, in which Barnes &AMP; Noble holds a 40 percent 
share, and the partial sale of Chapters Inc. Stock in Barnes &AMP; 
Noble fell 5/8 to 24 1/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Nestle, Haagen-Dazs in Venture  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The makers of Haagen-Dazs frozen desserts and  
Drumstick ice cream bars are combining their U.S. ice cream 
operations in a new joint venture designed to increase sales. 
Pillsbury Co. and Nestle USA will retain ownership of the brands 
and production technology and license them to the joint venture, 
which has been temporarily named Ice Cream Partners USA. The new 
company will continue to use the popular brand names of Haagen-Dazs 
for its premium ice cream and frozen yogurt, and the Drumstick, 
Nestle Crunch and Butterfinger brands for its ice cream bars. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Drug Co. Exec To Plead Guilty  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A former Swiss pharmaceutical company  
executive agreed today to plead guilty and serve six months in jail 
for his role in a worldwide case of vitamin price-fixing, the 
Justice Department announced. This was the 10th prosecution in the 
case in which the company, F. Hoffmann-La Roche, already has been 
sentenced to pay a record $500 million criminal fine. Hoffmann-La 
Roche and some of its competitors have admitted they raised and 
fixed prices and allocated market shares for vitamins used by 
Americans and added to bread, milk and breakfast cereal. 

</P>
<P>
	Virus May Hit Computers on Christmas  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A computer virus timed to strike Windows PCs on  
Christmas Day has yet to pose a significant threat because of its 
low prevalence, but anti-virus software makers are gearing up to 
help computer users combat it. The new virus, named W32/Kriz.3862, 
is designed to damage Windows 95, Windows 98 and Windows NT 
machines. The virus overwrites data on hard drives and destroys the 
memory that stores a computer's setup, sometimes making a computer 
unbootable. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Trade deficit: up 16.3 percent to $24.6 billion  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: up 4,000 to 287,000  

</P>
<P>
	AP Financial NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  



  	   	
</P>
