<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Official Resigns After Booze Cruise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Citing his ``errors in judgment,'' the head of the  
state Port Authority has resigned following his trip on a ``booze 
cruise'' paid for by his agency during which a woman bared her 
breasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Photographs of the four-hour party boat cruise were published in  
Wednesday's Boston Herald, which said its reporters saw agency 
chief Peter Blute and lobbyist Sandy Tennant, who once headed the 
state Republican Party, drinking beer and champagne. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the harbor tour, a female passenger lifted her  
shirt, eliciting whoops and hollers from other passengers, the 
newspaper said. The Herald published a photo of the woman with her 
shirt raised, blacking out the section of the photo showing her 
breasts. 
</P>
<P>
	A source close to Massport, speaking on condition of anonymity,  
told The Associated Press that Blute, a former congressman, was not 
on deck when the woman bared her breasts. 
</P>
<P>
	In his letter of resignation to Gov. Paul Cellucci, Blute wrote,  
``Recent errors in judgment by myself have called into question my 
ability to remain as executive director of this authority.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cellucci said he supported Blute's departure, saying he  
``exercised bad judgment and acted inappropriately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The authority, commonly known as Massport, oversees Logan  
International Airport and the Port of Boston and has annual revenue 
of $330 million. Blute, who was appointed in 1997 by former Gov. 
William Weld, made $120,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennant said he was on the cruise to help Maureen Stemberg,  
ex-wife of Staples office-supply founder and Republican fund-raiser 
Thomas Stemberg, plan a fund-raiser for a cancer charity. 
</P>
<P>
	Massport spokesman Jeremy Crockford said Massport reserved the  
boat, and paid $834 for the charter, with the understanding that 
Ms. Stemberg would repay the agency. In the meantime, Blute wrote a 
personal check Wednesday to reimburse Massport, Crockford said. 
</P>
<P>
	He showed up for the cruise bringing three young women in his  
white Mercedes. Tennant, whose license was revoked for 120 days 
after a May 20 drunken driving arrest, said he wasn't driving. The 
arrest was particularly embarrassing for Tennant since it happened 
shortly after he had challenged Texas Gov. George W. Bush at a 
fund-raiser about his past drinking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
