<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chase Cuts 32 Jobs in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Bank has closed its U.S. equity  
management department in New York, eliminating 32 jobs, as the 
nation's third-largest bank tries to streamline its operations, 
according to company executives. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase, which has divided its $39 billion U.S. equity management  
business between offices in New York and Houston, will shift all of 
the operations to Houston. Henry Lartigue, executive vice president 
and chief investment officer for Chase Bank of Texas, will oversee 
the combined asset management business. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the grand scheme of things, it's not a big deal for the  
bank,'' said Diane Glossman, an analyst at Lehman Brothers. She 
added, however: ``There are some people reading into it that it 
would speed the concept of an acquisition of Merrill Lynch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A merger between Chase and the Merrill Lynch ``has been rumored  
a thousand times,'' she said. A deal between the two companies 
``makes strategic sense, but it all depends on the price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch, the nation's largest stock brokerage firm, has a  
$309 billion U.S. asset management business based in Princeton, 
N.J. Both companies invest money for wealthy individuals, pension 
funds and mutual funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies declined to comment.  
</P>
<P>
	David Klassen, head of U.S. equities for Chase in New York, was  
the most senior executive to lose his job in the shakeout. A call 
to his office was not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Chase fell $2.56 1/4 to $82.43 3/4 on the New York Stock  
Exchange. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
