<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bob Dole Quietly Helps Wife's Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- He's tapping at the door, but Elizabeth Dole's  
campaign is not quite ready to let Bob Dole in. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 GOP presidential nominee has been quietly working the  
telephone to drum up money and political organizers for his wife, 
Elizabeth, and her 2000 presidential race. 
</P>
<P>
	``She wants to make sure everybody knows this is HER campaign  
... not a co-presidency thing,'' the former senator, now a 
lobbyist, said in an interview Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Being purposefully kept out of her spotlight, he flew solo at  
small-fund raisers in far-flung Iowa outposts leading up to last 
weekend's Iowa straw poll. There, he stood by his wife's side and -- 
for the most part -- courted voters with just a smile, a handshake 
and a quip. 
</P>
<P>
	The former GOP presidential nominee spoke most admiringly of how  
his wife pulled off a strong third-place showing in the straw poll, 
despite being outspent four or five times over by Texas Gov. George 
W. Bush and millionaire businessman Steve Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hear they're giving her the Scrooge award for spending the  
least,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke almost longingly for the campaign trail, for a piece of  
the action. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever somebody blows a whistle, I'll be there,'' he said,  
pointing out that his wife has some 25 fund-raising appearances 
scheduled over the next 45 days. ``Hopefully, I'll be able to do 
some of these for her just as she did some for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One campaign official responded with a firm ``not likely.''  
While Sen. Dole remains enormously popular among many Republicans, 
contributors come to fund-raisers to see the candidate, this 
official said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, the former senator is offering his wife comfort  
after a long day on the stump. ``She came home Monday and we 
watched a movie,'' he recalled with a genial chuckle. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, I've seen 'em all, sitting in hotel rooms all day.  
Maybe pretty soon I can start showing up (at her events) more.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 14:10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IAAF Tightens Nationality Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Concerned that richer nations are luring  
away athletes from poorer countries, track and field's governing 
body voted Thursday to tighten rules concerning nationality. 
</P>
<P>
	While previously needing only to live in a country in order to  
be eligible to compete under its flag, athletes must now acquire 
full citizenship of their adoptive nation. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, athletes will only be able to represent their  
adoptive land if they have not competed for their former country 
for at least three years. 
</P>
<P>
	``There must be three years since the date you last represented  
the first country at World Championships, Olympic Games and a 
number of other events, including World Cup, before you can 
represent your new country at the same level,'' IAAF general 
secretary Istvan Gyulai said. ``This can be, if both federations 
concerned agree, reduced to one year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gyulai said certain exceptional situations, as in the case of  
refugees, would be reviewed by the IAAF council on an individual 
basis. 
</P>
<P>
	Once a popular way to switch countries, marriage will no longer  
provide a loophole. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are cases of marriages of convenience,'' Gyulai said.  
``In one year we suddenly saw 10 athletes all marry and move to the 
same country ... I won't say which country. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no special rule for marriage. If you acquire  
citizenship through marriage, it is the same as if you acquire 
citizenship through any other means.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gyulai said country-swapping had become a worrisome trend, with  
more and more athletes deserting the countries which had fostered 
and developed them. 
</P>
<P>
	Pole-vaulter Victor Chistiakov, who recently traded his Russian  
passport for an Australian one and had not represented Russia for 
the last three years, has opted to compete under Australia's colors 
at the upcoming World Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson Kipketer, the 800-meter world record-holder, left Kenya  
after being recruited by a club director looking for runners for 
his Danish team. Kipketer obtained full Danish citizenship last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Moroccan Khalid Khannouchi, a two-time champion of the Chicago  
marathon, and Mebrahtom Keflezighi of Eritrea, who finished fourth 
in the 10,000-meters at the U.S. Championships in June, are both 
campaigning to compete for the United States at the Olympic Games 
in Sydney next year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 10:58:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Doesn't Rule Out Taiwan Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- China hopes the current tensions with Taiwan  
will be resolved peacefully but ``we cannot rule out the force 
option,'' China's ambassador to the United States said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Li Zhaoxing cautioned the United States against interfering in  
what China views as an internal matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent comments by members of Congress suggesting that the  
United States increase its defense ties with the island are ``very 
dangerous statements,'' Li told a news conference at the Chinese 
Embassy. 
</P>
<P>
	While reiterating Beijing's hard line on Taiwan, Li was  
generally positive on U.S.-Chinese relations in advance of 
President Clinton's meeting next month with Chinese President Jiang 
Zemin in New Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	Li suggested that negotiations over reparations for the U.S.  
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade in May were progressing. 
And he expressed hopes that remaining U.S. obstacles to China's 
entry into the World Trade Organization would soon be resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Chinese official showed little flexibility on the issue  
of Taiwan and had harsh words for Taiwanese President Lee Teng-Hui. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee's comments on July 9 that Taiwan and the mainland should  
have ``state-to-state'' relations set off the current tempest. 
</P>
<P>
	China views Taiwan as a renegade province.  
</P>
<P>
	Li called the Taiwanese president a ``troublemaker'' and  
suggested Lee had made his ``state-to-state'' comments in a 
deliberate attempt to drive a wedge between China and the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	``He should stop his state-to-state (statements) otherwise he  
will go down in history as a national traitor,'' Li said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very serious and dangerous matter,'' Li said.  
</P>
<P>
	He would not directly answer questions on whether China was, in  
fact, planning a military show of force across the Taiwan Strait. 
But, he said without elaboration, ``The government of China knows 
very well what it should do. 
</P>
<P>
	``China does love peace. We do long for peace. However, we never  
will be cowed by military steps or blackmail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any escalation of tension between China and Taiwan could involve  
the United States, since the 1979 Taiwan Relations Act commits the 
United States to defend China against an attack from the mainland. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot rule out the force option,'' Li said. ``We want to  
prepare ourselves to stop any Taiwan independence or foreign 
intervention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also voiced opposition to any move by the United States to  
provide Taiwan with any type of missile-defense system. 
</P>
<P>
	``China is firmly opposed to the U.S. selling such an advanced  
weaponry system'' to Taiwan, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Li also had sharp words for Japan, expressing alarm at recent  
indications that Japan was considering a missile-defense system in 
conjunction with the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe all people in Asia ... would request Japan to pursue  
the policy of peace. History should be remembered,'' he said. 
``Japan should never forget the catastrophe it imposed on the 
people of Asia and the people of the world.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
