<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Assaults Launched in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Anti-independence fighters in East Timor  
launched new assaults on U.N. and pro-independence targets Thursday 
as others handed in weapons in advance of a referendum to determine 
the future of the troubled territory. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.N. vehicle was damaged when one group threw rocks into a  
churchyard in Suai, 60 miles south of the capital Dili, where more 
than 2,300 displaced villagers were taking shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	In Manatutu, about 40 miles east of Dili, a militia gang  
ransacked the office of the pro-independence organization and fired 
shots into the air. Police said there were no serious injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The incidents were the latest in a series of disturbances before  
the Aug. 30 ballot, in which East Timor's people will decide 
between full independence or staying part of Indonesia as an 
autonomous region. 
</P>
<P>
	Security has become a prime concern. Anti-independence militias  
have been blamed for a wave of violence in recent months that has 
killed dozens of civilians and displaced tens of thousands. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, about 600 militiamen in Dili -- many wearing  
Indonesia's red and white national colors -- surrendered an array of 
guns, explosives and dozens of homemade weapons. Pro- and 
anti-independence fighters have begun surrendering weapons in 
recent days under the eye of the U.N. Assistance Mission in East 
Timor, which is supervising the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Militia leader Eurico Gutteres said his men, accused of past  
violence, would take part in the ballot peacefully. 
</P>
<P>
	``We look forward to the festival of democracy,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia occupied East Timor in 1975 and the former Portuguese  
colony has been wracked by guerrilla warfare and human rights 
abuses since. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
