<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ken Starr May Quit Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Kenneth Starr's imprint would be on a final  
report focusing on President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, even 
though a successor may finish the independent counsel's work, legal 
experts say. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr informed a three-judge panel earlier this month that he  
plans to leave before his office's work is finished, a legal source 
said Thursday, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	``He indicated there were allegations to be prosecuted or  
declined,'' said the source, who is familiar with a conversation 
between Starr and the presiding judge of the special court, David 
Sentelle. ``He brought up this business about retiring. Certainly 
the impression was sooner rather than later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The panel of judges could name a successor to take over Starr's  
office, even though the independent counsel law has expired, 
according to congressional staffers who worked on efforts to renew 
or replace the statute. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC News first reported that Starr was considering leaving in  
the next few months, quoting sources on its Web site Tuesday as 
saying Starr had submitted the resumes of three deputies as 
possible successors. 
</P>
<P>
	As he left his McLean, Va., home Thursday morning, Starr said,  
``I have no comment at this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers who worked on previous independent counsel  
investigations said that if Starr left, his successor likely would 
be a current or former deputy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will either be Ken Starr's report because he stays or Ken  
Starr's report with an asterisk -- 'as told to Ken Starr,''' said 
John Douglass, a law professor at the University of Richmond who 
worked on the Iran-Contra investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Douglass said it ``would be inconceivable to me'' that anyone  
not previously in Starr's office ``would accept the job at this 
time. Why would anybody want it?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno declined Thursday to discuss who  
might take over any unfinished investigations if Starr were to 
resign. ``I'd prefer the Department of Justice to address the 
issues as they arise,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	A department official, requesting anonymity, said that despite  
some ambiguity in the now-expired independent counsel law, it would 
be logical for Starr to ask the three-judge panel that selected him 
to name a successor, as those judges would have done if the law had 
not expired. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional staffers familiar with the law said it was meant  
to provide for a successor to be named even after the expiration. 
Language in the law says even after its expiration, the law ``shall 
continue in effect with respect to then pending matters'' if an 
independent counsel believes the work should be completed. 
</P>
<P>
	However, congressional researchers said there never has been an  
instance when a successor was named at a time the law had lapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	A split on the judicial panel that would make the decision was  
revealed Wednesday when, in a routine, periodic check of the 
probe's status, the judges voted 2-1 to allow Starr's investigation 
to continue. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Monica Lewinsky investigation ended with Clinton's  
impeachment and acquittal in the Senate, Starr issued a statement 
saying his probe was continuing on several fronts. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a matter related to his investigation of the Clintons'  
Whitewater land dealings in Arkansas remains under appeal, and 
noted that the office also is responsible for investigating the 
firing of White House Travel Office employees and whether the White 
House misused FBI background files. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr said Wednesday he was working with the Justice Department  
to determine whether some matters could be referred there. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the topics of Starr's investigations still pose the  
same conflicts for Justice investigators that they did when Reno 
referred them to Starr in the first place, so the cases could not 
come back to Justice, said a department official who would not be 
quoted by name. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph diGenova, the independent counsel who investigated  
allegations that the Bush administration misused State Department 
files, said the report should remain associated with Starr, even if 
he leaves before it's finished. 
</P>
<P>
	``The person responsible for the majority of the investigation  
should be responsible for publication of the report,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Yannett, also a former Iran-Contra prosecutor, said,  
``Whatever the office does, it will be viewed forever as the Starr 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's just one of his deputies filling out the role for  
purposes of the report, it will properly be viewed as the Starr 
report.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 03:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lutherans Mull Pact With Church </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Leaders of the nation's largest Lutheran  
denomination faced a key decision on whether to form a sweeping 
alliance with the Episcopal Church, a move that could affect 
thousands of congregations. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was scheduled for today at the national convention of  
the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America in Denver. If the 
alliance is approved, Episcopalians will vote on it during their 
convention next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the ``full communion'' pact, the churches would recognize  
and share each other's sacraments and clergy and cooperate in 
missionary projects, something supporters say would strengthen the 
ministry and prove helpful in urban and rural areas where church 
resources are scarce. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, the churches have about 7.5 million members in 18,000  
congregations. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike similar pacts the Lutheran group has with three other  
denominations, the agreement -- already supported by the Episcopal 
Church -- requires Lutherans to follow an ordination practice known 
as the historic episcopate: Each bishop is installed by a laying on 
of hands by three predecessor bishops from a line believed to 
extend back to Christ's apostles. 
</P>
<P>
	That has raised opposition within the Lutheran ranks. While  
Catholic and Orthodox churches, as well as Episcopalians, follow 
the practice, Lutheran teachings don't require such historic 
succession. Many of the world's Lutheran bodies do not practice it. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Lutheran delegates narrowly rejected a similar  
pact with the Episcopal Church. During the same convention, the 
delegates approved pacts with the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.), 
Reformed Church in America and United Church of Christ -- none of 
which required changes in Lutheran tradition. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, opponents said the Episcopal Church should be  
willing to take Lutherans as they are without requiring them to 
adopt the historic episcopate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Jaynan Clark-Egland of Bonners Ferry, Idaho, said her  
opposition was ``based on scripture and the freedom of the 
Gospel.'' Bishops are no more sanctified than clergy, she said, and 
clergy no more than the laity. 
</P>
<P>
	Others considered the pact old-fashioned. The Rev. Thomas Lyberg  
of Convoy, Ohio, labeled it a ``political, ecclesiastical 
document'' that envisions ``maintenance to marginal congregations'' 
in both churches, rather than new evangelism. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. James Hanson of Winters, Texas, called the proposal ``a  
move in the wrong direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have so obviously not yet gained wide consensus among  
ourselves,'' declared the Rev. Stephanie Frey of Redwood Falls, 
Minn., who said Lutherans should forget the pact and tend to their 
own internal ``division and woundedness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters said the time had come for a change.  
</P>
<P>
	``We write the final chapter for this century in this  
assembly,'' said President Timothy Lull of Pacific Lutheran 
Theological Seminary in Berkeley, Calif. ``How does it end? With 
whimpering and squabbling that are, woefully, part of the dark side 
of Lutheranism past?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 14:10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Martin Happy To Be Back in Michigan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLYN, Mich. (AP) -- Mark Martin is in second place in the  
Winston Cup standings, but a whopping 300 points behind the leader. 
Little wonder that he's happy to be back at Michigan Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin has won four times at Michigan. Three of those victories  
were in the August race. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale Jarrett has 3,359 points to lead the NASCAR circuit with 13  
races remaining, including Sunday's running of the Pepsi 400 at the 
2-mile super speedway in Michigan's lush Irish Hills region. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett's caution-free run to the finish of the Kmart 400 at  
Michigan on June 13 set a race record with an average speed of 
173.997 mph. Jarrett's speed in that race also set a record for a 
400-mile NASCAR race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could still reel him in, but it's going to take a little  
luck,'' Martin said Thursday during a rain delay in practice for 
the Busch Series NAPA 200, a support race scheduled for Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of Martin's luck so far this season has been bad.  
</P>
<P>
	He still has some pain from the mending fractures he picked up  
July 2 in a stock car crash in Daytona Beach, Fla. And two weeks 
ago, he came one point short of what would have been a fourth 
straight International Race of Champions title. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just drive as fast as I can,'' Martin said. ``That's really  
all I can do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And hope for a little luck.  
</P>
<P>
	``I need to have some better luck than I've had, that's for  
sure,'' Martin said. ``But we'd need for Dale Jarrett to have some 
different luck, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's a tough thing for a proud driver like Martin to swallow.  
He drives for Jack Roush, one of the most competitive owners in the 
business. Teams this strong generally make their own luck. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just deal with it,'' said Martin, who admits to getting  
frustrated. ``You just keep your eye on the target. I learned how 
to do that pretty early in my racing career. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're going to worry, you get mentally exhausted.''  
</P>
<P>
	Still, that doesn't mean Martin cares any less.  
</P>
<P>
	``I definitely have a temper,'' he said. ``I just don't lose it  
as much as I used to. That's the value of the years of experience. 
I have a one-track mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin and Jarrett won't be the only drivers in Sunday's race,  
of course. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Gordon, fresh off last week's road-course victory at  
Watkins Glen, N.Y., also has run well on this track. His pole speed 
of 186.945 mph for this year's June race broke his 1995 record by 
.334 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a whole bunch of people you'd want to keep an eye  
on,'' Martin said. ``I would also include the No. 99 car (Jeff 
Burton) and the 18 (Bobby Labonte).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte is third in the Winston Cup standings with 2,997 points.  
Burton, who also drives for Roush, is fourth with 2,943 and Gordon 
-- the defending champion -- is fifth at 2,877. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon won the August race at Michigan last year on the way to  
his second straight Winston Cup title and third overall. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
