<DOCNO> APW19990819.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 14:10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Won't Stop Ventura Appearance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- There's no law that says Jesse Ventura  
can't be both The Body and The Gov. 
</P>
<P>
	State District Judge Kathleen Gearin refused on Thursday to stop  
the pro wrestler-turned-governor from refereeing some bouts this 
weekend when Ventura's old buddies from the World Wrestling 
Federation come to town. 
</P>
<P>
	A former write-in candidate for governor had sued, alleging the  
referee gig was a conflict of interest for Ventura. The judge gave 
the lawsuit a 10-minute read and dismissed it. 
</P>
<P>
	``An elected official does not by their election become someone  
who does not have personal, social, economic and private 
interests,'' Gearin said. If Minnesotans disapprove, they can oust 
Ventura at the polls, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura said he planned to give his $100,000 fee for refereeing  
to charity. He also is likely to receive at least $1 million in 
video royalties and for the use of his trademarked name. But 
Ventura, known as ``The Body'' when he wrestled, has not said what 
he will do with that money. 
</P>
<P>
	Leslie Davis, the former candidate who sued, said the governor's  
being paid by the WWF might influence decisions he might have to 
make about the organization or the Target Center, where Sunday's 
matches are scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said the governor is covered by Minnesota laws  
prohibiting civil service employees from getting special benefits 
because of their positions. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura's attorney said the Legislature never designated the  
governor a civil service employee. As for the WWF or the Target 
Center, there are no pending issues involving them and the 
governor, the judge said. 
</P>
<P>
	The watchdog group Common Cause Minnesota also filed a complaint  
alleging conflict of interest Wednesday with the Department of 
Employee Relations. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're hoping it will do is impress upon the governor that  
the laws apply to him,'' said Common Cause President David Schultz. 
``It's more directed towards future behavior.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura's spokesman John Wodele called the complaint  
``irritating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The governor obviously is not one out of the conventional  
mold,'' Wodele said. ``Common Cause, other politicians and elected 
officials obviously have some trouble with that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
