<DOCNO> APW19990819.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nestle, Haagen-Dazs in Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The makers of Haagen-Dazs frozen desserts and  
Drumstick ice cream bars are combining their U.S. ice cream 
operations in a new joint venture designed to increase sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Pillsbury Co. and Nestle USA will retain ownership of the brands  
and production technology and license them to the joint venture, 
which has been temporarily named Ice Cream Partners USA. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company will continue to use the popular brand names of  
Haagen-Dazs for its premium ice cream and frozen yogurt, and the 
Drumstick, Nestle Crunch and Butterfinger brands for its ice cream 
bars, said Pillsbury spokeswoman Elizabeth Hanlin. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the future we might see some migration but you won't see  
two logos on one product,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The recipes will remain the same.  
</P>
<P>
	Nestle's Drumstick is the No. 3 brand in the novelty ice cream  
category, while Nestle Crunch vanilla ranked fifth among individual 
novelty items, said Rochelle Brown, director of corporate and brand 
affairs for Nestle USA. Nestle IceScreamers is the No. 2 brand 
among children's frozen novelties. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the 50-50 joint venture, which requires government  
approval, the new company will have its own management team and a 
separate board with four directors each from Nestle USA and 
Pillsbury, but its performance will be reflected in the stocks of 
Nestle S.A., a Swiss company, and Diageo PLC, the British parent of 
Pillsbury. 
</P>
<P>
	The venture includes only the companies' U.S. operations and  
does not include the Haagen-Dazs frozen dessert shops. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company will be located in northern California. Although  
a specific location has not been chosen, the location would take 
advantage of the Haagen-Dazs facility in Tulare and the Nestle 
plant in Bakersfield, the companies said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
