<DOCNO> APW19990819.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 16:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Witness Says he Reimbursed Martin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A defense witness told jurors Thursday he  
reimbursed Miami Dolphins receiver Tony Martin out of his own funds 
for $100,000 in fees paid to a longtime friend's lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Damain Toledo's testimony in the drug and money  
laundering case was met with sharp questioning from prosecutors who 
noted his statements often contradicted what he told a grand jury 
last December. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Opa-locka convenience store owner has been jailed  
since Dec. 4, charged with civil contempt after he refused to 
answer any more questions before the grand jury. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going through what we went through back on Dec. 4,''  
Toledo told assistant U.S. attorney Ron DeWaard at one point. ``I 
felt I was being trapped or having my words twisted. That's why I 
decided to stand on my Fifth Amendment right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin is being tried alongside Rickey Brownlee, who spent seven  
years in prison for two 1980s drug convictions, in a case centering 
on Brownlee's alleged drug activities from 1994 to 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Michael K. Moore recessed proceedings for  
the week, allowing Martin to join teammates in San Diego for 
workouts and an exhibition game against the Chargers. The receiver 
made arrangements to fly out Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll be nice to get away from here and get out on the  
field,'' Martin said as he left the courthouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Toledo's cross-examination will finish Monday, ending Brownlee's  
defense. Three members of the Dolphins, possibly including coach 
Jimmy Johnson, are expected to open Martin's defense as character 
witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin, 33, is accused of leasing three cars in his name on  
behalf of Brownlee, who paid him back with cash. He also is accused 
of writing a $100,000 check to Brownlee's first lawyer in exchange 
for cash. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue is whether Martin, who has known Brownlee since  
childhood and calls him his uncle, knowingly accepted drug money. 
</P>
<P>
	Toledo, whose store was in a building owned by Brownlee, denied  
allegations that Brownlee arranged to repay Martin for the lawyer's 
fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Toledo testified, most of the money came from store  
profits -- in cash -- he had saved up over two years. He said he also 
sold his jewelry and borrowed about $12,000 from another Brownlee 
associate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was trying to get every dime I could,'' Toledo testified.  
``I know I needed to use it for Mr. Brownlee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why he hadn't just obtained a cashier's check himself,  
Toledo said he thought it risky. ``A young minority male walking to 
the bank with $100,000 cash and asking for a check -- that wouldn't 
go over with nobody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin wrote a $100,000 check to lawyer Milton Hirsch in March  
1998, then stopped payment after federal investigators subpoenaed 
his financial records. He repaid the sum to Toledo shortly 
thereafter. 
</P>
<P>
	On cross-examination, DeWaard pulled out a transcript of  
Toledo's brief grand jury appearance and pointed to where Toledo 
had testified the money was Martin's. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as I'm concerned, once I gave the money to Tony, it was  
Tony's,'' Toledo replied. 
</P>
<P>
	The two also clashed over whether Toledo had told the grand jury  
that there was no side agreement for anybody to reimburse Martin or 
merely that Brownlee had nothing to do with repayment. It was at 
about that point that Toledo had ended his grand jury testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to answer the questions truthfully and honestly. I  
went in to do that,'' Toledo told DeWaard. ``But the questions got 
more hostile and I felt my integrity was in question. I didn't want 
to be part of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin's lawyer, Howard Srebnick, later asked Moore to order a  
mistrial or separate the trials. He argued that the heated exchange 
over Toledo's testimony regarding Martin, raised as part of 
Brownlee's defense, could taint jurors' views when it came time to 
judge Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	``Frankly, I don't even know how to go about questioning this  
witness,'' Srebnick told the judge. Moore denied the motion. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
