<DOCNO> APW19990819.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 02:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 19, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Death Toll Keeps Rising in Turkey  
</P>
<P>
	IZMIT, Turkey (AP) -- With the death toll from Tuesday's  
earthquake now beyond 4,000, and with some 10,000 people still 
missing, citizens of Turkey demanded that rescue efforts be 
increased and better organized. The 7.4-magnitude earthquake struck 
the highly populated region before dawn. So far, 3,839 people have 
died and nearly 18,500 were injured, according to a special Turkish 
crisis unit. How many people are still alive under the debris isn't 
known, but the death toll appeared destined to swell as Turkish and 
foreign rescue teams slowly picked their way through the rubble -- a 
task likely to last days. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Crack Down on Suburban Guns  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Federal prosecutors have launched what they  
called the nation's first concerted attack on suburban gun dealers 
who arm city gangs, announcing charges yesterday against 13 buyers 
and sellers. Owners and employees of five suburban gun shops and 
two of the shops themselves were accused of supplying guns to 
``straw purchasers'' with clean police records who were standing in 
for the actual buyers. Authorities say gang members with long rap 
sheets use the method to get around state laws barring convicted 
criminals from buying guns. While handgun sales are illegal within 
Chicago's city limits, officials say the gangs can get them easily 
in nearby suburbs. 

</P>
<P>
	Satellites Measuring Wash. Monument  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington Monument stands a bit taller  
today. A team of government scientists climbed to the top of the 
giant stone spire Wednesday and used the latest in satellite 
technology to take its measure -- 555-feet-5.9 inches. Thats 
four-tenths of an inch more than had previously been recorded. The 
monument was last measured 65 years ago by government surveyors. 
Scaffolding in place for a renovation of the spire gave researchers 
the opportunity to reach the top and take new measurements. 

</P>
<P>
	US, SKorea Resume Military Exercise  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- U.S. and South Korean forces continued  
a joint military exercise today in the world's largest 
computer-simulated war games, intended to train senior officers for 
battle on the Korean peninsula. The 12-day exercise went on for a 
fourth day, after reclusive, Stalinist North Korea made a 
conciliatory gesture, saying it was ready for negotiations to 
resolve international concern over its reported plan to test-launch 
a long-range ballistic missile. Late last night, North Korea said 
it was compelled to develop missiles because the United States 
plans to invade the North, but it was ready for negotiation ``if 
the hostile nations honestly ask for it out of an intention to 
alleviate our concern.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Won't Answer Drug Questions  
</P>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- George W. Bush says he hasn't used illegal  
drugs within the past seven years, while insisting that such 
personal issues have no place in the 2000 presidential race. He 
snapped at reporters asking about possible illegal drug use 
yesterday, saying he would ``refuse to play'' that game. But he 
answered a hypothetical question The Dallas Morning News put to him 
later in the day. The newspaper questioned him about the 
requirement that federal employees answer questions about drug use 
in the past seven years to get high-level security clearances. Bush 
said that he could answer that question with a ``no.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Employers Use Transcripts for Hires  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Youngsters seeking work at more than 10,000  
businesses, from McDonald's to IBM, are finding they cannot hide 
from a spotty academic career: Their high school records are being 
requested by companies worried that poor grades and lax attendance 
may suggest an employment risk. Prospective employers hope they're 
sending a message to high school students and recent graduates that 
school performance and their commitment to learning matter -- even 
in today's job market, where employers are crying for help. ``We 
let standards go down over the years; it's time to get them back to 
where they used to be,'' said John Wentling, the general manager of 
a McDonald's restaurant in Dover, Del. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Slip  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Share prices opened lower Thursday following the  
yen's surge against the dollar overnight. The Nikkei dropped 12.52 
points to hit 17,879.74 in early trading. On Wall Street on 
Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 125.70 points to 
10,991.38. 

</P>
<P>
	Elliott Continues To Recuperate  
</P>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- A brother of Spurs forward Sean Elliott said  
yesterday he had no hesitation about donating a kidney for 
Elliott's transplant and urged others to become organ donors. Noel 
Elliott's kidney was removed in surgery Monday then immediately 
used in his brother's transplant. Sean Elliott, 31, a 10-year NBA 
veteran who helped lead San Antonio to its first NBA championship 
in June, continues to recuperate at Methodist Specialty and 
Transplant Hospital. 


</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
