<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elections Head Indicted in La. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- The state's elections commissioner has  
been indicted on charges he made millions of dollars through 
kickbacks and a money laundering scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	Among that accusations against Jerry Fowler is he funneled  
$900,000 to a New Jersey investment company partly owned by him, 
prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment came in the wake of a legislative audit that said  
Fowler paid more than twice what he should have for voting 
machines, voting machine parts and installation of the machines, 
ignoring the public bid law. 
</P>
<P>
	Fowler could not be reached for comment Thursday. His lawyer  
said the allegations are untrue. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a rather bare-bones indictment,'' Mike Small said.  
``It came as no surprise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The grand jury indicted Fowler on eight counts: four of  
malfeasance in office, three of conspiracy to commit money 
laundering and one of filing false public records. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant District Attorney Sandra Ribes said Fowler avoided the  
state's public bid law and gave contracts to two companies in 
return for kickbacks and personal profits worth millions of 
dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	In one instance, a New Jersey investment firm in which Fowler  
had a financial interest, Independent Voting Machine Service Co., 
was sent $900,000 by Election Services Inc. of Alabama, one of the 
firms awarded a contract by Fowler, Ribes said. 
</P>
<P>
	A legislative audit issued earlier this month found that  
Independent Voting Machine Service Co. and Election Services Inc., 
got a total of $15.4 million from the elections department from 
1991 through 1998 for equipment and services that could have been 
made for less than half the price paid. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the companies also made cash payments of $20,000 a month  
to Fowler, said Ribes, who did not identify the company. 
</P>
<P>
	The grand jury in Baton Rouge earlier indicted 11 people who  
worked for or had done business with the agency in the hauling of 
voting machines. Ten pleaded innocent. One pleaded guilty. 
</P>
<P>
	The audit said Fowler bought 3,200 reconditioned mechanical  
machines without seeking competitive bids required by law. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
