<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IAAF Rejects German Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Track and field's world governing body on  
Thursday rejected a German proposal to scrap some existing world 
records and start a new list in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be no changes,'' said Primo Nebiolo, president of  
the International Amateur Athletic Federation. ``The idea was 
seriously discussed and seemed interesting, but we are not 
following this idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal to throw out records and start afresh in 2000 was  
rejected by ``an overwhelming majority'' of delegates at the IAAF 
Congress, the IAAF said in a written statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The German Athletics Federation had launched the proposal in an  
effort to dispel concerns that existing records were tainted by 
drug use. But most IAAF officials felt such a move would only cast 
suspicion on all records, throwing in doubt their own credibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most believed that such a sweeping change would send out the  
message that the IAAF felt that all its records were doubtful, 
which was unjust to innocent athletes,'' the IAAF said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Germans suggested throwing out records only in certain  
events such as shot-put, discus, javelin and women's sprints, and 
creating a new list starting in the new millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	Some records date back to the 1980s when organized doping  
programs were rampant in East Germany and other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	With court cases in Germany continually exposing evidence of  
systematic doping, pressure is growing for the world of sport to 
restore justice. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the national Olympic committees of the United States  
and Britain filed petitions asking the IOC to award gold medals to 
their swimmers who finished second behind East Germans. The IOC 
rejected the petitions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
