<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees and City Agree on Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Disabled sports fans will have an easier time  
securing good seats at reasonable prices after the federal 
government struck an interim deal with the New York Yankees and the 
city of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal announced Thursday requires the Yankees to  
substantially change ticketing and pricing policies for the rest of 
the season, according to U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White. 
</P>
<P>
	The government had joined a private lawsuit that alleged the  
Yankees and the city had discriminated against the disabled by 
failing to make the ballpark accessible to those who need special 
accommodations. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the club had offered six price levels for the general  
public, including $8 seats, it had required those who needed 
wheelchair seats to pay $26 or $50. The $50 seats were the only 
ones with unobstructed views. 
</P>
<P>
	With the changes, the unobstructed view seats will cost $29 and  
the rest of the wheelchair and companion seating will be sold for 
either $8 or $14, depending on their location. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, those buying wheelchair seats will be able to purchase  
tickets over the Internet, through Ticketmaster or at stadium 
ticket windows. Previously, those needing the seats were required 
to call the Yankees' main office to order tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	``This interim agreement addresses some of the New York Yankees'  
ticketing and pricing policies for fans who use wheelchairs for the 
remainder of the 1999 season, while preserving the government's 
right to seek more comprehensive relief,'' White said. 
</P>
<P>
	A telephone message left with a Yankees spokeswoman was not  
immediately returned. A trial has been set for Dec. 6. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
