<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> LeClair To Return to Philadelphia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Flyers forward John LeClair is close to  
returning to Philadelphia and should not miss any regular season 
games because of his ailing back, his agent said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	LeClair, being treated by a back specialist in Los Angeles,  
probably will return to Philadelphia on Friday night or Saturday, 
agent Lewis Gross said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The doctor gave him a good report,'' Gross said. ``He's doing  
some physical therapy. He hurt it back in March and never really 
did the exercises to get it strong again. When it started bothering 
him a little bit, we thought it was best to go see somebody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LeClair, who described it as a ``minor injury,'' was examined by  
Dr. Robert G. Watkins, the same specialist who treated NBA star 
Scottie Pippen last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a reoccurrence of what happened last spring and I  
didn't want it to be a problem for the upcoming season,'' LeClair 
said. ``I felt it was best to have it looked at now. I'm feeling 
much better. I don't anticipate this being a problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he would be ready to participate in the team's upcoming  
training camp, LeClair said, ``I'm assuming that and I'm planning 
on it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers announced Wednesday that LeClair suffered nerve  
damage doing ``off-ice exercises,'' but did not give specifics. 
Gross said he believes the back pain is not a new injury, but is 
related to back spasms that forced LeClair to miss several games 
late in the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He could have re-aggravated it,'' Gross said. ``But with the  
back, it could be anything. Based on what Dr. Watkins said, he 
should be fine for the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Flyers doctors have not examined LeClair since late last season,  
Gross said. He was limited to 76 games last year, scoring 43 goals, 
after playing all 82 games in three straight seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	In another development Thursday, the agent for first-round draft  
pick Simon Gagne said he was close to agreeing to a three-year 
contract. The deal is expected to be worth $975,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still talking, and we're getting closer and closer,''  
agent Bob Sauve said. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-year contract signed Wednesday by defenseman Karl  
Dykhuis is worth $3 million. He will make $800,000 this season, $1 
million in 2000-2001 and $1.2 million in 2001-2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
