<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Statistics From Annual Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Findings from the 1998 National Household Survey on Drug Abuse:  
</P>
<P>
	--Teens: The portion of teens, ages 12 to 17, saying they ever  
had used drugs fell from 18.8 percent in 1997 to 16.4 percent last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	--Marijuana: Usage has fluctuated over the past few years. Last  
year it fell to 8.3 percent among teens, back to its 1995 level but 
significantly higher than the 3.4 percent recorded in 1992. The 
number of new teen-age users dropped in 1997, the latest statistics 
available for new users. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall use of marijuana was steady in 1998, with about 11  
million Americans smoking it in the month preceding the survey. 
</P>
<P>
	--Heroin: A total of 130,000 people currently were using heroin,  
double the number in 1993. The age of users was dropping. In 1997, 
the typical heroin user was 17.6 years old the first time they 
tried it, down from 18.3 years old in 1996, though not 
significantly different statistically. 
</P>
<P>
	--Cocaine: The number of users was stable in 1998, with about  
1.75 million, though there were increases among teens and young 
adults. 
</P>
<P>
	--Cigarettes: Some 60 million Americans age 12 and older said  
they were current smokers, down from 29.6 percent in 1997. Among 
young adults, the percentage has steadily increased from 34.6 
percent in 1994 to 41.6 percent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	--Cigars: Use increased to 6.9 percent last year, compared with  
5.9 percent in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	--Alcohol: About half of Americans age 12 and older were  
drinkers. Nearly 30 percent of them were binge drinkers, meaning 
they had five or more drinks on the same occasion at least once. 
These statistics have remained steady since 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	--Tobacco: The rate of young adult smoking increased from 34.6  
percent in 1994 to 40.6 percent in 1997 and 41.6 percent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	--Teen-age smoking: Teens who smoked were 11.4 times more likely  
to use illegal drugs and 16 times more likely to be heavy drinkers 
than their non-smoking peers. 
</P>
<P>
	The annual survey is conducted through in-person interviews.  
Interviews are conducted in private, away from other family 
members. People responding to the questions mark their answers on a 
sheet that they seal when the interview is over. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey includes only people who live in households, meaning  
it does not reach the homeless or people living in prisons or 
college dormitories. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 23:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Army To Skip Final Missile Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon is preparing to move to the next  
phase of development of its experimental anti-missile missile, even 
though the weapon has succeeded in only two of eight flight tests. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon announced Thursday that it has dropped its  
self-imposed requirement that the Theater High Altitude Area 
Defense, or THAAD, system score three successful intercepts in 
flight. Instead of conducting another test of the prototype missile 
later this year, the Army's contractor, Lockheed Martin Corp., will 
begin engineering a more advanced version to be fielded by the Army 
in 2007. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last year, when the THAAD program was reeling from six  
straight test failures, the Pentagon said it would not give the 
go-ahead for Lockheed to move into the next phase of development 
until the prototype scored three successful intercepts of mock 
warheads. It recorded its first success in June, followed by 
another Aug. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	THAAD is the centerpiece of the Defense Department's effort to  
provide missile protection abroad for U.S. and allied troops and 
their staging areas. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related development, the Army called off a flight test of  
its Patriot 3 missile interceptor after the missile that was 
supposed to launch as the Patriot's target over White Sands Missile 
Range, N.M., shut itself down just 30 seconds before launch. The 
Army said it didn't know what went wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriot 3 is a new version of the missile interceptor used  
in the 1991 Persian Gulf War; it is intended as a complement to the 
THAAD missile defense system but does not have as great range as 
THAAD. 
</P>
<P>
	Army Maj. Gen. Peter Franklin, deputy director of the Ballistic  
Missile Defense Organization, said the main reason for moving ahead 
with THAAD after two successes instead of three is to force 
Lockheed to focus on the missile interceptor that will actually be 
fielded, rather than the prototype used thus far. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the two successful tests this summer have ``proven''  
that the missile works. Critics, however, said after the second 
successful test in August that the THAAD system should be tested 
against faster, more capable missiles than the Hera rockets used in 
testing at White Sands Missile Range. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rather than spending months and millions of dollars on another  
THAAD prototype launch only to prove a point, we have decided to 
get on with the business of engineering development of the real 
thing,'' Jacques Gansler, the Pentagon's top acquisition official, 
wrote in a letter Wednesday to Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., the 
chairman of the House Armed Services Committee and a supporter of 
THAAD. 
</P>
<P>
	Franklin said a final decision will be made next year on  
beginning the next phase of the project, in which Lockheed Martin 
will translate the design work done thus far into a missile that 
will enter initial low-rate production. The Pentagon is scheduled 
to begin fielding the THAAD system in 2007; Franklin would not say 
whether skipping the final flight test will enable it to be fielded 
earlier than that. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon has spent about $4 billion on THAAD so far.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 21:30:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duke &AMP; Co. Chairman Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The former chairman of Duke &AMP; Co., a now-defunct  
securities firm, pulled off his blue prison shirt as soon as he 
emerged from a courtroom after admitting he cheated investors out 
of tens of millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Victor M. Wang, 34, of Sarasota Fla., was freed on bail Thursday  
after entering pleas in state Supreme Court in Manhattan and U.S. 
District Court in Brooklyn. The firm had operated out of Manhattan 
and Long Island. 
</P>
<P>
	In state court, he calmly answered a prosecutor's questions  
about how his company colluded with sales people at other firms to 
raise and keep artificially high the initial public offering prices 
of certain stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	He admitted that he falsely represented and deliberately omitted  
information given to investors to encourage them to buy securities 
at the inflated prices. Wang pleaded guilty to charges of 
enterprise corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	Late in the afternoon, he pleaded guilty in Brooklyn to  
conspiracy to commit securities fraud and conspiracy to commit 
money laundering, charges which could bring up to 25 years in 
prison and millions in fines and restitution. Sentencing was set 
for Nov. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	Wang was released on $500,000 bond secured by a Long Island  
home. He also must submit to electronic monitoring. 
</P>
<P>
	Wang pleaded guilty to an indictment alleging that Duke was ``a  
criminal enterprise'' that ran a scheme to manipulate the stock 
prices of six companies from January 1995 through March 1998, when 
the company went out of business. 
</P>
<P>
	The six companies whose IPOs were used to defraud investors were  
Renaissance Entertainment Corp., Sel-Leb Marketing Inc., Paravant 
Computer Systems, Bristol Technologies, IFS International, and 
Aviation Group Inc. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 07:38:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russian War Planes Pound Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOTLIKH, Russia (AP) -- Russian war planes and artillery today  
pounded a mountain village that's already been reduced to rubble, 
but determined Islamic militants refused to yield, fighting back 
from amid the ruins. 
</P>
<P>
	The Caucasus Mountains battle between the Russians and the  
rebels has focused for several days on the tiny hamlet of Tando, 
and many of the homes have been destroyed by repeated Russian 
bombing raids. 
</P>
<P>
	But the militants, many of them taking periodic shelter in  
caves, have put up fierce resistance in Tando and other nearby 
villages. The Russian forces suffered their worst single-day losses 
with 18 soldiers killed and at least 20 wounded on Wednesday, the 
Defense Ministry said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the rebels still control at least five villages, including  
Tando, the ministry told the Interfax news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians have lost 40 troops and 160 have been wounded in  
the 13-day conflict, Deputy Interior Minister Lt. Gen. Igor Zubov 
said today. He claimed that up to 500 rebels had been killed, 
though the rebels say the figure is hugely exaggerated. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Russian casualties on Wednesday were paratroopers who were  
hit as they landed in a failed attempt to storm Tando, the 
Kommersant newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	After an overnight lull, government forces resumed bombing raids  
and artillery strikes on Tando early today. The assault was 
witnessed by an Associated Press reporter from the nearby town of 
Botlikh. 
</P>
<P>
	Tando's strategic importance is based on its mountaintop  
location just a few miles from the border with Chechnya, the 
breakaway territory from which the rebels emerged on Aug. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Chechnya is also the source of reinforcements and supplies for  
the rebels, who are fighting for an independent Islamic state in 
southern Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians want to sever the supply line, but most of their  
forces have been restricted to a valley down the mountain from 
Tando, making it difficult to get close to the village, let alone 
storm it. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians believed their daily airstrikes had sufficiently  
weakened the rebels to permit a ground assault, but the militants 
emerged from basements and caves to beat back the government 
troops, Kommersant said. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian officials have repeatedly promised the rebels' imminent  
defeat, but militants still control at least four villages near the 
border with Chechnya. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has been pouring troops and weaponry into the region, and  
is believed to now have several thousand troops in Dagestan, an 
impoverished republic along the west coast of the Caspian Sea. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebel forces are estimated at around 1,200, and include  
fighters from Chechnya and Dagestan as well as Muslims from 
elsewhere in southern Russian. 
</P>
<P>
	The ground fighting around Tando suggests Russia is stepping up  
its campaign against the rebels. Reluctant to take heavy losses, 
Moscow had relied previously on its dominant air power. 
</P>
<P>
	Zubov, the Interior Ministry official, said the sustained  
Russian attacks had forced the rebels to divide up into small 
groups and they were no longer massing in a single location. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have been scattered into smaller groups and are fighting  
federal troops with the use of guerrilla tactics,'' Zubov said. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not explain why the Russian forces had been unable to  
capture Tando or other villages if so few rebels were left to 
defend them. He also claimed that more than 90 percent of the 
population in Dagestan were opposed to the militants. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian forces pulled out of neighboring Chechnya in 1996 after  
a two-year war in which they suffered repeated humiliations at the 
hands of the Chechens. 
</P>
<P>
	Chechnya has had de facto independence since then, but many of  
the former rebels now belong to armed gangs that have made the 
territory ungovernable. 
</P>
<P>
	Criminal groups from Chechnya often cross into neighboring  
regions on kidnapping missions, and the rebel incursion on Aug. 7 
sparked Russia's most serious internal conflict since the end of 
the Chechen war. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 07:38:29 </DATE_TIME>
