<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 07:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trane Recalls Nearly 10,000 Heaters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Almost 10,000 electric heaters were recalled  
Wednesday because of faulty wiring that may cause fires. 
</P>
<P>
	The Consumer Product Safety Commission said some supplemental  
heaters that provide additional warmth for larger home electric 
systems may have defective wiring that doesn't properly control the 
motor. The accessory heaters -- made by the Trane Co. of Tyler, 
Texas, a division of American Standard -- cycle on and off, 
regardless of where the heater has been set. 
</P>
<P>
	That creates a potential fire hazard, said commission spokesman  
Ken Giles. However, no injuries or fires have been reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Trane and American Standard dealers sold the accessory heaters  
from October 1997 until May for $250 to $400. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers should call 888-556-0125 or their local dealer to  
determine if their heater is part of the recall. The company will 
provide free inspection and repair. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990819.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 20:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Johnny Byrne    	
</P>
<P>
	LIVERPOOL, England (AP) -- Johnny Byrne, a guitarist who played  
with Ringo Starr in the pre-Beatles band Rory Storm and the 
Hurricanes, died Wednesday after collapsing at home. He was 59. 
</P>
<P>
	Rory Storm and the Hurricanes was one of Liverpool's most  
popular bands in the years before Beatlemania, but unlike a host of 
other Merseyside bands, it never had a record on the British hit 
charts. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrne and Alan Caldwell, who took the stage name of Rory Storm,  
started playing together in 1957 in a skiffle band called The 
Raving Texans, which combined elements of jazz, blues, country and 
folk. The group became the Hurricanes in 1959. 
</P>
<P>
	With Starr on drums, Rory Storm and the Hurricanes played at the  
Kaiserkeller in Hamburg, Germany, in late 1960, getting star 
billing over The Beatles. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr joined The Beatles in 1962.  
</P>
<P>
	The Hurricanes continued performing until 1967. Caldwell died in  
1972, and Byrne went to work as an ambulance driver the same year. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Dee Fondy    	
</P>
<P>
	REDLANDS, Calif. (AP) -- Dee Fondy, who played for the Chicago  
Cubs, Pittsburgh Pirates and Cincinnati Reds and was the last 
player to bat in Ebbets Field in Brooklyn, died Thursday of 
pancreatic cancer. He was 74. 
</P>
<P>
	Fondy grounded out for the last out at Ebbets Field in  
Pittsburgh's 2-0 loss to the Dodgers on Sept. 24, 1957. The Dodgers 
moved to Los Angeles the following year. 
</P>
<P>
	He hit .286 with 1,000 hits in eight seasons in the majors.  
Following his playing career, Fondy worked as a scout and front 
office official for the New York Mets and Milwaukee Brewers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fondy, a native of Slaton, Texas, served in the Army during  
World War II and was part of the forces that landed on Utah Beach 
in Normandy in 1944, three months after D-Day. He received the 
Purple Heart. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Samuel Joelson    	
</P>
<P>
	HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) -- Former New Jersey Rep. Charles Samuel  
Joelson, who helped President Lyndon Johnson enact his Great 
Society social-welfare reforms, died Tuesday. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1969, the Paterson Democrat successfully pushed a  
congressional spending amendment that provided funding to school 
libraries nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Joelson, elected in 1960, served five terms and became known as  
a civil-rights advocate. He stepped down to become a state Superior 
Court judge. 
</P>
<P>
	Before his election, the Cornell University-trained attorney  
practiced law in Paterson, served as deputy state attorney general 
and a Passaic County prosecutor. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Galen Lemke    	
</P>
<P>
	TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) -- Galen Lemke, a former weapons plant worker  
who became a leading advocate for victims of beryllium disease, 
died Wednesday after a long battle with the illness. He was 58. 
</P>
<P>
	The often fatal disease, which can be treated but has no cure,  
results from exposure to dust from the metal beryllium. The metal 
is a hard, yet lightweight substance used to make nuclear weapons, 
electronics, auto parts and golf clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 1,200 workers have contracted the disease since the  
1940s, including 53 current and former Brush Wellman Inc. workers 
at the company's Elmore plant just outside Toledo, where Lemke 
worked. It is the nation's largest beryllium plant. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemke's struggle to raise awareness about the disease led to an  
investigation by The Blade, which in March published a series of 
stories that said government and industry officials knew for years 
about the dangers of beryllium but allowed workers to be exposed to 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, the federal government for the first time acknowledged  
that workers were made sick from beryllium while making nuclear 
weapons and announced a plan to compensate many of them for medical 
care and lost wages. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemke is survived by his wife, Betty; a daughter and a son.  

</P>
<P>
                            *Kim Perrot    	
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Kim Perrot, the popular point guard who helped  
the Houston Comets win two WNBA championships, died Thursday of 
lung cancer, six months after she was diagnosed. She was 32. 
</P>
<P>
	Perrot died with friends and family by her side at the  
University of Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center, the team said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite her 5-foot-5 frame, Perrot quickly became a starter and  
crowd favorite noted for ferocious play that helped the Comets win 
consecutive championships in 1997 and 1998, the league's inaugural 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year Perrot averaged 8.5 points and 4.7 assists with 84  
steals in 30 regular-season games and was second in voting for WNBA 
defensive player of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	At Monday's game, as her condition worsened, each player wore  
white stickers bearing Perrot's No. 10. Fans wore white ribbons in 
her honor. The game ended with chants of ``Kim, we love you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Lafayette, La., Perrot played four seasons at  
Southwestern Louisiana. She scored 58 points against Southeastern 
Louisiana in 1990, the second-highest total in NCAA history. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Howard Scammon    	
</P>
<P>
	WILLIAMSBURG, Va. (AP) -- Howard Scammon, a former College of  
William and Mary professor whose theater instruction helped launch 
the careers of Glenn Close and others, died Wednesday after a long 
illness. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	A graduate of William and Mary, Scammon joined the college's  
theater and speech department in 1948 and retired as its chairman 
in 1976. He continued to teach there part time for several years. 
</P>
<P>
	Other students of his who went on to success include Linda Lavin  
and Goldie Hawn. 
</P>
<P>
	When she returned to campus 10 years ago to give the  
commencement speech, Ms. Close credited Scammon with giving her the 
advice that she passed on to the graduates: ``Just go out there and 
do it.'' 

</P>
<P>
                             *Eva Shain    	
</P>
<P>
	ENGLEWOOD, N.J. (AP) -- Eva Shain, who helped break the gender  
barrier for boxing judges and went on to score 5,000 fights, died 
of breast cancer Thursday. She was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Shain, of Fort Lee, N.J., earned a reputation as a competent  
boxing judge who blazed a trail for women. But she didn't consider 
herself a pioneer. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't the idea of being a trailblazer. I was thinking  
about me, what I wanted to do,'' Shain said in a 1996 interview 
with The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Jersey City, Shain worked as an interior decorator  
before getting her start in boxing by attending Golden Gloves 
matches with her husband, longtime ring announcer Frank Shain. She 
would score fights privately and then compare the judges scores 
with her own, to see if she was close. She usually was. 
</P>
<P>
	Shain worked amateur fights for eight years and got her  
professional license in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years later, she was a judge for a title fight between  
Muhammad Ali and Earnie Shavers. It was the first time in history a 
woman had judged a heavyweight championship. 
</P>
<P>
	The distinction later landed her in the Guinness Book, Trivial  
Pursuit and on the TV quiz show ``To Tell The Truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shain judged about 5,000 fights, including bouts involving  
Roberto Duran, Hector Camacho, Larry Holmes, Lennox Lewis, Ray 
Mancini, Ali and Mike Tyson, among others. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
