<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian markets closed higher Thursday on  
positive local news, but the big Tokyo exchange fell slightly amid 
worries that Japanese companies would lose overseas earnings from a 
stronger yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average dropped 12.52  
points, or 0.07 percent, to close at 17,879.74. On Wednesday, the 
average rose 0.18 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Worries about overseas earnings of companies kept investors from  
buying heavily into the Tokyo blue chips, said Robert Sasaki of 
Jardine Fleming in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were spooked as they saw the yen rise to seven-month  
highs, a trend that could hurt Japan's exporters by making their 
products less competitive in overseas markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 111.63 yen in afternoon trading, down  
1.45 yen from its level late Wednesday in Tokyo and below its late 
level of 112.03 yen overnight in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares surged 3.2 percent as overseas fund  
managers scooped up selected blue chips. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark Hang Seng Index rose 410.49 points to 13,403.59.  
On Wednesday, the Hang Seng had risen 1.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The markets were flush with cash as foreign buyers overlooked  
interest rate concerns and relaxed their worries about tensions 
between China and Taiwan, said Louis Shum of Emperor Securities 
Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	``The tension between China and Taiwan doesn't seem to be  
worsening,'' said Shum. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong investors have discounted interest rate worries amid  
indications that any rise in U.S. interest rates likely would be 
modest. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares rose 2 percent as investors scooped up banking  
and finance shares. The SET index rose 8.24 points to 418.00. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares rallied 3.6 percent as domestic investors bought  
stocks on the stronger rupiah. The JSX Composite Index ended up 
20.381 points at 581.746. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares rose despite investors cashing in on recent  
gains. The Composite Index rose 2.36 points, or 0.30 percent, to 
758.44. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares rallied on foreign buying of selected shares. The  
PSE Index rose 54.11 points, or 2.6 percent, at 2,159.20. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Blue chips rose steadily. The STI rose 21.14 points,  
or 1 percent, to 2,070.02. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares were slightly higher amid optimism on certain  
listed companies. The All Ordinaries Index rose 1.1 points, or 0.03 
percent, to 3,027.1. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Shares rose slightly on a stronger yen and foreign  
buying. The Kospi rose 2.24 points, or 0.25 percent, to 871.18. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Shares fell on Wall Street's overnight losses. The  
Weighted Price Index dropped 29.04 points, or 0.36 percent, to 
7,964.67. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares fell on losses from Telecom Corp. of New  
Zealand. The NZSE-40 index fell 16.49 points, or 0.70 percent, at 
2181.56. 


  	   	
</P>
