<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemieux, Penguins Closer to a Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Mario Lemieux moved a step closer to owning  
the Pittsburgh Penguins when a county commissioner said Thursday he 
was satisfied with a financing plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Bob Cranmer had complained that a deal between  
Allegheny County and Lemieux's group to pay off debts associated 
with improvements at the Civic Arena had been negotiated by staff 
without the approval of elected leaders or the county budget 
director. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Cranmer said he was satisfied with a revised plan  
that shifts a portion of the debt from the county's general fund -- 
which is paid for by local property taxes -- to the county's 
Regional Asset District fund. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, the district board voted to spend part of a special  
1-cent sales tax on repaying bonds sold to pay for arena 
improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins' Hall of Famer is expected to finalize his deal to  
buy the team in the near future, perhaps as early as next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``This in our minds was certainly the final, final step that had  
to be completed. At least it appears that way now,'' said John 
Brabender, a spokesman for Lemieux. 
</P>
<P>
	Cranmer's satisfaction with the revised deal ensures two votes  
on the three-member board of commissioners to approve the 
financing. Pittsburgh's City Council also is expected to endorse 
the new formula. 
</P>
<P>
	Both governments should vote on the revised plan in the next two  
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	But what troubled Cranmer was the question of who should repay  
more than $12 million borrowed for improvements that include luxury 
seating, a fancy scoreboard and lounges at the Civic Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins also want to replace the 38-year-old Civic Arena,  
the oldest in use by the National Hockey League. 
</P>
<P>
	But the revised deal explicitly does not commit local  
governments to pay for a new arena by 2002, a revision Cranmer 
insisted on, saying language in the previous deal was ambiguous. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial details of the new deal include the Regional Asset  
District agreeing to relieve the county and city of $10.7 million 
in debt payments, starting in 2007 and continuing through 2018. 
</P>
<P>
	The city and county still will pay an extra $6 million in the  
next 10 years to help bail out the Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	The team will pay $200,000 in cash toward the debt by December  
2000 and an additional $800,000 if the Penguins make at least $1 
million in profit in the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
	SMG, which leases the Civic Arena and subleases it to the  
Penguins, agreed to pay $175,000 a year for the next five years to 
help retire the debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
