<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Names White House Counsel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A lawyer whose nomination for a top Justice  
Department job is on hold in the Senate will instead become 
President Clinton's new lead lawyer, the White House said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Beth Nolan will succeed Charles F.C. Ruff as White House counsel  
next month, the White House said. The appointment marks the first 
time a woman has held the job. 
</P>
<P>
	The position is also a return to the White House for Ms. Nolan.  
She was an ethics adviser in the White House counsel's office 
during Clinton's first term. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has a distinguished record of public service both in the  
White House and at the Department of Justice,'' a statement from 
Clinton said. ``While Chuck Ruff is a tough act to follow, I know 
of no one better than Beth to succeed him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Nolan, 47, is a senior Justice Department lawyer. Her boss,  
Attorney General Janet Reno, called her ``perfectly suited'' for 
the new job. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Clinton nominated Ms. Nolan to run the Justice  
Department Office of Legal Counsel, where she now works as a deputy 
assistant attorney general. The Senate has not acted on her 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a tough time for her because she's been on hold, so  
to speak,'' said Theodore Olson, a Washington lawyer who was Ms. 
Nolan's boss at the Justice Department during her first stint there 
from 1981-1985. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel very good for her that this has had a happy  
conclusion,'' Olson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Nolan also taught constitutional law, legal ethics and other  
subjects at George Washington University's law school between 
stints of government service. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruff, who led Clinton's defense during impeachment proceedings  
in Congress, has already left his post. Clinton's first choice to 
succeed Ruff, acting counsel Cheryl Mills, declined the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Mills would have been both the first woman and first black to  
serve as the president's chief lawyer. She has worked for Clinton 
since the start of his presidency, and became a central player on 
the legal team that defended him and Hillary Rodham Clinton during 
the many investigations of the last few years -- from Whitewater and 
fund raising to the Monica Lewinsky affair. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
