<HEADLINE> Gay Lawmaker Discusses Bush's Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Texas' only openly gay state legislator  
lawmaker said Thursday that Gov. George W. Bush told him in April 
he shouldn't take personally Bush's public remarks about gay 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Bush, now the leading GOP presidential  
candidate, denied that the governor made the comment. 
</P>
<P>
	State Rep. Glen Maxey, an Austin Democrat, said Bush -- on an  
April 14 visit to the Texas House chamber -- congratulated the 
Democratic lawmaker on winning a bigger expansion of a children's 
health insurance program than the governor wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, Maxey said, ``He put his hands on my shoulders and he  
pulled me in close. We were nose to nose. ... He says to me 'Glen, 
I value you as a person. I value you as a human being. And I want 
you to know that what I say publicly about gay people does not 
pertain to you personally.''' 
</P>
<P>
	``And of course, my rejoinder to that was when you say a gay  
person is not fit to be a parent, you're talking about me,'' Maxey 
said. He said Bush then moved on to greet a nearby lawmaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has said he opposes allowing gay couples to adopt, saying,  
``I believe children ought to be adopted in families with a woman 
and a man who are married.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush campaign spokesman Scott McClellan denied the governor made  
the comments as recounted by Maxey. 
</P>
<P>
	``The governor simply congratulated him on the Children's Health  
Insurance Program. That was the extent of the conversation,'' 
McClellan said. ``It's baffling if he (Maxey) was offended by 
something that supposedly happened four months ago that he's just 
now bringing it up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maxey said he cited the encounter after being asked on Wednesday  
by a reporter for the Houston Chronicle about the governor's stand 
on gay issues. The Chronicle reported the story Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	State Rep. Dawnna Dukes, D-Austin, said Maxey had recounted the  
conversation to her immediately after he and Bush had spoken. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Dukes said of the governor's remarks, ``I think in this  
particular case, when he saw Glen Maxey, he felt bad about his 
public statements. I think in a way this was his apology. It just 
kind of got messed up.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
