<HEADLINE> Weather Pushes Grains, Soybeans Up / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures rocketed higher Thursday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade after overnight rains missed bone-dry Midwest 
growing regions. Wheat also gained, while corn retreated. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybeans led the gains after rainfall of up to an inch fell  
in Minnesota, Iowa and parts of Illinois, but missed fields that have 
languished for weeks under hot, dry conditions. Forecasters says those 
same fields likely will remain dry over the next week, which will increase 
the potential for lower yields. 
</P>
<P>
        Farm tours are finding that average yields for corn and soybeans  
are slipping as the dry weather prevents maturing crops from filling 
properly. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat futures also were supported by strong weekly export sales.  
The U.S. Agriculture Department reported that net export sales totaled 
566,800 metric tons, which was slightly higher than market expectations. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for December delivery rose 1 3/4 cents to $2.89 1/2 a  
bushel; December corn fell 1 3/4 cents to $2.26 1/4 a bushel; December 
oats fell 1/2 cent to $1.14 a bushel; November soybeans rose 1/4 cents 
to $4.77 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Beef futures were mostly higher on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while pork futures were mostly lower. 
</P>
<P>
        October live cattle fell .15 cent to 65.65 cents a pound; October  
feeder cattle rose .20 cent to 78.17 cents a pound; October lean hogs 
rose .80 cent to 43.20 cents a pound; February pork bellies fell 1. 
92 cents to 54.15 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
