<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Todd Stottlemyre Set To Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Three months ago, Todd Stottlemyre tore his right  
rotator cuff, an injury that almost always means surgery, a year or 
more of rehabilitation and maybe the end of a pitcher's career. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Friday night, Stottlemyre will be on the mound as Arizona's  
starter in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	The cuff is still torn. The right-hander refused surgery and  
opted for an intense strengthening program instead. Team doctor 
David Zeman calls the quick comeback a miracle. Stottlemyre calls 
it a gift. But both of them know that his next pitch could be his 
last. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tell him he may pitch one pitch and that will be it, or he  
may pitch the next five years,'' Zeman said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the back of his mind, between innings, between starts,  
Stottlemyre admits he wonders when or if the injury will reoccur. 
But he expects to block all that out when he's on the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel like I'm taking the mound with any diabilities or  
that I'm somehow not able to pitch,'' he said. ``I have no fear of 
letting go with that first pitch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stottlemyre said he'll just cherish every trip to the mound from  
now on. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every start is a new gift,'' he said, ``to be able to put on a  
major league uniform and go out and compete at this level. That's 
all I want to do, to compete and be able to pitch the way I did 
before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For 12 seasons, Stottlemyre has been one of baseball's most  
competitive players. So when he felt the pain in his arm while 
pitching in San Francisco on May 17, and exams showed that the main 
muscle in his rotator cuff was 70 percent torn, he weighed the 
options and surgery did not seem like a good one. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 34 years old. He had just signed a four-year, $32 million  
contract with the Diamondbacks and the team was hoping to make a 
run at the NL West title. The same injury had ended the standout 
career of his father, Mel. He watched his brother, Mel Jr., undergo 
five surgeries on his shoulder and knee and never be able to 
compete again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I played with Andy Benes' brother, Alan, in St. Louis. He had  
surgery in 1997 and he hasn't pitched yet,'' Stottlemyre said. ``I 
just didn't feel that at age 34, having surgery and coming back in 
two years and maybe being able to pitch was much of an option.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides, if this doesn't work, surgery can still be done.  
</P>
<P>
	For a month, he couldn't throw at all. Then he could play a  
light game of catch. Through it all, he worked out every day on 
weights and on the stationary bicycle. He took only one day off in 
just over three months. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he's done is kind of overcompensate by strengthening the  
rest of his rotator cuff, all the muscles that stabilize his 
shoulder blade, his back, his abdomen,'' Dr. Zeman said. ``So he's 
using his whole body to pitch now, whereas by his own admission he 
was pretty much just forcing it before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stottlemyre's dad, now the pitching coach for the New York  
Yankees, encouraged him from the start. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I first got injured, he said, `One thing about it is it  
will take a lot of hard work, and you like to work,' '' Stottlemyre 
said. '' `You're going to enjoy finding a way to beat this thing,' 
and that's how I've taken it. It's a challenge and somehow with the 
help of the trainers and my family, we'll find a way to beat it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stottlemyre slowly worked his way up to pitching hard, first in  
a few simulated games, then in three increasingly longer starts for 
the Diamondbacks team in the Arizona Rookie League. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Buck Showalter said he believes Stottlemyre won't show  
any hesitation on the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	``He will rear back and fire,'' Showalter said.  
</P>
<P>
	When Stottlemyre takes the mound at Three Rivers Stadium, he  
said will try to simply concentrate on doing his job. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want to be able to go out there with a game plan,'' he  
said. ``Try to leave all the emotions of the last three months and 
what it means to me personally on that day, push it aside and just 
go pitch.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
