<HEADLINE> European Shares Continue Downward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European shares continued to sag Thursday,  
influenced by the slide in U.S. stocks on the back of a 
wider-than-expected trade deficit for June. 
</P>
<P>
	Worst hit were resources and energy stocks, but technology  
shares also were hurt by weakness in the Nasdaq Composite index. 
The Dow Jones Stoxx basic resources index was down 1.5 percent, the 
energy index closed 1.8 percent lower and the technology index was 
off 1.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In Paris, shares of Alcatel-Alsthom closed down 3.10 euros at  
139.80 euros, while Nokia in Helsinki dropped 4.1 percent to 78.80 
euros. That caused the Finnish stock market to fall 3.3 percent, 
the biggest decline in the European bourses. 
</P>
<P>
	Total and Elf-Aquitaine were among the biggest losers on the  
French market. 
</P>
<P>
	A record trade deficit for June in the United States sent bond  
yields rising and hurt the dollar, causing the Dow Jones Industrial 
Average index to lose more than 100 points at the open. At 1600 
GMT, the Dow was down 90.86 points at 10,900.83. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies closed down  
3.25 points, or 1.1 percent, at 302.94, while the Dow Jones Euro 
Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies in countries that joined 
the single currency, was down 3.76 points at 316.10. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index was down 59.35 points at  
3,679.48 points, while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index was down 47.47 points 
at 3,637.23. 
</P>
<P>
	In domestic markets, Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index was down 0.8  
percent. The Paris CAC-40 index was 1.5 percent lower, Milan's 
MIBtel index fell 0.8 percent and Amsterdam's AEX Index fell 1.7 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	London's FTSE 100 index of blue-chip shares was down 83.8  
points, or 1.4 percent, at 6,118. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
