<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CART Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CICERO, Ill. (AP) -- Don't call Jimmy Vasser racing's forgotten  
man, at least not in front of team owner Chip Ganassi. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a bunch of bull; he's not the forgotten man,'' Ganassi  
said Thursday while watching the former CART champion circle 
Ganassi's new track in suburban Chicago. ``He just had a great 
finish last week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vasser, who gave Ganassi the first of three consecutive  
championships as a team owner in 1996, finished a hard-closing 
fourth at Mid-Ohio Sports Car Course last Sunday. Nonetheless, 
Vasser took a back seat to rookie teammate Juan Montoya, who scored 
his fifth victory of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he's scored four victories since his breakthrough year  
in '96, Vasser has sometimes seemed an afterthought in light of his 
teammates' sensational performances. 
</P>
<P>
	Alex Zanardi won consecutive championships before leaving this  
season for Formula 1. Now there's Montoya, bidding to give Ganassi 
a fourth straight title. 
</P>
<P>
	Vasser doesn't object to being called forgotten, but doesn't  
agree with it, either. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm perfectly secure with my accomplishments and my talents  
and who I am,'' said Vasser, who has no victories and is 10th in 
the driver standings. ``We're not satisfied with where we are. 
We've made some mistakes that have cost us points and race wins. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's never just the driver. I'm on a great race team and I'd  
like to think I had something to do with building it. It wasn't 
like that when I came here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He's still one of the more solid guys out here,'' Ganassi  
said. ``You're not scraping him off the wall all the time. He's the 
consummate professional.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides his car owner's endorsement, Vasser has the security of  
being in the first year of a three-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``You still look over your shoulder,'' he said. ``You can never  
relax. You're judged by your last race.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BUSY MAN:* Ganassi has more on his mind this weekend than  
defending his driver. As president of the new track, ``it's been 
very difficult,'' he said. ``I've got a lot of running around to 
do. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to make sure my peer group is taken care of. I've got  
to see to it that new fans are exposed to racing in the right way. 
There are a lot of high-level people who will be here -- and I'm 
trying to win a championship on top of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow team owner Carl Haas can sympathize, because Haas can  
remember the first year he took over the Milwaukee Mile as 
promoter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kind of got it separated,'' Haas said. ``I had people  
responsible for the daily running of the track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Haas presented his first race at Milwaukee in 1993, he was  
a double winner. Not only were the stands full, but his driver, 
Nigel Mansell, won the race. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MORE MEARS:* Look for a familiar name to pop up next season,  
either behind the wheel of an Indy car or at the Indianapolis 500 -- 
or both. 
</P>
<P>
	Casey Mears, son of off-road specialist Roger Mears and nephew  
of four-time Indy 500 winner Rick Mears, is poised to move up to 
the big time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's ready,'' says Uncle Rick, who is closely  
following Casey's career in the steppingstone Indy Lights series. 
``I think he's the only driver who's finished every lap of every 
race. Now he needs to get a win under his belt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even without that first taste of victory, Casey Mears is tied  
for second in the series, behind teammate Oriol Servia of Spain. 
``I want to move up and on,'' Casey Mears said. ``I've been in Indy 
Lights for three seasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first two years were under the aegis of the Mears brothers,  
with Rick's son, Clint, in a second car. A lack of sponsorship 
forced the brothers to merge the operation with Dorricott Racing. 
Clint is now teaching at a driving school in California, awaiting 
another opportunity. 
</P>
<P>
	Casey is just waiting to move up. The big question is where.  
</P>
<P>
	Clearly, he'd prefer to run both for the CART championship and  
the Indy 500, but a ride in the rival Indy Racing League -- an 
all-oval circuit -- remains an option. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been scoring better on ovals,'' Rick Mears said, ``but  
he's quick on both.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DREAM TEAM:* Imagine Michael Andretti and Al Unser Jr., the two  
winningest drivers in CART's 21-year history, sons of racing stars 
and stars in their own right, driving for the same team. 
</P>
<P>
	Little Al's willing, Michael's willing, but the only man who  
currently could make it happen says it's not possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Unser is looking for a new ride next season after losing his  
seat with Roger Penske. 
</P>
<P>
	``That'd be super,'' Unser said when asked how he'd like to pair  
with Andretti. ``It would bring back old memories.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was referring to the fact that his father, Al Unser, and  
Michael's father, Mario Andretti, once were part of a three-man 
race team in the early 1970s. ``That was the first super team,'' Al 
Jr. recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	An Unser-Andretti pairing would be a marketer's dream, but  
Michael is under contract to the Newman-Haas team, which also has 
Christian Fittipaldi. ``I'm assuming they're happy with him 
(Fittipaldi),'' Unser said. ``He's won a race and been very 
competitive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd love to have Al on the team,'' Michael said. ``It'd be  
great. I'm all for it if you could work it out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's the rub.  
</P>
<P>
	Team owner Carl Haas would have to field a third car were he to  
sign Unser and ``that would be impossible for me,'' Haas says. 
``I've got my drivers for 2000 and a three-car team is not 
possible. It's hard enough to try to do it with two.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even if he could come up with the necessary sponsorship money,  
``it's not the money,'' Haas says. ``It's just the logistics. It's 
so competitive these days. I don't want to take on that big a 
task.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
