<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Is Bush Eyeing Dole and Her Support? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The congratulatory fax to Elizabeth Dole came  
from an old pal who happens to be a top official in rival George W. 
Bush's campaign. A sign, her husband said, that Dole has something 
Bush needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Women voters.  
</P>
<P>
	The private overture from former Republican Party chairman Haley  
Barbour, now co-chairman of Bush's effort, can't help but fuel 
whispers -- from within Dole's own camp, even -- that if Dole can't 
beat Bush's formidable bankroll and poll numbers in the race for 
the GOP presidential nomination, she might increasingly count on 
joining him. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have to keep looking at each other,'' former Sen. Bob  
Dole, her husband, said Thursday. But it's president, not vice 
president that she's running for, he added. ``She's not trying to 
do anything else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``She has this inherent strength that's so good for the party,  
so good for everyone who's involved in Campaign 2000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Dole should know. The GOP's traditional -- and  
ever-more-gaping -- deficit to Democrats when it comes to women 
voters helped lead to his presidential defeat in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Barbour wrote Dole after she placed a strong third behind Bush  
and Steve Forbes in the Ames, Iowa, straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ames is a vivid reminder that there is a huge appetite out  
there for Elizabeth Dole's candidacy,'' Barbour told The Associated 
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Discussing Barbour's gesture, the former senator said: ``He  
knows where we've needed muscle in the party. We've got some pretty 
scary people out there when it comes to what women see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After a dismal spring of organizational disarray and sinking  
poll numbers, aides said Dole had earned a new lease on political 
life. On a West Coast fund-raising swing, Dole said her strategy 
for making the most of this second chance is ``Just keep moving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She promised to roll out the ideas on crime, drugs, taxes and  
education to prove herself more qualified than Bush, the Texas 
governor, to head the GOP ticket in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Some in her circle of Washington staff and advisers, with an eye  
on Bush's lead, said privately that if Dole can keep the momentum 
going into the winter primaries, she cements herself a fallback 
position by forcing Bush to make her his running mate. 
</P>
<P>
	Her strong appeal among women already makes her a must-have on  
any Republican ticket hoping to overcome the GOP's gender gap. 
</P>
<P>
	Another top Bush operative, speaking on condition of anonymity,  
flipped the Dole team's postulate inside out, saying that if Dole 
now does poorly in the primaries, she loses any chance of joining a 
Bush ticket. She would have a more guaranteed shot, this person 
said, had she stayed out of the race, keeping her mystique and 
celebrity unblemished. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole's press secretary, Ari Fleischer, called the talk of No. 2  
``inevitable chitchat in political circles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, the better she does, the more the chitchat will  
grow. But she's running for one position and one position only, and 
she's running to win,'' Fleischer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole herself seems to strain to keep the competition with Bush  
congenial, feeding theories that she's carefully avoiding burned 
bridges. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing personal,'' she said, painting herself as a workhorse  
candidate keeping her head down. When arguing her point that Bush 
is less qualified than she for the White House, Dole gently poked 
at him not by name but as ``one other candidate I can think of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were traces of resentment over Bush's whopping lead and  
his ``gobs of money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To capitalize on any post-Ames momentum, Dole is rushing out two  
fund-raising appeals this week that boast of her Iowa showing and 
ask for the money to keep going. Her campaign, which was focused 
almost exclusively on Iowa, is now scrambling to organize for New 
Hampshire's leadoff primary. 
</P>
<P>
	A back-to-school swing will, she hopes, win a spotlight on her  
plan for school safety and discipline. An anti-drug policy is due 
to follow. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll draw a very, very clear line in the sand ... and force,  
if we can, a discussion with George W. Bush. If he chooses to 
remain silent, he gives Mrs. Dole a wide open field,'' strategist 
Tony Fabrizio said. 
</P>
<P>
	She is moving up -- from October to mid September -- a kickoff  
from her hometown of Salisbury, N.C. And she looked ahead to a 
dizzy pace of 25 fund-raisers in the next 45 days. 
</P>
<P>
	One Republican strategist close to her campaign said that when  
the next finance reports are filed Sept. 30 she'll need to bring 
her fund-raising tally to at least $5 million to remain a credible 
contender. 
</P>
<P>
	She raised $3.5 million in the first six months of this year.  
</P>
<P>
	Senator Dole said he was working the phones to raise money and  
to convert workers from the now-defunct Lamar Alexander campaign. 
Already, 10 of Alexander's Iowa organizers enlisted with Dole this 
week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
