<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Family Sought by Coast Guard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Coast Guard and its Canadian counterpart  
are searching for a family of four that disappeared off the East 
Coast while sailing from Florida to the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Stewart, Debbie Stewart and their children, Chad, 16,  
and Mischa, 12, of Ludlow Falls, Ohio, last spoke to their 
relatives around July 25 from Newport, R.I., according to Coast 
Guard Cmdr. Jim McPherson. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators say the family's credit cards were last used on  
July 26 in Newport. Their cellular phone was last activated on Aug. 
3 near Piscataway, N.J., located about 20 miles inland from the 
entrance to the Hudson River. 
</P>
<P>
	In the more than two weeks since, there has been no contact with  
the Stewarts. The Coast Guard has been unable to locate them 
despite an aerial search along the East Coast and calls to marinas 
along the New England coast, the Hudson River Valley and the St. 
Lawrence Seaway, which parallels the U.S.-Canadian border. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have basically vanished,'' said McPherson, speaking from  
Coast Guard headquarters in Washington. ``We have no reports of 
finding life jackets or life rings or (signals from) emergency 
beacons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Searchers have investigated the possibilities of a hoax and that  
the family is simply overdue, but the time that has passed and the 
lack of contact with relatives have raised concerns. Richard 
Stewart is described as an inexperienced sailor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had situations where we've had single-hand sailors  
change their itinerary and not tell anybody, but it's seldom that 
you have an entire family disappear,'' McPherson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The family was aboard a 65-foot sailboat, the ``Jolly Joyce.''  
The ketch is cream-colored with two white sails and carries a gray 
10-foot dinghy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dayton (Ohio) Daily News reported today that the family had  
been living on the boat in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., since buying it 
in January. Chad and Mischa are home-schooled, according to their 
older sister, Beth Stewart. She told the newspaper she stayed 
behind in Ludlow Falls, near Dayton, to run the family's two video 
rental stores. The family home is also up for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Coast Guard officials said the Stewarts intended to sail north  
along the coast to the St. Lawrence Seaway and then to the Great 
Lakes. The ultimate destination was the Michigan home of Debbie 
Stewart's parents, Beth Stewart told the Daily News. 
</P>
<P>
	En route, one of the boat's two engines died near Newport and  
the other started faltering, so the family docked there and sought 
repairs, said Coast Guard Petty Officer Al Bennett, based at 
Atlantic Area Headquarters in Portsmouth, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stewarts had problems finding parts, however, because the  
boat was nearly 30 years old. Bennett said a family friend located 
some parts in Louisiana and intended to install them in Fort 
Lauderdale, but the Stewarts never returned, Bennett said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone in Newport overheard them saying they might keep going  
(to the Great Lakes), but we're not sure,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the family initially decided against using the Hudson  
River because they would have had to take down the sailboat's mast 
upon reaching the Erie Canal, the Coast Guard has searched and 
called marinas throughout New York because of the nearby cell phone 
use. The phone was turned on but no call completed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadians are also searching off Nova Scotia and along the  
St. Lawrence River on the assumption the Stewarts could have 
continued north. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know which way they went and our search area is  
literally the Atlantic Ocean and the Hudson River,'' said 
McPherson. ``What we're hoping is somebody gives us a better search 
area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He asked anyone with information about the Jolly Joyce or the  
Stewart family to call the local Coast Guard station. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
