<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DiMaggio No. 22 on ESPN's List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ESPN's countdown of the greatest athletes of the  
century reaches No. 22 with Joe DiMaggio on Friday night and the 
presentation includes rare footage of the Hall of Famer singing. 
</P>
<P>
	In a cameo, DiMaggio managed to get through one line -- ``Have  
you ever been in heaven?'' -- when his off-key effort was 
interrupted by an actor playing an outraged listener. DiMaggio 
shrugged off the complaint saying, ``I'm a center fielder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ESPN tribute to him included interviews with former New York  
Yankees teammates Phil Rizzuto, Jerry Coleman and Yogi Berra. 
</P>
<P>
	There was extensive coverage of the catch by Brooklyn's Al  
Gionfriddo's against the bullpen fence in the 1947 World Series 
that robbed DiMaggio of a triple and left the Yankees slugger 
kicking the basepath dirt in disgust, one of his very rare displays 
of emotion. 
</P>
<P>
	Coleman recalled DiMaggio's great pride and how it was shaken  
once near the end of his career by manager Casey Stengel. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was hitting fifth,'' Coleman said of the Yankees longtime  
cleanup batter. ``Joe never hit fifth. I don't think he ever 
forgave him for that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then, there was the scouting report near the end of DiMaggio's  
career that recommended throwing fastballs inside. ``He can't get 
around on it anymore,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	A year later, DiMaggio left baseball as one of its most heroic  
figures and married film star Marilyn Monroe. Much of the ESPN 
treatment deals with their stormy nine-month relationship including 
the famous exchange when Marilyn returned from a trip to entertain 
American troops overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh, Joe,'' she gushed, ``you never heard such cheering.''  
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, I did,'' the taciturn slugger replied.  
</P>
<P>
	Even after their divorce, DiMaggio remained loyal to his  
ex-wife, rushing to her side in troubled times. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe's brother, Dominic, who played center field for the Boston  
Red Sox, spoke warmly of DiMaggio, who died March 8 at 84. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was always the perfect gentleman,'' he said. ``He did  
everything with style, on the field and off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Hall of Famer Ted Williams remembered the grace with which  
his longtime rival played the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``He did it so easy and made it look so good -- going for a ball,  
hitting a ball, throwing a ball,'' Williams said. ``He never looked 
bad. I never saw him look bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio is the fourth baseball player on the ESPN list,  
following Sandy Koufax, No. 42; Mickey Mantle, No. 37; and Lou 
Gehrig, No 34. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
