<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bomber Testifies About 1963 Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- Two white supremacist leaders during a  
period of Ku Klux Klan violence went before a federal grand jury 
investigating the 1963 bombing of the Sixteenth Street Baptist 
Church that killed four black girls. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Shelton, former head of the United Klans of America,  
entered the federal building today for his appearance and declined 
to comment as he walked past reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the first to testify was J.B. Stoner, who was  
convicted in 1980 for an earlier bombing of a black church, a 
nonfatal 1958 blast at Birmingham's Bethel Baptist Church. He 
served most of his 3 1/2 years in prison with Robert Chambliss -- the 
only man convicted so far for the deaths of four little black girls 
in the Sept. 15, 1963, explosion at Sixteenth Street Baptist. 
</P>
<P>
	The Birmingham News reported today that Stoner said he was not  
questioned about the time he spent in jail with Chambliss and was 
not surprised by any questions. But he would not discuss the 
specifics of his grand jury testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal investigation at the time of the Sixteenth Street  
bombing resulted in no charges. Former Attorney General Bill Baxley 
led an investigation in the 1970s that resulted in the murder 
conviction for Chambliss. The investigation was reopened yet again 
in 1997, with federal agents saying there was new information. 
</P>
<P>
	Stoner, 75, and Chambliss shared a cell separated from other  
inmates, who had threatened them, Stoner said. Chambliss died in 
prison in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prison had gotten the best of him and he didn't have his wits  
about him,'' Stoner told the News. ``But he prayed every night to 
say he was innocent and to ask God to punish Bill Baxley.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also testifying Wednesday was Wayne Monk, who was married in the  
early 1970s to the daughter of bombing suspect Bobby Frank Cherry. 
He said he testified about rumors that he heard while he was a part 
of the family. He said he had heard ``hearsay'' about Cherry. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't remember where I got my stories from,'' Monk said. ``I  
just heard tales. I don't know if he (Cherry) was guilty or if he 
was just bragging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least three other people reportedly have told the grand jury  
that Cherry, 69, had boasted of being involved in the 1963 bombing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
