<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Midwest Town Faces Flood Dilemma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLEPORT, Iowa (AP) -- He's been burned out and flooded out of  
his home, but John Zapf says he won't be bought out. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government has approved more than $1 million to buy  
homes and businesses flooded last May by the Volga River and Honey 
Creek in eastern Iowa. Zapf, born here 43 years ago, is among those 
who aren't interested. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just used to it here,'' Zapf said Thursday from his mobile  
home a stone's throw from the Volga. 
</P>
<P>
	This hamlet of 67 people was under water last spring. All but 23  
people have since moved out and the Littleport City Council faces a 
big decision: whether to allow the community to become 
unincorporated. 
</P>
<P>
	State officials say 32 homes, about 90 percent of the community,  
are in a flood plain and eligible for the voluntary buyout offered 
by the Federal Emergency Management Agency, or FEMA. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the ``risk reduction program'' the government would buyout  
the homeowners to move them out of the flood plain to prevent 
property damage or injuries. The agency wants to create either an 
open space or recreational wetland in Littleport, nestled in a 
valley off a county road some 50 miles northwest of Dubuque. 
</P>
<P>
	Other towns have faced similar circumstances. After Midwest  
flooding in 1993, the Missouri towns of Pattonsburg and Rhineland, 
along with Valmeyer, Ill., agreed to relocate out of flood plains. 
Over the years, other small communities have essentially 
disappeared after the government bought out residents and 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	And Littleport isn't alone. Mayor Al Pritchard said FEMA buyout  
offers are being made to hundreds of homeowners in Independence, 
Cedar Falls and Dunkerton affected by flooding this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know, I just don't know what we'll do until we get  
more information,'' Pritchard said. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor himself has moved. He once owned a Littleport tavern  
called Al's -- famous for its giant hamburgers -- but now calls 
nearby Edgewood home. 
</P>
<P>
	It was May 16 and 17 when the Volga, fed by drenching rains,  
spilled over its banks in what many considered a 500-year flood -- 
so rare it happens once every 500 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Not much was spared. The bank and post office, which shared the  
same building near the river, are both closed. The community has 
more or less become a ghost town. 
</P>
<P>
	Clusters of houses sit deserted, overrun with ankle-deep mud,  
weeds and debris. In all of them, windows are broken -- not by 
vandals, but from furniture that floated high enough to crash 
through the windows. 
</P>
<P>
	``I managed to save a glider rocker and a few antique pieces  
that I had put enough varnish on that they withstood water 
damage,'' said Gary Stewart, whose two-story white house took on 7 
feet of water. Eight inches of dried mud was left caked on his 
floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Someone had shoveled a path from just inside the front door and  
into the main floor -- but that was before warning notices, affixed 
with duct tape, were hung by the front door. 
</P>
<P>
	The placards, declaring the buildings structurally unsound,  
warn: ``Entry may result in death or injury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	FEMA and the state are providing more than $1.1 million in grant  
money to move people out of the flood plain, said Dennis Harper of 
the Iowa Emergency Management Division. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents in Littleport are awaiting appraisals of their  
properties, though Harper said $30,000 ``is a pretty fair 
assessment across the board.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zapf had his flood-damaged mobile home removed and is living in  
another one parked in the same spot. He said he doubts he'd be paid 
enough to move. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his brother, Dan, who lives across the street in the  
house that their grandparents and parents lived in, also is 
staying. 
</P>
<P>
	Not Stewart.  
</P>
<P>
	``The Volga, it done a number. I'm moving to Elkader, even  
though it's not very pleasant to have to start over,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Pritchard, who estimates Littleport is 140 to 150 years  
old, isn't sure how much longer it will remain a town. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a farming community, just a little place where  
everybody helped everybody. Everyone was always pretty much 
together on things,'' he said. ``It's sad to go back down there. 
The wife doesn't even want to go down there after what happened.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
