<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TotalFina May Sweeten Elf Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The chairman of the Franco-Belgian oil giant  
TotalFina said Thursday his company's takeover bid for rival Elf 
Aquitaine might be sweetened a bit, but not by much. 
</P>
<P>
	Thierry Desmarest said any new TotalFina bid will show only ``a  
limited increase'' on the company's original offer for ELF in an 
effort to create the world's fourth largest oil company. 
</P>
<P>
	TotalFina launched a $43 billion hostile bid for Elf in early  
July. Several weeks later Elf made a $51 billion counterbid, and 
the two companies have been embroiled in a war to win over 
shareholders ever since. 
</P>
<P>
	The messy battle is the latest example of the radical shakeup  
now underway in European business where the need for consolidation 
is paramount in a new era of global competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Banque Nationale de Paris has been trying to take over rival  
banks Paribas and Societe Generale to create the world's largest 
bank -- with assets of more than $1 trillion. But it has gained only 
a third of Societe Generale shares and 31.5 percent of its voting 
rights. French regulators is expected to step in and broker a 
compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made a fair offer which was around 20 percent above the  
market price,'' Desmarest told a news conference. ``At that level, 
Elf shareholders get the majority of the synergy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Desmarest stressed that TotalFina would only consider making a  
sweetened offer if Elf demonstrated it was open to friendly merger 
talks, which would speed up the merger and increase value. 
</P>
<P>
	A French appeals court Wednesday ruled that TotalFina can  
continue its bid. The court decided not to suspend TotalFina's bid 
pending a case scheduled for Oct. 11 that was brought by Elf 
contending that French stock market regulators should have 
disallowed TotalFina's takeover bid on technical grounds. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
