<DOCNO> APW19990819.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 20:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> International Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CASTLE ROCK, Colo. (AP) -- Steve Elkington's mind was at ease  
when he played the International on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Elkington endured a scary medical emergency with his caddy, Joe  
``Gypsy'' Grillo, at last week's PGA championship. About an hour 
before Elkington's scheduled tee time in the first round of the PGA 
last Thursday, Grillo, 48, experienced tightness in his chest, 
couldn't feel his arm and was having difficulty breathing. 
</P>
<P>
	It was feared he had suffered a heart attack, and he was taken  
to a Chicago hospital. Elkington immediately withdrew from the 
tournament and accompanied Grillo to the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The diagnosis wasn't as dire.  
</P>
<P>
	``He had an asthmatic seizure,'' Elkington said Thursday. ``He  
passed all the stress tests. His heart is fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gypsy is family. He's a real close friend of mine. I thought  
he was going to die. He wasn't breathing. He was in a lot of 
distress. I thought it was real important to be there with him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was so shook up I probably couldn't have made a  
two-footer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although the crisis is past, Elkington's bag is being lugged  
this week by Jimmy Johnson, a friend from Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jimmy caddies for me on and off,'' Elkington said. ``He's  
pinch-hitting this week. Gypsy doesn't caddy for me here normally 
anyway because of his asthma.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PICKY NICKY:* Call Nick Price a traditionalist.  
</P>
<P>
	While the majority of his colleagues love the International  
format, a modified Stableford scoring system that rewards birdies 
more than it penalizes bogeys, Price isn't sold. 
</P>
<P>
	A birdie is worth plus-2 points, while a bogey counts minus-1.  
Thus a player in this tournament who fires four birdies and four 
bogeys has 4 points, as opposed to being even par under the 
standard stroke-play format. Other players say they like the break 
in the routine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd still prefer it be 72-hole stroke play,'' Price said  
Thursday after scoring 7 points. ``Making a birdie and then making 
a bogey and being 1 point up is not what golf is about, to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Price, however, benefited nicely from the format. He received 5  
points for his eagle on the 17th hole. He stands comfortably on the 
leaderboard, whereas in a standard tournament he would have shot a 
modest 1-under-par. 
</P>
<P>
	Price also took a shot at the Jack Nicklaus-designed course.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's a couple of goofy holes out there I've never liked on  
the golf course,'' he said. ``You have to hit the ball sky high to 
be able to play them, and I'm generally a pretty low-ball striker, 
so I feel I'm at a disadvantage here.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TRIO OF TAP-INS:* Mark O'Meara didn't put much pressure on his  
putting Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Of his six birdie putts, three were from a mere 8 inches away.  
</P>
<P>
	He hit an 8-iron to gimme range on the 11th hole, a 9-iron to  
the same distance on the 15th, and chipped to that distance on the 
par-5 17th. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people can handle those,'' O'Meara told the media. ``Even  
you guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When several reporters shook their heads in jest, he added,  
``OK, maybe not you guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	THIRD AND SHORT:@ David Sutherland made two eagles, on the  
eighth and 14th holes, helping him post a score of 12. ... Perry 
Moss made the best of his good fortune. An alternate, Moss said he 
``found out about 30 minutes before my tee time'' that he was in 
the tournament. He scored 8 points. ... Peter Jacobsen posted 
minus-3 points and subsequently withdrew because of an ankle 
injury. ... Playing the back nine first, Greg Norman scored minus-7 
points on that side, then had plus-7 on the front to finish at 
zero. 
  	   	
</P>
